*   `1 <= k <= n`

title: Subsets
content:
Given an integer array `nums` of **unique** elements, return _all possible_ _subsets_ _(the power set)_._x000D_
_x000D_
The solution set **must not** contain duplicate subsets. Return the solution in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[\],\[1\],\[2\],\[1,2\],\[3\],\[1,3\],\[2,3\],\[1,2,3\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[\],\[0\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 10`_x000D_
*   `-10 <= nums[i] <= 10`_x000D_
*   All the numbers of `nums` are **unique**.

title: Word Search
content:
Given an `m x n` grid of characters `board` and a string `word`, return `true` _if_ `word` _exists in the grid_._x000D_
_x000D_
The word can be constructed from letters of sequentially adjacent cells, where adjacent cells are horizontally or vertically neighboring. The same letter cell may not be used more than once._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** board = \[\[ "A ", "B ", "C ", "E "\],\[ "S ", "F ", "C ", "S "\],\[ "A ", "D ", "E ", "E "\]\], word =  "ABCCED "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** board = \[\[ "A ", "B ", "C ", "E "\],\[ "S ", "F ", "C ", "S "\],\[ "A ", "D ", "E ", "E "\]\], word =  "SEE "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** board = \[\[ "A ", "B ", "C ", "E "\],\[ "S ", "F ", "C ", "S "\],\[ "A ", "D ", "E ", "E "\]\], word =  "ABCB "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == board.length`_x000D_
*   `n = board[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 6`_x000D_
*   `1 <= word.length <= 15`_x000D_
*   `board` and `word` consists of only lowercase and uppercase English letters._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you use search pruning to make your solution faster with a larger `board`?

title: Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array II
content:
Given an integer array `nums` sorted in **non-decreasing order**, remove some duplicates [**in-place**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm) such that each unique element appears **at most twice**. The **relative order** of the elements should be kept the **same**._x000D_
_x000D_
Since it is impossible to change the length of the array in some languages, you must instead have the result be placed in the **first part** of the array `nums`. More formally, if there are `k` elements after removing the duplicates, then the first `k` elements of `nums` should hold the final result. It does not matter what you leave beyond the first `k` elements._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `k` _after placing the final result in the first_ `k` _slots of_ `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
Do **not** allocate extra space for another array. You must do this by **modifying the input array [in-place](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In-place_algorithm)** with O(1) extra memory._x000D_
_x000D_
**Custom Judge:**_x000D_
_x000D_
The judge will test your solution with the following code:_x000D_
_x000D_
int\[\] nums = \[...\]; // Input array_x000D_
int\[\] expectedNums = \[...\]; // The expected answer with correct length_x000D_
_x000D_
int k = removeDuplicates(nums); // Calls your implementation_x000D_
_x000D_
assert k == expectedNums.length;_x000D_
for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {_x000D_
    assert nums\[i\] == expectedNums\[i\];_x000D_
}_x000D_
_x000D_
If all assertions pass, then your solution will be **accepted**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,1,1,2,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5, nums = \[1,1,2,2,3,\_\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Your function should return k = 5, with the first five elements of nums being 1, 1, 2, 2 and 3 respectively._x000D_
It does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0,0,1,1,1,1,2,3,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 7, nums = \[0,0,1,1,2,3,3,\_,\_\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Your function should return k = 7, with the first seven elements of nums being 0, 0, 1, 1, 2, 3 and 3 respectively._x000D_
It does not matter what you leave beyond the returned k (hence they are underscores)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= nums[i] <= 104`_x000D_
*   `nums` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.

title: Search in Rotated Sorted Array II
content:
There is an integer array `nums` sorted in non-decreasing order (not necessarily with **distinct** values)._x000D_
_x000D_
Before being passed to your function, `nums` is **rotated** at an unknown pivot index `k` (`0 <= k < nums.length`) such that the resulting array is `[nums[k], nums[k+1], ..., nums[n-1], nums[0], nums[1], ..., nums[k-1]]` (**0-indexed**). For example, `[0,1,2,4,4,4,5,6,6,7]` might be rotated at pivot index `5` and become `[4,5,6,6,7,0,1,2,4,4]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the array `nums` **after** the rotation and an integer `target`, return `true` _if_ `target` _is in_ `nums`_, or_ `false` _if it is not in_ `nums`_.__x000D_
_x000D_
You must decrease the overall operation steps as much as possible._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,5,6,0,0,1,2\], target = 0_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,5,6,0,0,1,2\], target = 3_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= nums[i] <= 104`_x000D_
*   `nums` is guaranteed to be rotated at some pivot._x000D_
*   `-104 <= target <= 104`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** This problem is similar to Search in Rotated Sorted Array, but `nums` may contain **duplicates**. Would this affect the runtime complexity? How and why?

title: Remove Duplicates from Sorted List II
content:
Given the `head` of a sorted linked list, _delete all nodes that have duplicate numbers, leaving only distinct numbers from the original list_. Return _the linked list **sorted** as well_._x000D_

*   `-100 <= Node.val <= 100`_x000D_

title: Maximal Rectangle
content:

title: Partition List
content:
Given the `head` of a linked list and a value `x`, partition it such that all nodes **less than** `x` come before nodes **greater than or equal** to `x`._x000D_
_x000D_
You should **preserve** the original relative order of the nodes in each of the two partitions._x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,4,3,2,5,2\], x = 3_x000D_

_x000D_

*   `-100 <= Node.val <= 100`_x000D_

title: Scramble String
content:
We can scramble a string s to get a string t using the following algorithm:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  If the length of the string is 1, stop._x000D_
2.  If the length of the string is > 1, do the following:_x000D_
    *   Split the string into two non-empty substrings at a random index, i.e., if the string is `s`, divide it to `x` and `y` where `s = x + y`._x000D_
    *   **Randomly** decide to swap the two substrings or to keep them in the same order. i.e., after this step, `s` may become `s = x + y` or `s = y + x`._x000D_
    *   Apply step 1 recursively on each of the two substrings `x` and `y`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given two strings `s1` and `s2` of **the same length**, return `true` if `s2` is a scrambled string of `s1`, otherwise, return `false`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "great ", s2 =  "rgeat "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** One possible scenario applied on s1 is:_x000D_
 "great " -->  "gr/eat " // divide at random index._x000D_
 "gr/eat " -->  "gr/eat " // random decision is not to swap the two substrings and keep them in order._x000D_
 "gr/eat " -->  "g/r / e/at " // apply the same algorithm recursively on both substrings. divide at random index each of them._x000D_
 "g/r / e/at " -->  "r/g / e/at " // random decision was to swap the first substring and to keep the second substring in the same order._x000D_
 "r/g / e/at " -->  "r/g / e/ a/t " // again apply the algorithm recursively, divide  "at " to  "a/t "._x000D_
 "r/g / e/ a/t " -->  "r/g / e/ a/t " // random decision is to keep both substrings in the same order._x000D_
The algorithm stops now, and the result string is  "rgeat " which is s2._x000D_
As one possible scenario led s1 to be scrambled to s2, we return true._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "abcde ", s2 =  "caebd "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "a ", s2 =  "a "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `s1.length == s2.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= s1.length <= 30`_x000D_
*   `s1` and `s2` consist of lowercase English letters.

title: Merge Sorted Array
content:
You are given two integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2`, sorted in **non-decreasing order**, and two integers `m` and `n`, representing the number of elements in `nums1` and `nums2` respectively._x000D_
_x000D_
**Merge** `nums1` and `nums2` into a single array sorted in **non-decreasing order**._x000D_
_x000D_
The final sorted array should not be returned by the function, but instead be _stored inside the array_ `nums1`. To accommodate this, `nums1` has a length of `m + n`, where the first `m` elements denote the elements that should be merged, and the last `n` elements are set to `0` and should be ignored. `nums2` has a length of `n`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[1,2,3,0,0,0\], m = 3, nums2 = \[2,5,6\], n = 3_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2,2,3,5,6\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The arrays we are merging are \[1,2,3\] and \[2,5,6\]._x000D_
The result of the merge is \[1,2,2,3,5,6\] with the underlined elements coming from nums1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[1\], m = 1, nums2 = \[\], n = 0_x000D_
**Output:** \[1\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The arrays we are merging are \[1\] and \[\]._x000D_
The result of the merge is \[1\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[0\], m = 0, nums2 = \[1\], n = 1_x000D_
**Output:** \[1\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The arrays we are merging are \[\] and \[1\]._x000D_
The result of the merge is \[1\]._x000D_
Note that because m = 0, there are no elements in nums1. The 0 is only there to ensure the merge result can fit in nums1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `nums1.length == m + n`_x000D_
*   `nums2.length == n`_x000D_
*   `0 <= m, n <= 200`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m + n <= 200`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= nums1[i], nums2[j] <= 109`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you come up with an algorithm that runs in `O(m + n)` time?

title: Gray Code
content:
An **n-bit gray code sequence** is a sequence of `2n` integers where:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Every integer is in the **inclusive** range `[0, 2n - 1]`,_x000D_
*   The first integer is `0`,_x000D_
*   An integer appears **no more than once** in the sequence,_x000D_
*   The binary representation of every pair of **adjacent** integers differs by **exactly one bit**, and_x000D_
*   The binary representation of the **first** and **last** integers differs by **exactly one bit**._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an integer `n`, return _any valid **n-bit gray code sequence**_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** \[0,1,3,2\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
The binary representation of \[0,1,3,2\] is \[00,01,11,10\]._x000D_
- 00 and 01 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 01 and 11 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 11 and 10 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 10 and 00 differ by one bit_x000D_
\[0,2,3,1\] is also a valid gray code sequence, whose binary representation is \[00,10,11,01\]._x000D_
- 00 and 10 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 10 and 11 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 11 and 01 differ by one bit_x000D_
- 01 and 00 differ by one bit_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1_x000D_
**Output:** \[0,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 16`

title: Subsets II
content:
Given an integer array `nums` that may contain duplicates, return _all possible_ _subsets_ _(the power set)_._x000D_
_x000D_
The solution set **must not** contain duplicate subsets. Return the solution in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[\],\[1\],\[1,2\],\[1,2,2\],\[2\],\[2,2\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[\],\[0\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 10`_x000D_
*   `-10 <= nums[i] <= 10`

title: Decode Ways
content:
A message containing letters from `A-Z` can be **encoded** into numbers using the following mapping:_x000D_
_x000D_
'A' ->  "1 "_x000D_
'B' ->  "2 "_x000D_
..._x000D_
'Z' ->  "26 "_x000D_
_x000D_
To **decode** an encoded message, all the digits must be grouped then mapped back into letters using the reverse of the mapping above (there may be multiple ways). For example, `"11106 "` can be mapped into:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `"AAJF "` with the grouping `(1 1 10 6)`_x000D_
*   `"KJF "` with the grouping `(11 10 6)`_x000D_
_x000D_
Note that the grouping `(1 11 06)` is invalid because `"06 "` cannot be mapped into `'F'` since `"6 "` is different from `"06 "`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a string `s` containing only digits, return _the **number** of ways to **decode** it_._x000D_
_x000D_
The test cases are generated so that the answer fits in a **32-bit** integer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "12 "_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "12 " could be decoded as  "AB " (1 2) or  "L " (12)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "226 "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "226 " could be decoded as  "BZ " (2 26),  "VF " (22 6), or  "BBF " (2 2 6)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "06 "_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "06 " cannot be mapped to  "F " because of the leading zero ( "6 " is different from  "06 ")._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `s` contains only digits and may contain leading zero(s).

title: Reverse Linked List II
content:
Given the `head` of a singly linked list and two integers `left` and `right` where `left <= right`, reverse the nodes of the list from position `left` to position `right`, and return _the reversed list_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,2,3,4,5\], left = 2, right = 4_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,4,3,2,5\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_

title: Restore IP Addresses
content:
A **valid IP address** consists of exactly four integers separated by single dots. Each integer is between `0` and `255` (**inclusive**) and cannot have leading zeros._x000D_
_x000D_
*   For example, `"0.1.2.201 "` and `"192.168.1.1 "` are **valid** IP addresses, but `"0.011.255.245 "`, `"192.168.1.312 "` and `"192.168@1.1 "` are **invalid** IP addresses._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a string `s` containing only digits, return _all possible valid IP addresses that can be formed by inserting dots into_ `s`. You are **not** allowed to reorder or remove any digits in `s`. You may return the valid IP addresses in **any** order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "25525511135 "_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "255.255.11.135 ", "255.255.111.35 "\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "0000 "_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "0.0.0.0 "\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "101023 "_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "1.0.10.23 ", "1.0.102.3 ", "10.1.0.23 ", "10.10.2.3 ", "101.0.2.3 "\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 20`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of digits only.

title: Interleaving String
content:
Given strings `s1`, `s2`, and `s3`, find whether `s3` is formed by an **interleaving** of `s1` and `s2`._x000D_
_x000D_
An **interleaving** of two strings `s` and `t` is a configuration where `s` and `t` are divided into `n` and `m` substrings respectively, such that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `s = s1 + s2 + ... + sn`_x000D_
*   `t = t1 + t2 + ... + tm`_x000D_
*   `|n - m| <= 1`_x000D_
*   The **interleaving** is `s1 + t1 + s2 + t2 + s3 + t3 + ...` or `t1 + s1 + t2 + s2 + t3 + s3 + ...`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:** `a + b` is the concatenation of strings `a` and `b`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "aabcc ", s2 =  "dbbca ", s3 =  "aadbbcbcac "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** One way to obtain s3 is:_x000D_
Split s1 into s1 =  "aa " +  "bc " +  "c ", and s2 into s2 =  "dbbc " +  "a "._x000D_
Interleaving the two splits, we get  "aa " +  "dbbc " +  "bc " +  "a " +  "c " =  "aadbbcbcac "._x000D_
Since s3 can be obtained by interleaving s1 and s2, we return true._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "aabcc ", s2 =  "dbbca ", s3 =  "aadbbbaccc "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** Notice how it is impossible to interleave s2 with any other string to obtain s3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  " ", s2 =  " ", s3 =  " "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= s1.length, s2.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `0 <= s3.length <= 200`_x000D_
*   `s1`, `s2`, and `s3` consist of lowercase English letters._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you solve it using only `O(s2.length)` additional memory space?

title: Validate Binary Search Tree
content:
Given the `root` of a binary tree, _determine if it is a valid binary search tree (BST)_._x000D_
_x000D_
A **valid BST** is defined as follows:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The left subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys **less than** the node's key._x000D_
*   The right subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys **greater than** the node's key._x000D_
*   Both the left and right subtrees must also be binary search trees._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[2,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[5,1,4,null,null,3,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** The root node's value is 5 but its right child's value is 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   `-231 <= Node.val <= 231 - 1`

title: Recover Binary Search Tree
content:
You are given the `root` of a binary search tree (BST), where the values of **exactly** two nodes of the tree were swapped by mistake. _Recover the tree without changing its structure_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,3,null,null,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,1,null,null,2\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** 3 cannot be a left child of 1 because 3 > 1. Swapping 1 and 3 makes the BST valid._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[3,1,4,null,null,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,1,4,null,null,3\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** 2 cannot be in the right subtree of 3 because 2 < 3. Swapping 2 and 3 makes the BST valid._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[2, 1000]`._x000D_
*   `-231 <= Node.val <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** A solution using `O(n)` space is pretty straight-forward. Could you devise a constant `O(1)` space solution?

*   `preorder` and `inorder` consist of **unique** values._x000D_

*   `preorder` is **guaranteed** to be the preorder traversal of the tree._x000D_
*   `inorder` is **guaranteed** to be the inorder traversal of the tree.

_x000D_
A **leaf** is a node with no children._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[5,4,8,11,null,13,4,7,2,null,null,null,1\], targetSum = 22_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** The root-to-leaf path with the target sum is shown._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3\], targetSum = 5_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** There two root-to-leaf paths in the tree:_x000D_
(1 --> 2): The sum is 3._x000D_
(1 --> 3): The sum is 4._x000D_
There is no root-to-leaf path with sum = 5._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[\], targetSum = 0_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** Since the tree is empty, there are no root-to-leaf paths._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[0, 5000]`._x000D_
*   `-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= targetSum <= 1000`

*   `-100 <= Node.val <= 100`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you flatten the tree in-place (with `O(1)` extra space)?

title: Distinct Subsequences
content:
Given two strings `s` and `t`, return _the number of distinct_ **_subsequences_** _of_ `s` _which equals_ `t`._x000D_
_x000D_
The test cases are generated so that the answer fits on a 32-bit signed integer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "rabbbit ", t =  "rabbit "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
As shown below, there are 3 ways you can generate  "rabbit " from s._x000D_
`**rabb**b**it**`_x000D_
`**ra**b**bbit**`_x000D_
`**rab**b**bit**`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "babgbag ", t =  "bag "_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
As shown below, there are 5 ways you can generate  "bag " from s._x000D_
`**ba**b**g**bag`_x000D_
`**ba**bgba**g**`_x000D_
`**b**abgb**ag**`_x000D_
`ba**b**gb**ag**`_x000D_
`babg**bag**`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length, t.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `s` and `t` consist of English letters.

title: Populating Next Right Pointers in Each Node
content:
You are given a **perfect binary tree** where all leaves are on the same level, and every parent has two children. The binary tree has the following definition:_x000D_
_x000D_
struct Node {_x000D_
  int val;_x000D_
  Node \*left;_x000D_
  Node \*right;_x000D_
  Node \*next;_x000D_
}_x000D_
_x000D_
Populate each next pointer to point to its next right node. If there is no next right node, the next pointer should be set to `NULL`._x000D_
_x000D_
Initially, all next pointers are set to `NULL`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3,4,5,6,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,#,2,3,#,4,5,6,7,#\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Given the above perfect binary tree (Figure A), your function should populate each next pointer to point to its next right node, just like in Figure B. The serialized output is in level order as connected by the next pointers, with '#' signifying the end of each level._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[0, 212 - 1]`._x000D_
*   `-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow-up:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   You may only use constant extra space._x000D_
*   The recursive approach is fine. You may assume implicit stack space does not count as extra space for this problem.

title: Populating Next Right Pointers in Each Node II
content:

_x000D_
struct Node {_x000D_

**Explanation:** Given the above binary tree (Figure A), your function should populate each next pointer to point to its next right node, just like in Figure B. The serialized output is in level order as connected by the next pointers, with '#' signifying the end of each level._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_

title: Pascal's Triangle
content:
Given an integer `numRows`, return the first numRows of **Pascal's triangle**._x000D_
_x000D_
In **Pascal's triangle**, each number is the sum of the two numbers directly above it as shown:_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numRows = 5_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1\],\[1,1\],\[1,2,1\],\[1,3,3,1\],\[1,4,6,4,1\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numRows = 1_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= numRows <= 30`

title: Pascal's Triangle II
content:
Given an integer `rowIndex`, return the `rowIndexth` (**0-indexed**) row of the **Pascal's triangle**._x000D_
_x000D_
In **Pascal's triangle**, each number is the sum of the two numbers directly above it as shown:_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rowIndex = 3_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,3,3,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rowIndex = 0_x000D_
**Output:** \[1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rowIndex = 1_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= rowIndex <= 33`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you optimize your algorithm to use only `O(rowIndex)` extra space?

title: Triangle
content:
Given a `triangle` array, return _the minimum path sum from top to bottom_._x000D_
_x000D_
For each step, you may move to an adjacent number of the row below. More formally, if you are on index `i` on the current row, you may move to either index `i` or index `i + 1` on the next row._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** triangle = \[\[2\],\[3,4\],\[6,5,7\],\[4,1,8,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 11_x000D_
**Explanation:** The triangle looks like:_x000D_
   2_x000D_
  3 4_x000D_
 6 5 7_x000D_
4 1 8 3_x000D_
The minimum path sum from top to bottom is 2 + 3 + 5 + 1 = 11 (underlined above)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** triangle = \[\[-10\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** -10_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= triangle.length <= 200`_x000D_
*   `triangle[0].length == 1`_x000D_
*   `triangle[i].length == triangle[i - 1].length + 1`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= triangle[i][j] <= 104`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you do this using only `O(n)` extra space, where `n` is the total number of rows in the triangle?

title: Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock
content:
You are given an array `prices` where `prices[i]` is the price of a given stock on the `ith` day._x000D_
_x000D_
You want to maximize your profit by choosing a **single day** to buy one stock and choosing a **different day in the future** to sell that stock._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the maximum profit you can achieve from this transaction_. If you cannot achieve any profit, return `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[7,1,5,3,6,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** Buy on day 2 (price = 1) and sell on day 5 (price = 6), profit = 6-1 = 5._x000D_
Note that buying on day 2 and selling on day 1 is not allowed because you must buy before you sell._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[7,6,4,3,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this case, no transactions are done and the max profit = 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= prices.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= prices[i] <= 104`

title: Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock II
content:
You are given an integer array `prices` where `prices[i]` is the price of a given stock on the `ith` day._x000D_
_x000D_
On each day, you may decide to buy and/or sell the stock. You can only hold **at most one** share of the stock at any time. However, you can buy it then immediately sell it on the **same day**._x000D_
_x000D_
Find and return _the **maximum** profit you can achieve_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[7,1,5,3,6,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 7_x000D_
**Explanation:** Buy on day 2 (price = 1) and sell on day 3 (price = 5), profit = 5-1 = 4._x000D_
Then buy on day 4 (price = 3) and sell on day 5 (price = 6), profit = 6-3 = 3._x000D_
Total profit is 4 + 3 = 7._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[1,2,3,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** Buy on day 1 (price = 1) and sell on day 5 (price = 5), profit = 5-1 = 4._x000D_
Total profit is 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[7,6,4,3,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is no way to make a positive profit, so we never buy the stock to achieve the maximum profit of 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= prices.length <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   `0 <= prices[i] <= 104`

title: Best Time to Buy and Sell Stock III
content:
You are given an array `prices` where `prices[i]` is the price of a given stock on the `ith` day._x000D_
_x000D_
Find the maximum profit you can achieve. You may complete **at most two transactions**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:** You may not engage in multiple transactions simultaneously (i.e., you must sell the stock before you buy again)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[3,3,5,0,0,3,1,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** Buy on day 4 (price = 0) and sell on day 6 (price = 3), profit = 3-0 = 3._x000D_
Then buy on day 7 (price = 1) and sell on day 8 (price = 4), profit = 4-1 = 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[1,2,3,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** Buy on day 1 (price = 1) and sell on day 5 (price = 5), profit = 5-1 = 4._x000D_
Note that you cannot buy on day 1, buy on day 2 and sell them later, as you are engaging multiple transactions at the same time. You must sell before buying again._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prices = \[7,6,4,3,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this case, no transaction is done, i.e. max profit = 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= prices.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= prices[i] <= 105`

title: Binary Tree Maximum Path Sum
content:
A **path** in a binary tree is a sequence of nodes where each pair of adjacent nodes in the sequence has an edge connecting them. A node can only appear in the sequence **at most once**. Note that the path does not need to pass through the root._x000D_
_x000D_
The **path sum** of a path is the sum of the node's values in the path._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the `root` of a binary tree, return _the maximum **path sum** of any **non-empty** path_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** The optimal path is 2 -> 1 -> 3 with a path sum of 2 + 1 + 3 = 6._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[-10,9,20,null,null,15,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** 42_x000D_
**Explanation:** The optimal path is 15 -> 20 -> 7 with a path sum of 15 + 20 + 7 = 42._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 3 * 104]`._x000D_
*   `-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000`

title: Valid Palindrome
content:
A phrase is a **palindrome** if, after converting all uppercase letters into lowercase letters and removing all non-alphanumeric characters, it reads the same forward and backward. Alphanumeric characters include letters and numbers._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a string `s`, return `true` _if it is a **palindrome**, or_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "A man, a plan, a canal: Panama "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "amanaplanacanalpanama " is a palindrome._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "race a car "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "raceacar " is not a palindrome._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "  "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** s is an empty string  " " after removing non-alphanumeric characters._x000D_
Since an empty string reads the same forward and backward, it is a palindrome._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 2 * 105`_x000D_
*   `s` consists only of printable ASCII characters.

title: Word Ladder II
content:
A **transformation sequence** from word `beginWord` to word `endWord` using a dictionary `wordList` is a sequence of words `beginWord -> s1 -> s2 -> ... -> sk` such that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Every adjacent pair of words differs by a single letter._x000D_
*   Every `si` for `1 <= i <= k` is in `wordList`. Note that `beginWord` does not need to be in `wordList`._x000D_
*   `sk == endWord`_x000D_
_x000D_
Given two words, `beginWord` and `endWord`, and a dictionary `wordList`, return _all the **shortest transformation sequences** from_ `beginWord` _to_ `endWord`_, or an empty list if no such sequence exists. Each sequence should be returned as a list of the words_ `[beginWord, s1, s2, ..., sk]`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** beginWord =  "hit ", endWord =  "cog ", wordList = \[ "hot ", "dot ", "dog ", "lot ", "log ", "cog "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "hit ", "hot ", "dot ", "dog ", "cog "\],\[ "hit ", "hot ", "lot ", "log ", "cog "\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 2 shortest transformation sequences:_x000D_
 "hit " ->  "hot " ->  "dot " ->  "dog " ->  "cog "_x000D_
 "hit " ->  "hot " ->  "lot " ->  "log " ->  "cog "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** beginWord =  "hit ", endWord =  "cog ", wordList = \[ "hot ", "dot ", "dog ", "lot ", "log "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The endWord  "cog " is not in wordList, therefore there is no valid transformation sequence._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= beginWord.length <= 5`_x000D_
*   `endWord.length == beginWord.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= wordList.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `wordList[i].length == beginWord.length`_x000D_
*   `beginWord`, `endWord`, and `wordList[i]` consist of lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   `beginWord != endWord`_x000D_
*   All the words in `wordList` are **unique**._x000D_
*   The **sum** of all shortest transformation sequences does not exceed `105`.

title: Word Ladder
content:
A **transformation sequence** from word `beginWord` to word `endWord` using a dictionary `wordList` is a sequence of words `beginWord -> s1 -> s2 -> ... -> sk` such that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Every adjacent pair of words differs by a single letter._x000D_
*   Every `si` for `1 <= i <= k` is in `wordList`. Note that `beginWord` does not need to be in `wordList`._x000D_
*   `sk == endWord`_x000D_
_x000D_
Given two words, `beginWord` and `endWord`, and a dictionary `wordList`, return _the **number of words** in the **shortest transformation sequence** from_ `beginWord` _to_ `endWord`_, or_ `0` _if no such sequence exists.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** beginWord =  "hit ", endWord =  "cog ", wordList = \[ "hot ", "dot ", "dog ", "lot ", "log ", "cog "\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** One shortest transformation sequence is  "hit " ->  "hot " ->  "dot " ->  "dog " -> cog ", which is 5 words long._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** beginWord =  "hit ", endWord =  "cog ", wordList = \[ "hot ", "dot ", "dog ", "lot ", "log "\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The endWord  "cog " is not in wordList, therefore there is no valid transformation sequence._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= beginWord.length <= 10`_x000D_
*   `endWord.length == beginWord.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= wordList.length <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `wordList[i].length == beginWord.length`_x000D_
*   `beginWord`, `endWord`, and `wordList[i]` consist of lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   `beginWord != endWord`_x000D_
*   All the words in `wordList` are **unique**.

title: Longest Consecutive Sequence
content:
Given an unsorted array of integers `nums`, return _the length of the longest consecutive elements sequence.__x000D_
_x000D_
You must write an algorithm that runs in `O(n)` time._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[100,4,200,1,3,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest consecutive elements sequence is `[1, 2, 3, 4]`. Therefore its length is 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0,3,7,2,5,8,4,6,0,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 9_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= nums[i] <= 109`

title: Sum Root to Leaf Numbers
content:
You are given the `root` of a binary tree containing digits from `0` to `9` only._x000D_
_x000D_
Each root-to-leaf path in the tree represents a number._x000D_
_x000D_
*   For example, the root-to-leaf path `1 -> 2 -> 3` represents the number `123`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the total sum of all root-to-leaf numbers_. Test cases are generated so that the answer will fit in a **32-bit** integer._x000D_
_x000D_
A **leaf** node is a node with no children._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 25_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
The root-to-leaf path `1->2` represents the number `12`._x000D_
The root-to-leaf path `1->3` represents the number `13`._x000D_
Therefore, sum = 12 + 13 = `25`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[4,9,0,5,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1026_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
The root-to-leaf path `4->9->5` represents the number 495._x000D_
The root-to-leaf path `4->9->1` represents the number 491._x000D_
The root-to-leaf path `4->0` represents the number 40._x000D_
Therefore, sum = 495 + 491 + 40 = `1026`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 1000]`._x000D_
*   `0 <= Node.val <= 9`_x000D_
*   The depth of the tree will not exceed `10`.

title: Surrounded Regions
content:
Given an `m x n` matrix `board` containing `'X'` and `'O'`, _capture all regions that are 4-directionally surrounded by_ `'X'`._x000D_
_x000D_
A region is **captured** by flipping all `'O'`s into `'X'`s in that surrounded region._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** board = \[\[ "X ", "X ", "X ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "O ", "O ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "X ", "O ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "O ", "X ", "X "\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "X ", "X ", "X ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "X ", "X ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "X ", "X ", "X "\],\[ "X ", "O ", "X ", "X "\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Notice that an 'O' should not be flipped if:_x000D_
- It is on the border, or_x000D_
- It is adjacent to an 'O' that should not be flipped._x000D_
The bottom 'O' is on the border, so it is not flipped._x000D_
The other three 'O' form a surrounded region, so they are flipped._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** board = \[\[ "X "\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "X "\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == board.length`_x000D_
*   `n == board[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 200`_x000D_
*   `board[i][j]` is `'X'` or `'O'`.

title: Palindrome Partitioning
content:
Given a string `s`, partition `s` such that every substring of the partition is a **palindrome**. Return _all possible palindrome partitioning of_ `s`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s = "aab"_x000D_
**Output:** \[\["a","a","b"\],\["aa","b"\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s = "a"_x000D_
**Output:** \[\["a"\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 16`_x000D_
*   `s` contains only lowercase English letters.

title: Palindrome Partitioning II
content:
Given a string `s`, partition `s` such that every substring of the partition is a palindrome._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimum** cuts needed for a palindrome partitioning of_ `s`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "aab "_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The palindrome partitioning \[ "aa ", "b "\] could be produced using 1 cut._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "a "_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "ab "_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 2000`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of lowercase English letters only.

title: Clone Graph
content:
Given a reference of a node in a **[connected](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectivity_(graph_theory)#Connected_graph)** undirected graph._x000D_
_x000D_
Return a [**deep copy**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object_copying#Deep_copy) (clone) of the graph._x000D_
_x000D_
Each node in the graph contains a value (`int`) and a list (`List[Node]`) of its neighbors._x000D_
_x000D_
class Node {_x000D_
    public int val;_x000D_
    public List neighbors;_x000D_
}_x000D_
_x000D_
**Test case format:**_x000D_
_x000D_
For simplicity, each node's value is the same as the node's index (1-indexed). For example, the first node with `val == 1`, the second node with `val == 2`, and so on. The graph is represented in the test case using an adjacency list._x000D_
_x000D_
**An adjacency list** is a collection of unordered **lists** used to represent a finite graph. Each list describes the set of neighbors of a node in the graph._x000D_
_x000D_
The given node will always be the first node with `val = 1`. You must return the **copy of the given node** as a reference to the cloned graph._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** adjList = \[\[2,4\],\[1,3\],\[2,4\],\[1,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[2,4\],\[1,3\],\[2,4\],\[1,3\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 4 nodes in the graph._x000D_
1st node (val = 1)'s neighbors are 2nd node (val = 2) and 4th node (val = 4)._x000D_
2nd node (val = 2)'s neighbors are 1st node (val = 1) and 3rd node (val = 3)._x000D_
3rd node (val = 3)'s neighbors are 2nd node (val = 2) and 4th node (val = 4)._x000D_
4th node (val = 4)'s neighbors are 1st node (val = 1) and 3rd node (val = 3)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** adjList = \[\[\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Note that the input contains one empty list. The graph consists of only one node with val = 1 and it does not have any neighbors._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** adjList = \[\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** This an empty graph, it does not have any nodes._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the graph is in the range `[0, 100]`._x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 100`_x000D_
*   `Node.val` is unique for each node._x000D_
*   There are no repeated edges and no self-loops in the graph._x000D_
*   The Graph is connected and all nodes can be visited starting from the given node.

title: Gas Station
content:
There are `n` gas stations along a circular route, where the amount of gas at the `ith` station is `gas[i]`._x000D_
_x000D_
You have a car with an unlimited gas tank and it costs `cost[i]` of gas to travel from the `ith` station to its next `(i + 1)th` station. You begin the journey with an empty tank at one of the gas stations._x000D_
_x000D_
Given two integer arrays `gas` and `cost`, return _the starting gas station's index if you can travel around the circuit once in the clockwise direction, otherwise return_ `-1`. If there exists a solution, it is **guaranteed** to be **unique**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** gas = \[1,2,3,4,5\], cost = \[3,4,5,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Start at station 3 (index 3) and fill up with 4 unit of gas. Your tank = 0 + 4 = 4_x000D_
Travel to station 4. Your tank = 4 - 1 + 5 = 8_x000D_
Travel to station 0. Your tank = 8 - 2 + 1 = 7_x000D_
Travel to station 1. Your tank = 7 - 3 + 2 = 6_x000D_
Travel to station 2. Your tank = 6 - 4 + 3 = 5_x000D_
Travel to station 3. The cost is 5. Your gas is just enough to travel back to station 3._x000D_
Therefore, return 3 as the starting index._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** gas = \[2,3,4\], cost = \[3,4,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
You can't start at station 0 or 1, as there is not enough gas to travel to the next station._x000D_
Let's start at station 2 and fill up with 4 unit of gas. Your tank = 0 + 4 = 4_x000D_
Travel to station 0. Your tank = 4 - 3 + 2 = 3_x000D_
Travel to station 1. Your tank = 3 - 3 + 3 = 3_x000D_
You cannot travel back to station 2, as it requires 4 unit of gas but you only have 3._x000D_
Therefore, you can't travel around the circuit once no matter where you start._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == gas.length == cost.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= gas[i], cost[i] <= 104`

title: Candy
content:
There are `n` children standing in a line. Each child is assigned a rating value given in the integer array `ratings`._x000D_
_x000D_
You are giving candies to these children subjected to the following requirements:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Each child must have at least one candy._x000D_
*   Children with a higher rating get more candies than their neighbors._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the minimum number of candies you need to have to distribute the candies to the children_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** ratings = \[1,0,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can allocate to the first, second and third child with 2, 1, 2 candies respectively._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** ratings = \[1,2,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can allocate to the first, second and third child with 1, 2, 1 candies respectively._x000D_
The third child gets 1 candy because it satisfies the above two conditions._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == ratings.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 2 * 104`_x000D_
*   `0 <= ratings[i] <= 2 * 104`

title: Single Number
content:
Given a **non-empty** array of integers `nums`, every element appears _twice_ except for one. Find that single one._x000D_
_x000D_
You must implement a solution with a linear runtime complexity and use only constant extra space._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,2,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[4,1,2,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-3 * 104 <= nums[i] <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   Each element in the array appears twice except for one element which appears only once.

title: Single Number II
content:
Given an integer array `nums` where every element appears **three times** except for one, which appears **exactly once**. _Find the single element and return it_._x000D_
_x000D_
You must implement a solution with a linear runtime complexity and use only constant extra space._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,2,3,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0,1,0,1,0,1,99\]_x000D_
**Output:** 99_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_

*   `-231 <= nums[i] <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
*   Each element in `nums` appears exactly **three times** except for one element which appears **once**.

title: Copy List with Random Pointer
content:
A linked list of length `n` is given such that each node contains an additional random pointer, which could point to any node in the list, or `null`._x000D_
_x000D_
Construct a [**deep copy**](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object_copying#Deep_copy) of the list. The deep copy should consist of exactly `n` **brand new** nodes, where each new node has its value set to the value of its corresponding original node. Both the `next` and `random` pointer of the new nodes should point to new nodes in the copied list such that the pointers in the original list and copied list represent the same list state. **None of the pointers in the new list should point to nodes in the original list**._x000D_
_x000D_
For example, if there are two nodes `X` and `Y` in the original list, where `X.random --> Y`, then for the corresponding two nodes `x` and `y` in the copied list, `x.random --> y`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the head of the copied linked list_._x000D_
_x000D_
The linked list is represented in the input/output as a list of `n` nodes. Each node is represented as a pair of `[val, random_index]` where:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `val`: an integer representing `Node.val`_x000D_
*   `random_index`: the index of the node (range from `0` to `n-1`) that the `random` pointer points to, or `null` if it does not point to any node._x000D_
_x000D_
Your code will **only** be given the `head` of the original linked list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[\[7,null\],\[13,0\],\[11,4\],\[10,2\],\[1,0\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[7,null\],\[13,0\],\[11,4\],\[10,2\],\[1,0\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[\[1,1\],\[2,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1,1\],\[2,1\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[\[3,null\],\[3,0\],\[3,null\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[3,null\],\[3,0\],\[3,null\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= Node.val <= 104`_x000D_
*   `Node.random` is `null` or is pointing to some node in the linked list.

title: Word Break
content:
Given a string `s` and a dictionary of strings `wordDict`, return `true` if `s` can be segmented into a space-separated sequence of one or more dictionary words._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that the same word in the dictionary may be reused multiple times in the segmentation._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "leetcode ", wordDict = \[ "leet ", "code "\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** Return true because  "leetcode " can be segmented as  "leet code "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "applepenapple ", wordDict = \[ "apple ", "pen "\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** Return true because  "applepenapple " can be segmented as  "apple pen apple "._x000D_
Note that you are allowed to reuse a dictionary word._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "catsandog ", wordDict = \[ "cats ", "dog ", "sand ", "and ", "cat "\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_

*   `1 <= wordDict.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= wordDict[i].length <= 20`_x000D_
*   `s` and `wordDict[i]` consist of only lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   All the strings of `wordDict` are **unique**.

title: Word Break II
content:

_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "catsandog ", wordDict = \[ "cats ", "dog ", "sand ", "and ", "cat "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_

*   `s` and `wordDict[i]` consist of only lowercase English letters._x000D_

title: Linked List Cycle
content:
Given `head`, the head of a linked list, determine if the linked list has a cycle in it._x000D_
_x000D_
There is a cycle in a linked list if there is some node in the list that can be reached again by continuously following the `next` pointer. Internally, `pos` is used to denote the index of the node that tail's `next` pointer is connected to. **Note that `pos` is not passed as a parameter**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `true` _if there is a cycle in the linked list_. Otherwise, return `false`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[3,2,0,-4\], pos = 1_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is a cycle in the linked list, where the tail connects to the 1st node (0-indexed)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,2\], pos = 0_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is a cycle in the linked list, where the tail connects to the 0th node._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1\], pos = -1_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is no cycle in the linked list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of the nodes in the list is in the range `[0, 104]`._x000D_
*   `-105 <= Node.val <= 105`_x000D_
*   `pos` is `-1` or a **valid index** in the linked-list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you solve it using `O(1)` (i.e. constant) memory?

title: Linked List Cycle II
content:
Given the `head` of a linked list, return _the node where the cycle begins. If there is no cycle, return_ `null`._x000D_
_x000D_
There is a cycle in a linked list if there is some node in the list that can be reached again by continuously following the `next` pointer. Internally, `pos` is used to denote the index of the node that tail's `next` pointer is connected to (**0-indexed**). It is `-1` if there is no cycle. **Note that** `pos` **is not passed as a parameter**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Do not modify** the linked list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[3,2,0,-4\], pos = 1_x000D_
**Output:** tail connects to node index 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is a cycle in the linked list, where tail connects to the second node._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,2\], pos = 0_x000D_
**Output:** tail connects to node index 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is a cycle in the linked list, where tail connects to the first node._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1\], pos = -1_x000D_
**Output:** no cycle_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is no cycle in the linked list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of the nodes in the list is in the range `[0, 104]`._x000D_
*   `-105 <= Node.val <= 105`_x000D_
*   `pos` is `-1` or a **valid index** in the linked-list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you solve it using `O(1)` (i.e. constant) memory?

title: Reorder List
content:
You are given the head of a singly linked-list. The list can be represented as:_x000D_
_x000D_
L0 -> L1 -> ... -> Ln - 1 -> Ln_x000D_
_x000D_
_Reorder the list to be on the following form:__x000D_
_x000D_
L0 -> Ln -> L1 -> Ln - 1 -> L2 -> Ln - 2 -> ..._x000D_
_x000D_
You may not modify the values in the list's nodes. Only nodes themselves may be changed._x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_

title: LRU Cache
content:
Design a data structure that follows the constraints of a **[Least Recently Used (LRU) cache](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cache_replacement_policies#LRU)**._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `LRUCache` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `LRUCache(int capacity)` Initialize the LRU cache with **positive** size `capacity`._x000D_
*   `int get(int key)` Return the value of the `key` if the key exists, otherwise return `-1`._x000D_
*   `void put(int key, int value)` Update the value of the `key` if the `key` exists. Otherwise, add the `key-value` pair to the cache. If the number of keys exceeds the `capacity` from this operation, **evict** the least recently used key._x000D_
_x000D_
The functions `get` and `put` must each run in `O(1)` average time complexity._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "LRUCache ",  "put ",  "put ",  "get ",  "put ",  "get ",  "put ",  "get ",  "get ",  "get "\]_x000D_
\[\[2\], \[1, 1\], \[2, 2\], \[1\], \[3, 3\], \[2\], \[4, 4\], \[1\], \[3\], \[4\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, null, null, 1, null, -1, null, -1, 3, 4\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
LRUCache lRUCache = new LRUCache(2);_x000D_
lRUCache.put(1, 1); // cache is {1=1}_x000D_
lRUCache.put(2, 2); // cache is {1=1, 2=2}_x000D_
lRUCache.get(1);    // return 1_x000D_
lRUCache.put(3, 3); // LRU key was 2, evicts key 2, cache is {1=1, 3=3}_x000D_
lRUCache.get(2);    // returns -1 (not found)_x000D_
lRUCache.put(4, 4); // LRU key was 1, evicts key 1, cache is {4=4, 3=3}_x000D_
lRUCache.get(1);    // return -1 (not found)_x000D_
lRUCache.get(3);    // return 3_x000D_
lRUCache.get(4);    // return 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= capacity <= 3000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= key <= 104`_x000D_
*   `0 <= value <= 105`_x000D_
*   At most `2 * 105` calls will be made to `get` and `put`.

title: Insertion Sort List
content:
Given the `head` of a singly linked list, sort the list using **insertion sort**, and return _the sorted list's head_._x000D_
_x000D_
The steps of the **insertion sort** algorithm:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  Insertion sort iterates, consuming one input element each repetition and growing a sorted output list._x000D_
2.  At each iteration, insertion sort removes one element from the input data, finds the location it belongs within the sorted list and inserts it there._x000D_
3.  It repeats until no input elements remain._x000D_
_x000D_
The following is a graphical example of the insertion sort algorithm. The partially sorted list (black) initially contains only the first element in the list. One element (red) is removed from the input data and inserted in-place into the sorted list with each iteration._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[4,2,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[-1,5,3,4,0\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[-1,0,3,4,5\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the list is in the range `[1, 5000]`._x000D_
*   `-5000 <= Node.val <= 5000`

title: Sort List

**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
