**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the list is in the range `[0, 5 * 104]`._x000D_
*   `-105 <= Node.val <= 105`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you sort the linked list in `O(n logn)` time and `O(1)` memory (i.e. constant space)?

title: Max Points on a Line
content:
Given an array of `points` where `points[i] = [xi, yi]` represents a point on the **X-Y** plane, return _the maximum number of points that lie on the same straight line_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** points = \[\[1,1\],\[2,2\],\[3,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** points = \[\[1,1\],\[3,2\],\[5,3\],\[4,1\],\[2,3\],\[1,4\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= points.length <= 300`_x000D_
*   `points[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= xi, yi <= 104`_x000D_
*   All the `points` are **unique**.

title: Evaluate Reverse Polish Notation
content:
You are given an array of strings `tokens` that represents an arithmetic expression in a [Reverse Polish Notation](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverse_Polish_notation)._x000D_
_x000D_
Evaluate the expression. Return _an integer that represents the value of the expression_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The valid operators are `'+'`, `'-'`, `'*'`, and `'/'`._x000D_
*   Each operand may be an integer or another expression._x000D_
*   The division between two integers always **truncates toward zero**._x000D_
*   There will not be any division by zero._x000D_
*   The input represents a valid arithmetic expression in a reverse polish notation._x000D_
*   The answer and all the intermediate calculations can be represented in a **32-bit** integer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tokens = \[ "2 ", "1 ", "+ ", "3 ", "\* "\]_x000D_
**Output:** 9_x000D_
**Explanation:** ((2 + 1) \* 3) = 9_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tokens = \[ "4 ", "13 ", "5 ", "/ ", "+ "\]_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** (4 + (13 / 5)) = 6_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tokens = \[ "10 ", "6 ", "9 ", "3 ", "+ ", "-11 ", "\* ", "/ ", "\* ", "17 ", "+ ", "5 ", "+ "\]_x000D_
**Output:** 22_x000D_
**Explanation:** ((10 \* (6 / ((9 + 3) \* -11))) + 17) + 5_x000D_
= ((10 \* (6 / (12 \* -11))) + 17) + 5_x000D_
= ((10 \* (6 / -132)) + 17) + 5_x000D_
= ((10 \* 0) + 17) + 5_x000D_
= (0 + 17) + 5_x000D_
= 17 + 5_x000D_
= 22_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= tokens.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `tokens[i]` is either an operator: `"+ "`, `"- "`, `"* "`, or `"/ "`, or an integer in the range `[-200, 200]`.

title: Reverse Words in a String
content:
Given an input string `s`, reverse the order of the **words**._x000D_
_x000D_
A **word** is defined as a sequence of non-space characters. The **words** in `s` will be separated by at least one space._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _a string of the words in reverse order concatenated by a single space.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that `s` may contain leading or trailing spaces or multiple spaces between two words. The returned string should only have a single space separating the words. Do not include any extra spaces._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "the sky is blue "_x000D_
**Output:**  "blue is sky the "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "  hello world   "_x000D_
**Output:**  "world hello "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Your reversed string should not contain leading or trailing spaces._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "a good   example "_x000D_
**Output:**  "example good a "_x000D_
**Explanation:** You need to reduce multiple spaces between two words to a single space in the reversed string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `s` contains English letters (upper-case and lower-case), digits, and spaces `' '`._x000D_
*   There is **at least one** word in `s`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow-up:** If the string data type is mutable in your language, can you solve it **in-place** with `O(1)` extra space?

title: Maximum Product Subarray
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, find a subarray that has the largest product, and return _the product_._x000D_
_x000D_
The test cases are generated so that the answer will fit in a **32-bit** integer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,3,-2,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** \[2,3\] has the largest product 6._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[-2,0,-1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The result cannot be 2, because \[-2,-1\] is not a subarray._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 2 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-10 <= nums[i] <= 10`_x000D_
*   The product of any prefix or suffix of `nums` is **guaranteed** to fit in a **32-bit** integer.

title: Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array
content:
Suppose an array of length `n` sorted in ascending order is **rotated** between `1` and `n` times. For example, the array `nums = [0,1,2,4,5,6,7]` might become:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `[4,5,6,7,0,1,2]` if it was rotated `4` times._x000D_
*   `[0,1,2,4,5,6,7]` if it was rotated `7` times._x000D_
_x000D_
Notice that **rotating** an array `[a[0], a[1], a[2], ..., a[n-1]]` 1 time results in the array `[a[n-1], a[0], a[1], a[2], ..., a[n-2]]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the sorted rotated array `nums` of **unique** elements, return _the minimum element of this array_._x000D_
_x000D_
You must write an algorithm that runs in `O(log n) time.`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[3,4,5,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The original array was \[1,2,3,4,5\] rotated 3 times._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[4,5,6,7,0,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The original array was \[0,1,2,4,5,6,7\] and it was rotated 4 times._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[11,13,15,17\]_x000D_
**Output:** 11_x000D_
**Explanation:** The original array was \[11,13,15,17\] and it was rotated 4 times. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == nums.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `-5000 <= nums[i] <= 5000`_x000D_
*   All the integers of `nums` are **unique**._x000D_
*   `nums` is sorted and rotated between `1` and `n` times.

title: Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array II
content:
Suppose an array of length `n` sorted in ascending order is **rotated** between `1` and `n` times. For example, the array `nums = [0,1,4,4,5,6,7]` might become:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `[4,5,6,7,0,1,4]` if it was rotated `4` times._x000D_
*   `[0,1,4,4,5,6,7]` if it was rotated `7` times._x000D_
_x000D_
Notice that **rotating** an array `[a[0], a[1], a[2], ..., a[n-1]]` 1 time results in the array `[a[n-1], a[0], a[1], a[2], ..., a[n-2]]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the sorted rotated array `nums` that may contain **duplicates**, return _the minimum element of this array_._x000D_
_x000D_
You must decrease the overall operation steps as much as possible._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,3,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,2,2,0,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == nums.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `-5000 <= nums[i] <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `nums` is sorted and rotated between `1` and `n` times._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** This problem is similar to [Find Minimum in Rotated Sorted Array](https://leetcode.com/problems/find-minimum-in-rotated-sorted-array/description/), but `nums` may contain **duplicates**. Would this affect the runtime complexity? How and why?

title: Min Stack
content:
Design a stack that supports push, pop, top, and retrieving the minimum element in constant time._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `MinStack` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `MinStack()` initializes the stack object._x000D_
*   `void push(int val)` pushes the element `val` onto the stack._x000D_
*   `void pop()` removes the element on the top of the stack._x000D_
*   `int top()` gets the top element of the stack._x000D_
*   `int getMin()` retrieves the minimum element in the stack._x000D_
_x000D_
You must implement a solution with `O(1)` time complexity for each function._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "MinStack ", "push ", "push ", "push ", "getMin ", "pop ", "top ", "getMin "\]_x000D_
\[\[\],\[-2\],\[0\],\[-3\],\[\],\[\],\[\],\[\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null,null,null,null,-3,null,0,-2\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
MinStack minStack = new MinStack();_x000D_
minStack.push(-2);_x000D_
minStack.push(0);_x000D_
minStack.push(-3);_x000D_
minStack.getMin(); // return -3_x000D_
minStack.pop();_x000D_
minStack.top();    // return 0_x000D_
minStack.getMin(); // return -2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `-231 <= val <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
*   Methods `pop`, `top` and `getMin` operations will always be called on **non-empty** stacks._x000D_
*   At most `3 * 104` calls will be made to `push`, `pop`, `top`, and `getMin`.

title: Binary Tree Upside Down
content:
Given the `root` of a binary tree, turn the tree upside down and return _the new root_._x000D_
_x000D_
You can turn a binary tree upside down with the following steps:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  The original left child becomes the new root._x000D_
2.  The original root becomes the new right child._x000D_
3.  The original right child becomes the new left child._x000D_
_x000D_
The mentioned steps are done level by level. It is **guaranteed** that every right node has a sibling (a left node with the same parent) and has no children._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[4,5,2,null,null,3,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree will be in the range `[0, 10]`._x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 10`_x000D_
*   Every right node in the tree has a sibling (a left node that shares the same parent)._x000D_
*   Every right node in the tree has no children.

title: Read N Characters Given Read4
content:
Given a `file` and assume that you can only read the file using a given method `read4`, implement a method to read `n` characters._x000D_
_x000D_
**Method read4:**_x000D_
_x000D_
The API `read4` reads **four consecutive characters** from `file`, then writes those characters into the buffer array `buf4`._x000D_
_x000D_
The return value is the number of actual characters read._x000D_
_x000D_
Note that `read4()` has its own file pointer, much like `FILE *fp` in C._x000D_
_x000D_
**Definition of read4:**_x000D_
_x000D_
    Parameter:  char\[\] buf4_x000D_
    Returns:    int_x000D_
_x000D_
buf4\[\] is a destination, not a source. The results from read4 will be copied to buf4\[\]._x000D_
_x000D_
Below is a high-level example of how `read4` works:_x000D_
_x000D_
File file( "abcde `"); // File is  "`abcde `", initially file pointer (fp) points to 'a' char[] buf4 = new char[4]; // Create buffer with enough space to store characters read4(buf4); // read4 returns 4. Now buf4 =  "abcd ", fp points to 'e' read4(buf4); // read4 returns 1. Now buf4 =  "e ", fp points to end of file read4(buf4); // read4 returns 0. Now buf4 =  " ", fp points to end of file`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Method read:**_x000D_
_x000D_
By using the `read4` method, implement the method read that reads `n` characters from `file` and store it in the buffer array `buf`. Consider that you cannot manipulate `file` directly._x000D_
_x000D_
The return value is the number of actual characters read._x000D_
_x000D_
**Definition of read:**_x000D_
_x000D_
    Parameters:    char\[\] buf, int n_x000D_
    Returns:    int_x000D_
_x000D_
buf\[\] is a destination, not a source. You will need to write the results to buf\[\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Consider that you cannot manipulate the file directly. The file is only accessible for `read4` but not for `read`._x000D_
*   The `read` function will only be called once for each test case._x000D_
*   You may assume the destination buffer array, `buf`, is guaranteed to have enough space for storing `n` characters._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** file =  "abc ", n = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** After calling your read method, buf should contain  "abc ". We read a total of 3 characters from the file, so return 3._x000D_
Note that  "abc " is the file's content, not buf. buf is the destination buffer that you will have to write the results to._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** file =  "abcde ", n = 5_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** After calling your read method, buf should contain  "abcde ". We read a total of 5 characters from the file, so return 5._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** file =  "abcdABCD1234 ", n = 12_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
**Explanation:** After calling your read method, buf should contain  "abcdABCD1234 ". We read a total of 12 characters from the file, so return 12._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= file.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `file` consist of English letters and digits._x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 1000`

title: Read N Characters Given read4 II - Call Multiple Times
content:
Given a `file` and assume that you can only read the file using a given method `read4`, implement a method `read` to read `n` characters. Your method `read` may be **called multiple times**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Method read4:**_x000D_
_x000D_
The API `read4` reads **four consecutive characters** from `file`, then writes those characters into the buffer array `buf4`._x000D_
_x000D_
The return value is the number of actual characters read._x000D_
_x000D_
Note that `read4()` has its own file pointer, much like `FILE *fp` in C._x000D_
_x000D_
**Definition of read4:**_x000D_
_x000D_
    Parameter:  char\[\] buf4_x000D_
    Returns:    int_x000D_
_x000D_
buf4\[\] is a destination, not a source. The results from read4 will be copied to buf4\[\]._x000D_
_x000D_
Below is a high-level example of how `read4` works:_x000D_
_x000D_
File file( "abcde `"); // File is  "`abcde `", initially file pointer (fp) points to 'a' char[] buf4 = new char[4]; // Create buffer with enough space to store characters read4(buf4); // read4 returns 4. Now buf4 =  "abcd ", fp points to 'e' read4(buf4); // read4 returns 1. Now buf4 =  "e ", fp points to end of file read4(buf4); // read4 returns 0. Now buf4 =  " ", fp points to end of file`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Method read:**_x000D_
_x000D_
By using the `read4` method, implement the method read that reads `n` characters from `file` and store it in the buffer array `buf`. Consider that you cannot manipulate `file` directly._x000D_
_x000D_
The return value is the number of actual characters read._x000D_
_x000D_
**Definition of read:**_x000D_
_x000D_
    Parameters:    char\[\] buf, int n_x000D_
    Returns:    int_x000D_
_x000D_
buf\[\] is a destination, not a source. You will need to write the results to buf\[\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Consider that you cannot manipulate the file directly. The file is only accessible for `read4` but not for `read`._x000D_
*   The read function may be **called multiple times**._x000D_
*   Please remember to **RESET** your class variables declared in Solution, as static/class variables are persisted across multiple test cases. Please see [here](https://leetcode.com/faq/) for more details._x000D_
*   You may assume the destination buffer array, `buf`, is guaranteed to have enough space for storing `n` characters._x000D_
*   It is guaranteed that in a given test case the same buffer `buf` is called by `read`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** file =  "abc ", queries = \[1,2,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2,0\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The test case represents the following scenario:_x000D_
File file( "abc ");_x000D_
Solution sol;_x000D_
sol.read(buf, 1); // After calling your read method, buf should contain  "a ". We read a total of 1 character from the file, so return 1._x000D_
sol.read(buf, 2); // Now buf should contain  "bc ". We read a total of 2 characters from the file, so return 2._x000D_
sol.read(buf, 1); // We have reached the end of file, no more characters can be read. So return 0._x000D_
Assume buf is allocated and guaranteed to have enough space for storing all characters from the file._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** file =  "abc ", queries = \[4,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,0\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The test case represents the following scenario:_x000D_
File file( "abc ");_x000D_
Solution sol;_x000D_
sol.read(buf, 4); // After calling your read method, buf should contain  "abc ". We read a total of 3 characters from the file, so return 3._x000D_
sol.read(buf, 1); // We have reached the end of file, no more characters can be read. So return 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= file.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `file` consist of English letters and digits._x000D_
*   `1 <= queries.length <= 10`_x000D_
*   `1 <= queries[i] <= 500`

title: Longest Substring with At Most Two Distinct Characters
content:
Given a string `s`, return _the length of the longest_ _substring_ _that contains at most **two distinct characters**_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "eceba "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** The substring is  "ece " which its length is 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "ccaabbb "_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** The substring is  "aabbb " which its length is 5._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of English letters.

title: Intersection of Two Linked Lists
content:
Given the heads of two singly linked-lists `headA` and `headB`, return _the node at which the two lists intersect_. If the two linked lists have no intersection at all, return `null`._x000D_
_x000D_
For example, the following two linked lists begin to intersect at node `c1`:_x000D_
_x000D_
The test cases are generated such that there are no cycles anywhere in the entire linked structure._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that the linked lists must **retain their original structure** after the function returns._x000D_
_x000D_
**Custom Judge:**_x000D_
_x000D_
The inputs to the **judge** are given as follows (your program is **not** given these inputs):_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `intersectVal` - The value of the node where the intersection occurs. This is `0` if there is no intersected node._x000D_
*   `listA` - The first linked list._x000D_
*   `listB` - The second linked list._x000D_
*   `skipA` - The number of nodes to skip ahead in `listA` (starting from the head) to get to the intersected node._x000D_
*   `skipB` - The number of nodes to skip ahead in `listB` (starting from the head) to get to the intersected node._x000D_
_x000D_
The judge will then create the linked structure based on these inputs and pass the two heads, `headA` and `headB` to your program. If you correctly return the intersected node, then your solution will be **accepted**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** intersectVal = 8, listA = \[4,1,8,4,5\], listB = \[5,6,1,8,4,5\], skipA = 2, skipB = 3_x000D_
**Output:** Intersected at '8'_x000D_
**Explanation:** The intersected node's value is 8 (note that this must not be 0 if the two lists intersect)._x000D_
From the head of A, it reads as \[4,1,8,4,5\]. From the head of B, it reads as \[5,6,1,8,4,5\]. There are 2 nodes before the intersected node in A; There are 3 nodes before the intersected node in B._x000D_
- Note that the intersected node's value is not 1 because the nodes with value 1 in A and B (2nd node in A and 3rd node in B) are different node references. In other words, they point to two different locations in memory, while the nodes with value 8 in A and B (3rd node in A and 4th node in B) point to the same location in memory._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** intersectVal = 2, listA = \[1,9,1,2,4\], listB = \[3,2,4\], skipA = 3, skipB = 1_x000D_
**Output:** Intersected at '2'_x000D_
**Explanation:** The intersected node's value is 2 (note that this must not be 0 if the two lists intersect)._x000D_
From the head of A, it reads as \[1,9,1,2,4\]. From the head of B, it reads as \[3,2,4\]. There are 3 nodes before the intersected node in A; There are 1 node before the intersected node in B._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** intersectVal = 0, listA = \[2,6,4\], listB = \[1,5\], skipA = 3, skipB = 2_x000D_
**Output:** No intersection_x000D_
**Explanation:** From the head of A, it reads as \[2,6,4\]. From the head of B, it reads as \[1,5\]. Since the two lists do not intersect, intersectVal must be 0, while skipA and skipB can be arbitrary values._x000D_
Explanation: The two lists do not intersect, so return null._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes of `listA` is in the `m`._x000D_
*   The number of nodes of `listB` is in the `n`._x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= skipA < m`_x000D_
*   `0 <= skipB < n`_x000D_
*   `intersectVal` is `0` if `listA` and `listB` do not intersect._x000D_
*   `intersectVal == listA[skipA] == listB[skipB]` if `listA` and `listB` intersect._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you write a solution that runs in `O(m + n)` time and use only `O(1)` memory?

title: One Edit Distance
content:
Given two strings `s` and `t`, return `true` if they are both one edit distance apart, otherwise return `false`._x000D_
_x000D_
A string `s` is said to be one distance apart from a string `t` if you can:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Insert **exactly one** character into `s` to get `t`._x000D_
*   Delete **exactly one** character from `s` to get `t`._x000D_
*   Replace **exactly one** character of `s` with **a different character** to get `t`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "ab ", t =  "acb "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can insert 'c' into s to get t._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  " ", t =  " "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** We cannot get t from s by only one step._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= s.length, t.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `s` and `t` consist of lowercase letters, uppercase letters, and digits.

title: Find Peak Element
content:
A peak element is an element that is strictly greater than its neighbors._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`, find a peak element, and return its index. If the array contains multiple peaks, return the index to **any of the peaks**._x000D_
_x000D_
You may imagine that `nums[-1] = nums[n] = -∞`. In other words, an element is always considered to be strictly greater than a neighbor that is outside the array._x000D_
_x000D_
You must write an algorithm that runs in `O(log n)` time._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** 3 is a peak element and your function should return the index number 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,1,3,5,6,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** Your function can return either index number 1 where the peak element is 2, or index number 5 where the peak element is 6._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `-231 <= nums[i] <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
*   `nums[i] != nums[i + 1]` for all valid `i`.

title: Missing Ranges
content:
You are given an inclusive range `[lower, upper]` and a **sorted unique** integer array `nums`, where all elements are in the inclusive range._x000D_
_x000D_
A number `x` is considered **missing** if `x` is in the range `[lower, upper]` and `x` is not in `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **smallest sorted** list of ranges that **cover every missing number exactly**_. That is, no element of `nums` is in any of the ranges, and each missing number is in one of the ranges._x000D_
_x000D_
Each range `[a,b]` in the list should be output as:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `"a->b "` if `a != b`_x000D_
*   `"a "` if `a == b`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0,1,3,50,75\], lower = 0, upper = 99_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "2 ", "4->49 ", "51->74 ", "76->99 "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The ranges are:_x000D_
\[2,2\] -->  "2 "_x000D_
\[4,49\] -->  "4->49 "_x000D_
\[51,74\] -->  "51->74 "_x000D_
\[76,99\] -->  "76->99 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[-1\], lower = -1, upper = -1_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are no missing ranges since there are no missing numbers._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `-109 <= lower <= upper <= 109`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `lower <= nums[i] <= upper`_x000D_
*   All the values of `nums` are **unique**.

title: Maximum Gap
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, return _the maximum difference between two successive elements in its sorted form_. If the array contains less than two elements, return `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
You must write an algorithm that runs in linear time and uses linear extra space._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[3,6,9,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** The sorted form of the array is \[1,3,6,9\], either (3,6) or (6,9) has the maximum difference 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[10\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The array contains less than 2 elements, therefore return 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums[i] <= 109`

title: Compare Version Numbers
content:
Given two version numbers, `version1` and `version2`, compare them._x000D_
_x000D_
Version numbers consist of **one or more revisions** joined by a dot `'.'`. Each revision consists of **digits** and may contain leading **zeros**. Every revision contains **at least one character**. Revisions are **0-indexed from left to right**, with the leftmost revision being revision 0, the next revision being revision 1, and so on. For example `2.5.33` and `0.1` are valid version numbers._x000D_
_x000D_
To compare version numbers, compare their revisions in **left-to-right order**. Revisions are compared using their **integer value ignoring any leading zeros**. This means that revisions `1` and `001` are considered **equal**. If a version number does not specify a revision at an index, then **treat the revision as `0`**. For example, version `1.0` is less than version `1.1` because their revision 0s are the same, but their revision 1s are `0` and `1` respectively, and `0 < 1`._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return the following:__x000D_
_x000D_
*   If `version1 < version2`, return `-1`._x000D_
*   If `version1 > version2`, return `1`._x000D_
*   Otherwise, return `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** version1 =  "1.01 ", version2 =  "1.001 "_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** Ignoring leading zeroes, both  "01 " and  "001 " represent the same integer  "1 "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** version1 =  "1.0 ", version2 =  "1.0.0 "_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** version1 does not specify revision 2, which means it is treated as  "0 "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** version1 =  "0.1 ", version2 =  "1.1 "_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** version1's revision 0 is  "0 ", while version2's revision 0 is  "1 ". 0 < 1, so version1 < version2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= version1.length, version2.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `version1` and `version2` only contain digits and `'.'`._x000D_
*   `version1` and `version2` **are valid version numbers**._x000D_
*   All the given revisions in `version1` and `version2` can be stored in a **32-bit integer**.

title: Fraction to Recurring Decimal
content:
Given two integers representing the `numerator` and `denominator` of a fraction, return _the fraction in string format_._x000D_
_x000D_
If the fractional part is repeating, enclose the repeating part in parentheses._x000D_
_x000D_
If multiple answers are possible, return **any of them**._x000D_
_x000D_
It is **guaranteed** that the length of the answer string is less than `104` for all the given inputs._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numerator = 1, denominator = 2_x000D_
**Output:**  "0.5 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numerator = 2, denominator = 1_x000D_
**Output:**  "2 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numerator = 4, denominator = 333_x000D_
**Output:**  "0.(012) "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `-231 <= numerator, denominator <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
*   `denominator != 0`

title: Two Sum II - Input Array Is Sorted
content:
Given a **1-indexed** array of integers `numbers` that is already **_sorted in non-decreasing order_**, find two numbers such that they add up to a specific `target` number. Let these two numbers be `numbers[index1]` and `numbers[index2]` where `1 <= index1 < index2 <= numbers.length`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the indices of the two numbers,_ `index1` _and_ `index2`_, **added by one** as an integer array_ `[index1, index2]` _of length 2.__x000D_
_x000D_
The tests are generated such that there is **exactly one solution**. You **may not** use the same element twice._x000D_
_x000D_
Your solution must use only constant extra space._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numbers = \[2,7,11,15\], target = 9_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The sum of 2 and 7 is 9. Therefore, index1 = 1, index2 = 2. We return \[1, 2\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numbers = \[2,3,4\], target = 6_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,3\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The sum of 2 and 4 is 6. Therefore index1 = 1, index2 = 3. We return \[1, 3\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** numbers = \[\-1,0\], target = -1_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The sum of -1 and 0 is -1. Therefore index1 = 1, index2 = 2. We return \[1, 2\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `2 <= numbers.length <= 3 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= numbers[i] <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `numbers` is sorted in **non-decreasing order**._x000D_
*   `-1000 <= target <= 1000`_x000D_
*   The tests are generated such that there is **exactly one solution**.

title: Excel Sheet Column Title
content:
Given an integer `columnNumber`, return _its corresponding column title as it appears in an Excel sheet_._x000D_
_x000D_
For example:_x000D_
_x000D_
A -> 1_x000D_
B -> 2_x000D_
C -> 3_x000D_
..._x000D_
Z -> 26_x000D_
AA -> 27_x000D_
AB -> 28 _x000D_
..._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnNumber = 1_x000D_
**Output:**  "A "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnNumber = 28_x000D_
**Output:**  "AB "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnNumber = 701_x000D_
**Output:**  "ZY "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= columnNumber <= 231 - 1`

title: Majority Element
content:
Given an array `nums` of size `n`, return _the majority element_._x000D_
_x000D_
The majority element is the element that appears more than `⌊n / 2⌋` times. You may assume that the majority element always exists in the array._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[3,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,2,1,1,1,2,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == nums.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= nums[i] <= 109`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow-up:** Could you solve the problem in linear time and in `O(1)` space?

title: Two Sum III - Data structure design
content:
Design a data structure that accepts a stream of integers and checks if it has a pair of integers that sum up to a particular value._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `TwoSum` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `TwoSum()` Initializes the `TwoSum` object, with an empty array initially._x000D_
*   `void add(int number)` Adds `number` to the data structure._x000D_
*   `boolean find(int value)` Returns `true` if there exists any pair of numbers whose sum is equal to `value`, otherwise, it returns `false`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "TwoSum ",  "add ",  "add ",  "add ",  "find ",  "find "\]_x000D_
\[\[\], \[1\], \[3\], \[5\], \[4\], \[7\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, null, null, null, true, false\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
TwoSum twoSum = new TwoSum();_x000D_
twoSum.add(1);   // \[\] --> \[1\]_x000D_
twoSum.add(3);   // \[1\] --> \[1,3\]_x000D_
twoSum.add(5);   // \[1,3\] --> \[1,3,5\]_x000D_
twoSum.find(4);  // 1 + 3 = 4, return true_x000D_
twoSum.find(7);  // No two integers sum up to 7, return false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `-105 <= number <= 105`_x000D_
*   `-231 <= value <= 231 - 1`_x000D_
*   At most `104` calls will be made to `add` and `find`.

title: Excel Sheet Column Number
content:
Given a string `columnTitle` that represents the column title as appears in an Excel sheet, return _its corresponding column number_._x000D_
_x000D_
For example:_x000D_
_x000D_
A -> 1_x000D_
B -> 2_x000D_
C -> 3_x000D_
..._x000D_
Z -> 26_x000D_
AA -> 27_x000D_
AB -> 28 _x000D_
..._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnTitle =  "A "_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnTitle =  "AB "_x000D_
**Output:** 28_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** columnTitle =  "ZY "_x000D_
**Output:** 701_x000D_
_x000D_
