title: Permutation in String
content:
Given two strings `s1` and `s2`, return `true` _if_ `s2` _contains a permutation of_ `s1`_, or_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
In other words, return `true` if one of `s1`'s permutations is the substring of `s2`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "ab ", s2 =  "eidbaooo "_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** s2 contains one permutation of s1 ( "ba ")._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s1 =  "ab ", s2 =  "eidboaoo "_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s1.length, s2.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `s1` and `s2` consist of lowercase English letters.

title: Maximum Vacation Days
content:
LeetCode wants to give one of its best employees the option to travel among `n` cities to collect algorithm problems. But all work and no play makes Jack a dull boy, you could take vacations in some particular cities and weeks. Your job is to schedule the traveling to maximize the number of vacation days you could take, but there are certain rules and restrictions you need to follow._x000D_
_x000D_
Rules and restrictions:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  You can only travel among `n` cities, represented by indexes from `0` to `n - 1`. Initially, you are in the city indexed `0` on **Monday**._x000D_
2.  The cities are connected by flights. The flights are represented as an `n x n` matrix (not necessarily symmetrical), called `flights` representing the airline status from the city `i` to the city `j`. If there is no flight from the city `i` to the city `j`, `flights[i][j] == 0`; Otherwise, `flights[i][j] == 1`. Also, `flights[i][i] == 0` for all `i`._x000D_
3.  You totally have `k` weeks (each week has **seven days**) to travel. You can only take flights at most once per day and can only take flights on each week's Monday morning. Since flight time is so short, we do not consider the impact of flight time._x000D_
4.  For each city, you can only have restricted vacation days in different weeks, given an `n x k` matrix called `days` representing this relationship. For the value of `days[i][j]`, it represents the maximum days you could take a vacation in the city `i` in the week `j`._x000D_
5.  You could stay in a city beyond the number of vacation days, but you should work on the extra days, which will not be counted as vacation days._x000D_
6.  If you fly from city `A` to city `B` and take the vacation on that day, the deduction towards vacation days will count towards the vacation days of city `B` in that week._x000D_
7.  We do not consider the impact of flight hours on the calculation of vacation days._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the two matrices `flights` and `days`, return _the maximum vacation days you could take during_ `k` _weeks_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flights = \[\[0,1,1\],\[1,0,1\],\[1,1,0\]\], days = \[\[1,3,1\],\[6,0,3\],\[3,3,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
One of the best strategies is:_x000D_
1st week : fly from city 0 to city 1 on Monday, and play 6 days and work 1 day._x000D_
(Although you start at city 0, we could also fly to and start at other cities since it is Monday.)_x000D_
2nd week : fly from city 1 to city 2 on Monday, and play 3 days and work 4 days._x000D_
3rd week : stay at city 2, and play 3 days and work 4 days._x000D_
Ans = 6 + 3 + 3 = 12._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flights = \[\[0,0,0\],\[0,0,0\],\[0,0,0\]\], days = \[\[1,1,1\],\[7,7,7\],\[7,7,7\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Since there are no flights that enable you to move to another city, you have to stay at city 0 for the whole 3 weeks. _x000D_
For each week, you only have one day to play and six days to work._x000D_
So the maximum number of vacation days is 3._x000D_
Ans = 1 + 1 + 1 = 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flights = \[\[0,1,1\],\[1,0,1\],\[1,1,0\]\], days = \[\[7,0,0\],\[0,7,0\],\[0,0,7\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 21_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
One of the best strategies is:_x000D_
1st week : stay at city 0, and play 7 days._x000D_
2nd week : fly from city 0 to city 1 on Monday, and play 7 days._x000D_
3rd week : fly from city 1 to city 2 on Monday, and play 7 days._x000D_
Ans = 7 + 7 + 7 = 21_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == flights.length`_x000D_
*   `n == flights[i].length`_x000D_
*   `n == days.length`_x000D_
*   `k == days[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n, k <= 100`_x000D_
*   `flights[i][j]` is either `0` or `1`._x000D_
*   `0 <= days[i][j] <= 7`

title: Subtree of Another Tree
content:
Given the roots of two binary trees `root` and `subRoot`, return `true` if there is a subtree of `root` with the same structure and node values of `subRoot` and `false` otherwise._x000D_
_x000D_
A subtree of a binary tree `tree` is a tree that consists of a node in `tree` and all of this node's descendants. The tree `tree` could also be considered as a subtree of itself._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[3,4,5,1,2\], subRoot = \[4,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[3,4,5,1,2,null,null,null,null,0\], subRoot = \[4,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the `root` tree is in the range `[1, 2000]`._x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the `subRoot` tree is in the range `[1, 1000]`._x000D_
*   `-104 <= root.val <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= subRoot.val <= 104`

title: Squirrel Simulation
content:
You are given two integers `height` and `width` representing a garden of size `height x width`. You are also given:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   an array `tree` where `tree = [treer, treec]` is the position of the tree in the garden,_x000D_
*   an array `squirrel` where `squirrel = [squirrelr, squirrelc]` is the position of the squirrel in the garden,_x000D_
*   and an array `nuts` where `nuts[i] = [nutir, nutic]` is the position of the `ith` nut in the garden._x000D_
_x000D_
The squirrel can only take at most one nut at one time and can move in four directions: up, down, left, and right, to the adjacent cell._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimal distance** for the squirrel to collect all the nuts and put them under the tree one by one_._x000D_
_x000D_
The **distance** is the number of moves._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** height = 5, width = 7, tree = \[2,2\], squirrel = \[4,4\], nuts = \[\[3,0\], \[2,5\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
**Explanation:** The squirrel should go to the nut at \[2, 5\] first to achieve a minimal distance._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** height = 1, width = 3, tree = \[0,1\], squirrel = \[0,0\], nuts = \[\[0,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= height, width <= 100`_x000D_
*   `tree.length == 2`_x000D_
*   `squirrel.length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nuts.length <= 5000`_x000D_
*   `nuts[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `0 <= treer, squirrelr, nutir <= height`_x000D_
*   `0 <= treec, squirrelc, nutic <= width`

title: Distribute Candies
content:
Alice has `n` candies, where the `ith` candy is of type `candyType[i]`. Alice noticed that she started to gain weight, so she visited a doctor._x000D_
_x000D_
The doctor advised Alice to only eat `n / 2` of the candies she has (`n` is always even). Alice likes her candies very much, and she wants to eat the maximum number of different types of candies while still following the doctor's advice._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the integer array `candyType` of length `n`, return _the **maximum** number of different types of candies she can eat if she only eats_ `n / 2` _of them_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** candyType = \[1,1,2,2,3,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice can only eat 6 / 2 = 3 candies. Since there are only 3 types, she can eat one of each type._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** candyType = \[1,1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice can only eat 4 / 2 = 2 candies. Whether she eats types \[1,2\], \[1,3\], or \[2,3\], she still can only eat 2 different types._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** candyType = \[6,6,6,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice can only eat 4 / 2 = 2 candies. Even though she can eat 2 candies, she only has 1 type._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == candyType.length`_x000D_
*   `2 <= n <= 104`_x000D_
*   `n` is even._x000D_
*   `-105 <= candyType[i] <= 105`

title: Out of Boundary Paths
content:
There is an `m x n` grid with a ball. The ball is initially at the position `[startRow, startColumn]`. You are allowed to move the ball to one of the four adjacent cells in the grid (possibly out of the grid crossing the grid boundary). You can apply **at most** `maxMove` moves to the ball._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the five integers `m`, `n`, `maxMove`, `startRow`, `startColumn`, return the number of paths to move the ball out of the grid boundary. Since the answer can be very large, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** m = 2, n = 2, maxMove = 2, startRow = 0, startColumn = 0_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** m = 1, n = 3, maxMove = 3, startRow = 0, startColumn = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 50`_x000D_
*   `0 <= maxMove <= 50`_x000D_
*   `0 <= startRow < m`_x000D_
*   `0 <= startColumn < n`

title: Shortest Unsorted Continuous Subarray
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, you need to find one **continuous subarray** that if you only sort this subarray in ascending order, then the whole array will be sorted in ascending order._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the shortest such subarray and output its length_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,6,4,8,10,9,15\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** You need to sort \[6, 4, 8, 10, 9\] in ascending order to make the whole array sorted in ascending order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-105 <= nums[i] <= 105`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Can you solve it in `O(n)` time complexity?

title: Kill Process
content:
You have `n` processes forming a rooted tree structure. You are given two integer arrays `pid` and `ppid`, where `pid[i]` is the ID of the `ith` process and `ppid[i]` is the ID of the `ith` process's parent process._x000D_
_x000D_
Each process has only **one parent process** but may have multiple children processes. Only one process has `ppid[i] = 0`, which means this process has **no parent process** (the root of the tree)._x000D_
_x000D_
When a process is **killed**, all of its children processes will also be killed._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an integer `kill` representing the ID of a process you want to kill, return _a list of the IDs of the processes that will be killed. You may return the answer in **any order**.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** pid = \[1,3,10,5\], ppid = \[3,0,5,3\], kill = 5_x000D_
**Output:** \[5,10\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The processes colored in red are the processes that should be killed._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** pid = \[1\], ppid = \[0\], kill = 1_x000D_
**Output:** \[1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == pid.length`_x000D_
*   `n == ppid.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= pid[i] <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   `0 <= ppid[i] <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   Only one process has no parent._x000D_
*   All the values of `pid` are **unique**._x000D_
*   `kill` is **guaranteed** to be in `pid`.

title: Delete Operation for Two Strings
content:
Given two strings `word1` and `word2`, return _the minimum number of **steps** required to make_ `word1` _and_ `word2` _the same_._x000D_
_x000D_
In one **step**, you can delete exactly one character in either string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** word1 =  "sea ", word2 =  "eat "_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** You need one step to make  "sea " to  "ea " and another step to make  "eat " to  "ea "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** word1 =  "leetcode ", word2 =  "etco "_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= word1.length, word2.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `word1` and `word2` consist of only lowercase English letters.

title: Erect the Fence
content:
You are given an array `trees` where `trees[i] = [xi, yi]` represents the location of a tree in the garden._x000D_
_x000D_
Fence the entire garden using the minimum length of rope, as it is expensive. The garden is well-fenced only if **all the trees are enclosed**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the coordinates of trees that are exactly located on the fence perimeter_. You may return the answer in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** trees = \[\[1,1\],\[2,2\],\[2,0\],\[2,4\],\[3,3\],\[4,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1,1\],\[2,0\],\[4,2\],\[3,3\],\[2,4\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** All the trees will be on the perimeter of the fence except the tree at \[2, 2\], which will be inside the fence._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** trees = \[\[1,2\],\[2,2\],\[4,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[4,2\],\[2,2\],\[1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The fence forms a line that passes through all the trees._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= trees.length <= 3000`_x000D_
*   `trees[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `0 <= xi, yi <= 100`_x000D_
*   All the given positions are **unique**.

title: Design In-Memory File System
content:
Design a data structure that simulates an in-memory file system._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the FileSystem class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `FileSystem()` Initializes the object of the system._x000D_
*   `List ls(String path)`_x000D_
    _x000D_
    *   If `path` is a file path, returns a list that only contains this file's name._x000D_
    *   If `path` is a directory path, returns the list of file and directory names **in this directory**._x000D_
    _x000D_
    The answer should in **lexicographic order**._x000D_
*   `void mkdir(String path)` Makes a new directory according to the given `path`. The given directory path does not exist. If the middle directories in the path do not exist, you should create them as well._x000D_
*   `void addContentToFile(String filePath, String content)`_x000D_
    *   If `filePath` does not exist, creates that file containing given `content`._x000D_
    *   If `filePath` already exists, appends the given `content` to original content._x000D_
*   `String readContentFromFile(String filePath)` Returns the content in the file at `filePath`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "FileSystem ",  "ls ",  "mkdir ",  "addContentToFile ",  "ls ",  "readContentFromFile "\]_x000D_
\[\[\], \[ "/ "\], \[ "/a/b/c "\], \[ "/a/b/c/d ",  "hello "\], \[ "/ "\], \[ "/a/b/c/d "\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, \[\], null, null, \[ "a "\],  "hello "\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
FileSystem fileSystem = new FileSystem();_x000D_
fileSystem.ls( "/ ");                         // return \[\]_x000D_
fileSystem.mkdir( "/a/b/c ");_x000D_
fileSystem.addContentToFile( "/a/b/c/d ",  "hello ");_x000D_
fileSystem.ls( "/ ");                         // return \[ "a "\]_x000D_
fileSystem.readContentFromFile( "/a/b/c/d "); // return  "hello "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= path.length, filePath.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `path` and `filePath` are absolute paths which begin with `'/'` and do not end with `'/'` except that the path is just `"/ "`._x000D_
*   You can assume that all directory names and file names only contain lowercase letters, and the same names will not exist in the same directory._x000D_
*   You can assume that all operations will be passed valid parameters, and users will not attempt to retrieve file content or list a directory or file that does not exist._x000D_
*   `1 <= content.length <= 50`_x000D_
*   At most `300` calls will be made to `ls`, `mkdir`, `addContentToFile`, and `readContentFromFile`.

title: N-ary Tree Preorder Traversal
content:
Given the `root` of an n-ary tree, return _the preorder traversal of its nodes' values_._x000D_
_x000D_
Nary-Tree input serialization is represented in their level order traversal. Each group of children is separated by the null value (See examples)_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,3,2,4,null,5,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,3,5,6,2,4\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,2,3,4,5,null,null,6,7,null,8,null,9,10,null,null,11,null,12,null,13,null,null,14\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2,3,6,7,11,14,4,8,12,5,9,13,10\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[0, 104]`._x000D_
*   `0 <= Node.val <= 104`_x000D_
*   The height of the n-ary tree is less than or equal to `1000`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Recursive solution is trivial, could you do it iteratively?

title: N-ary Tree Postorder Traversal
content:
Given the `root` of an n-ary tree, return _the postorder traversal of its nodes' values_._x000D_
_x000D_
Nary-Tree input serialization is represented in their level order traversal. Each group of children is separated by the null value (See examples)_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,3,2,4,null,5,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[5,6,3,2,4,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,2,3,4,5,null,null,6,7,null,8,null,9,10,null,null,11,null,12,null,13,null,null,14\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,6,14,11,7,3,12,8,4,13,9,10,5,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[0, 104]`._x000D_
*   `0 <= Node.val <= 104`_x000D_
*   The height of the n-ary tree is less than or equal to `1000`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Recursive solution is trivial, could you do it iteratively?

title: Tag Validator
content:
Given a string representing a code snippet, implement a tag validator to parse the code and return whether it is valid._x000D_
_x000D_
A code snippet is valid if all the following rules hold:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  The code must be wrapped in a **valid closed tag**. Otherwise, the code is invalid._x000D_
2.  A **closed tag** (not necessarily valid) has exactly the following format : `TAG_CONTENT`. Among them, is the start tag, and is the end tag. The TAG\_NAME in start and end tags should be the same. A closed tag is **valid** if and only if the TAG\_NAME and TAG\_CONTENT are valid._x000D_
3.  A **valid** `TAG_NAME` only contain **upper-case letters**, and has length in range \[1,9\]. Otherwise, the `TAG_NAME` is **invalid**._x000D_
4.  A **valid** `TAG_CONTENT` may contain other **valid closed tags**, **cdata** and any characters (see note1) **EXCEPT** unmatched `<`, unmatched start and end tag, and unmatched or closed tags with invalid TAG\_NAME. Otherwise, the `TAG_CONTENT` is **invalid**._x000D_
5.  A start tag is unmatched if no end tag exists with the same TAG\_NAME, and vice versa. However, you also need to consider the issue of unbalanced when tags are nested._x000D_
6.  A `<` is unmatched if you cannot find a subsequent `>`. And when you find a `<` or ``, all the subsequent characters until the next `>` should be parsed as TAG_NAME (not necessarily valid).``_x000D_
``` *   The cdata has the following format : . The range of `CDATA_CONTENT` is defined as the characters between ``and the **first subsequent** `]]>`.`` ``*   `CDATA_CONTENT` may contain **any characters**. The function of cdata is to forbid the validator to parse `CDATA_CONTENT`, so even it has some characters that can be parsed as tag (no matter valid or invalid), you should treat it as **regular characters**.`` ```_x000D_
_x000D_
``` ``  **Example 1:**  **Input:** code =  "  This is the first line ]]>   " **Output:** true **Explanation:**  The code is wrapped in a closed tag :    and   .  The TAG_NAME is valid, the TAG_CONTENT consists of some characters and cdata.  Although CDATA_CONTENT has an unmatched start tag with invalid TAG_NAME, it should be considered as plain text, not parsed as a tag. So TAG_CONTENT is valid, and then the code is valid. Thus return true.  **Example 2:**  **Input:** code =  "  >>  ![cdata[]] ]>]]>]]>>]   " **Output:** true **Explanation:** We first separate the code into : start_tag|tag_content|end_tag. start_tag -> ** "**   **"** end_tag -> ** "**   **"** tag_content could also be separated into : text1|cdata|text2. text1 -> ** ">>  ![cdata[]]  "** cdata -> ** "]>]]> "**, where the CDATA_CONTENT is ** "**  **]> "** text2 -> ** "]]>>] "** The reason why start_tag is NOT ** "**  **>> "** is because of the rule 6. The reason why cdata is NOT ** "]>]]>]]> "** is because of the rule 7.  **Example 3:**  **Input:** code =  "    " **Output:** false **Explanation:** Unbalanced. If  " " is closed, then  " **" must be unmatched, and vice versa.**  **  **Constraints:**  *   `1 <= code.length <= 500` *   `code` consists of English letters, digits, `'<'`, `'>'`, `'/'`, `'!'`, `'['`, `']'`, `'.'`, and `' '`.  **`` ```

title: Fraction Addition and Subtraction
content:
Given a string `expression` representing an expression of fraction addition and subtraction, return the calculation result in string format._x000D_
_x000D_
The final result should be an [irreducible fraction](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irreducible_fraction). If your final result is an integer, change it to the format of a fraction that has a denominator `1`. So in this case, `2` should be converted to `2/1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** expression =  "-1/2+1/2 "_x000D_
**Output:**  "0/1 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** expression =  "-1/2+1/2+1/3 "_x000D_
**Output:**  "1/3 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** expression =  "1/3-1/2 "_x000D_
**Output:**  "-1/6 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The input string only contains `'0'` to `'9'`, `'/'`, `'+'` and `'-'`. So does the output._x000D_
*   Each fraction (input and output) has the format `±numerator/denominator`. If the first input fraction or the output is positive, then `'+'` will be omitted._x000D_
*   The input only contains valid **irreducible fractions**, where the **numerator** and **denominator** of each fraction will always be in the range `[1, 10]`. If the denominator is `1`, it means this fraction is actually an integer in a fraction format defined above._x000D_
*   The number of given fractions will be in the range `[1, 10]`._x000D_
*   The numerator and denominator of the **final result** are guaranteed to be valid and in the range of **32-bit** int.

title: Valid Square
content:
Given the coordinates of four points in 2D space `p1`, `p2`, `p3` and `p4`, return `true` _if the four points construct a square_._x000D_
_x000D_
The coordinate of a point `pi` is represented as `[xi, yi]`. The input is **not** given in any order._x000D_
_x000D_
A **valid square** has four equal sides with positive length and four equal angles (90-degree angles)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** p1 = \[0,0\], p2 = \[1,1\], p3 = \[1,0\], p4 = \[0,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** p1 = \[0,0\], p2 = \[1,1\], p3 = \[1,0\], p4 = \[0,12\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** p1 = \[1,0\], p2 = \[-1,0\], p3 = \[0,1\], p4 = \[0,-1\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `p1.length == p2.length == p3.length == p4.length == 2`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= xi, yi <= 104`

title: Longest Harmonious Subsequence
content:
We define a harmonious array as an array where the difference between its maximum value and its minimum value is **exactly** `1`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an integer array `nums`, return _the length of its longest harmonious subsequence among all its possible subsequences_._x000D_
_x000D_
A **subsequence** of array is a sequence that can be derived from the array by deleting some or no elements without changing the order of the remaining elements._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,3,2,2,5,2,3,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest harmonious subsequence is \[3,2,2,2,3\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,1,1,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 2 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= nums[i] <= 109`

title: Range Addition II
content:
You are given an `m x n` matrix `M` initialized with all `0`'s and an array of operations `ops`, where `ops[i] = [ai, bi]` means `M[x][y]` should be incremented by one for all `0 <= x < ai` and `0 <= y < bi`._x000D_
_x000D_
Count and return _the number of maximum integers in the matrix after performing all the operations_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** m = 3, n = 3, ops = \[\[2,2\],\[3,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** The maximum integer in M is 2, and there are four of it in M. So return 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** m = 3, n = 3, ops = \[\[2,2\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\],\[2,2\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\],\[2,2\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\],\[3,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** m = 3, n = 3, ops = \[\]_x000D_
**Output:** 9_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 4 * 104`_x000D_
*   `0 <= ops.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `ops[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= ai <= m`_x000D_
*   `1 <= bi <= n`

title: Minimum Index Sum of Two Lists
content:
Given two arrays of strings `list1` and `list2`, find the **common strings with the least index sum**._x000D_
_x000D_
A **common string** is a string that appeared in both `list1` and `list2`._x000D_
_x000D_
A **common string with the least index sum** is a common string such that if it appeared at `list1[i]` and `list2[j]` then `i + j` should be the minimum value among all the other **common strings**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _all the **common strings with the least index sum**_. Return the answer in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** list1 = \[ "Shogun ", "Tapioca Express ", "Burger King ", "KFC "\], list2 = \[ "Piatti ", "The Grill at Torrey Pines ", "Hungry Hunter Steakhouse ", "Shogun "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "Shogun "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only common string is  "Shogun "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** list1 = \[ "Shogun ", "Tapioca Express ", "Burger King ", "KFC "\], list2 = \[ "KFC ", "Shogun ", "Burger King "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "Shogun "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The common string with the least index sum is  "Shogun " with index sum = (0 + 1) = 1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** list1 = \[ "happy ", "sad ", "good "\], list2 = \[ "sad ", "happy ", "good "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "sad ", "happy "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are three common strings:_x000D_
 "happy " with index sum = (0 + 1) = 1._x000D_
 "sad " with index sum = (1 + 0) = 1._x000D_
 "good " with index sum = (2 + 2) = 4._x000D_
The strings with the least index sum are  "sad " and  "happy "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= list1.length, list2.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= list1[i].length, list2[i].length <= 30`_x000D_
*   `list1[i]` and `list2[i]` consist of spaces `' '` and English letters._x000D_
*   All the strings of `list1` are **unique**._x000D_
*   All the strings of `list2` are **unique**._x000D_
*   There is at least a common string between `list1` and `list2`.

title: Non-negative Integers without Consecutive Ones
content:
Given a positive integer `n`, return the number of the integers in the range `[0, n]` whose binary representations **do not** contain consecutive ones._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 5_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Here are the non-negative integers <= 5 with their corresponding binary representations:_x000D_
0 : 0_x000D_
1 : 1_x000D_
2 : 10_x000D_
3 : 11_x000D_
4 : 100_x000D_
5 : 101_x000D_
Among them, only integer 3 disobeys the rule (two consecutive ones) and the other 5 satisfy the rule. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 109`

title: Design Compressed String Iterator
content:
Design and implement a data structure for a compressed string iterator. The given compressed string will be in the form of each letter followed by a positive integer representing the number of this letter existing in the original uncompressed string._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the StringIterator class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `next()` Returns **the next character** if the original string still has uncompressed characters, otherwise returns a **white space**._x000D_
*   `hasNext()` Returns true if there is any letter needs to be uncompressed in the original string, otherwise returns `false`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "StringIterator ",  "next ",  "next ",  "next ",  "next ",  "next ",  "next ",  "hasNext ",  "next ",  "hasNext "\]_x000D_
\[\[ "L1e2t1C1o1d1e1 "\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null,  "L ",  "e ",  "e ",  "t ",  "C ",  "o ", true,  "d ", true\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
StringIterator stringIterator = new StringIterator( "L1e2t1C1o1d1e1 ");_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "L "_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "e "_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "e "_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "t "_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "C "_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "o "_x000D_
stringIterator.hasNext(); // return True_x000D_
stringIterator.next(); // return  "d "_x000D_
stringIterator.hasNext(); // return True_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= compressedString.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `compressedString` consists of lower-case an upper-case English letters and digits._x000D_
*   The number of a single character repetitions in `compressedString` is in the range `[1, 10^9]`_x000D_
*   At most `100` calls will be made to `next` and `hasNext`.

title: Can Place Flowers
content:
You have a long flowerbed in which some of the plots are planted, and some are not. However, flowers cannot be planted in **adjacent** plots._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an integer array `flowerbed` containing `0`'s and `1`'s, where `0` means empty and `1` means not empty, and an integer `n`, return `true` _if_ `n` _new flowers can be planted in the_ `flowerbed` _without violating the no-adjacent-flowers rule and_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flowerbed = \[1,0,0,0,1\], n = 1_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flowerbed = \[1,0,0,0,1\], n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= flowerbed.length <= 2 * 104`_x000D_
*   `flowerbed[i]` is `0` or `1`._x000D_
*   There are no two adjacent flowers in `flowerbed`._x000D_
*   `0 <= n <= flowerbed.length`

title: Construct String from Binary Tree
content:
Given the `root` of a binary tree, construct a string consisting of parenthesis and integers from a binary tree with the preorder traversal way, and return it._x000D_
_x000D_
Omit all the empty parenthesis pairs that do not affect the one-to-one mapping relationship between the string and the original binary tree._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "1(2(4))(3) "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Originally, it needs to be  "1(2(4)())(3()()) ", but you need to omit all the unnecessary empty parenthesis pairs. And it will be  "1(2(4))(3) "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,2,3,null,4\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "1(2()(4))(3) "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Almost the same as the first example, except we cannot omit the first parenthesis pair to break the one-to-one mapping relationship between the input and the output._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   `-1000 <= Node.val <= 1000`

title: Find Duplicate File in System
content:
Given a list `paths` of directory info, including the directory path, and all the files with contents in this directory, return _all the duplicate files in the file system in terms of their paths_. You may return the answer in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
A group of duplicate files consists of at least two files that have the same content._x000D_
_x000D_
A single directory info string in the input list has the following format:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `"root/d1/d2/.../dm f1.txt(f1_content) f2.txt(f2_content) ... fn.txt(fn_content) "`_x000D_
_x000D_
It means there are `n` files `(f1.txt, f2.txt ... fn.txt)` with content `(f1_content, f2_content ... fn_content)` respectively in the directory "`root/d1/d2/.../dm "`. Note that `n >= 1` and `m >= 0`. If `m = 0`, it means the directory is just the root directory._x000D_
_x000D_
The output is a list of groups of duplicate file paths. For each group, it contains all the file paths of the files that have the same content. A file path is a string that has the following format:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `"directory_path/file_name.txt "`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** paths = \["root/a 1.txt(abcd) 2.txt(efgh)","root/c 3.txt(abcd)","root/c/d 4.txt(efgh)","root 4.txt(efgh)"\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\["root/a/2.txt","root/c/d/4.txt","root/4.txt"\],\["root/a/1.txt","root/c/3.txt"\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** paths = \["root/a 1.txt(abcd) 2.txt(efgh)","root/c 3.txt(abcd)","root/c/d 4.txt(efgh)"\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\["root/a/2.txt","root/c/d/4.txt"\],\["root/a/1.txt","root/c/3.txt"\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= paths.length <= 2 * 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= paths[i].length <= 3000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= sum(paths[i].length) <= 5 * 105`_x000D_
*   `paths[i]` consist of English letters, digits, `'/'`, `'.'`, `'('`, `')'`, and `' '`._x000D_
*   You may assume no files or directories share the same name in the same directory._x000D_
*   You may assume each given directory info represents a unique directory. A single blank space separates the directory path and file info._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Imagine you are given a real file system, how will you search files? DFS or BFS?_x000D_
*   If the file content is very large (GB level), how will you modify your solution?_x000D_
*   If you can only read the file by 1kb each time, how will you modify your solution?_x000D_
*   What is the time complexity of your modified solution? What is the most time-consuming part and memory-consuming part of it? How to optimize?_x000D_
*   How to make sure the duplicated files you find are not false positive?

title: Valid Triangle Number
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, return _the number of triplets chosen from the array that can make triangles if we take them as side lengths of a triangle_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** Valid combinations are: _x000D_
2,3,4 (using the first 2)_x000D_
2,3,4 (using the second 2)_x000D_
2,2,3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[4,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums[i] <= 1000`

title: Add Bold Tag in String
content:
You are given a string `s` and an array of strings `words`._x000D_
_x000D_
You should add a closed pair of bold tag **and** to wrap the substrings in `s` that exist in `words`._x000D_
_x000D_
*   If two such substrings overlap, you should wrap them together with only one pair of closed bold-tag._x000D_
*   If two substrings wrapped by bold tags are consecutive, you should combine them._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `s` _after adding the bold tags_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "abcxyz123 ", words = \[ "abc ", "123 "\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "**abc**xyz**123** "_x000D_
**Explanation:** The two strings of words are substrings of s as following:  "abcxyz123 "._x000D_
We add ** before each substring and ** after each substring._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "aaabbb ", words = \[ "aa ", "b "\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "**aaabbb** "_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
 "aa " appears as a substring two times:  "aaabbb " and  "aaabbb "._x000D_
 "b " appears as a substring three times:  "aaabbb ",  "aaabbb ", and  "aaabbb "._x000D_
We add ** before each substring and ** after each substring:  "**a**a**a****b****b****b** "._x000D_
Since the first two **'s overlap, we merge them:  "**aaa****b****b****b** "._x000D_
Since now the four **'s are consecuutive, we merge them:  "**aaabbb** ".****_x000D_
_x000D_
****_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= words.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= words[i].length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `s` and `words[i]` consist of English letters and digits._x000D_
*   All the values of `words` are **unique**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:** This question is the same as 758: [https://leetcode.com/problems/bold-words-in-string/](https://leetcode.com/problems/bold-words-in-string/)_x000D_
_x000D_
****

title: Merge Two Binary Trees
content:
You are given two binary trees `root1` and `root2`._x000D_
_x000D_
Imagine that when you put one of them to cover the other, some nodes of the two trees are overlapped while the others are not. You need to merge the two trees into a new binary tree. The merge rule is that if two nodes overlap, then sum node values up as the new value of the merged node. Otherwise, the NOT null node will be used as the node of the new tree._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the merged tree_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:** The merging process must start from the root nodes of both trees._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root1 = \[1,3,2,5\], root2 = \[2,1,3,null,4,null,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,4,5,5,4,null,7\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root1 = \[1\], root2 = \[1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,2\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in both trees is in the range `[0, 2000]`._x000D_
*   `-104 <= Node.val <= 104`

title: Task Scheduler
content:
Given a characters array `tasks`, representing the tasks a CPU needs to do, where each letter represents a different task. Tasks could be done in any order. Each task is done in one unit of time. For each unit of time, the CPU could complete either one task or just be idle._x000D_
_x000D_
However, there is a non-negative integer `n` that represents the cooldown period between two **same tasks** (the same letter in the array), that is that there must be at least `n` units of time between any two same tasks._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the least number of units of times that the CPU will take to finish all the given tasks_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tasks = \[ "A ", "A ", "A ", "B ", "B ", "B "\], n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 8_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
A -> B -> idle -> A -> B -> idle -> A -> B_x000D_
There is at least 2 units of time between any two same tasks._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tasks = \[ "A ", "A ", "A ", "B ", "B ", "B "\], n = 0_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** On this case any permutation of size 6 would work since n = 0._x000D_
\[ "A ", "A ", "A ", "B ", "B ", "B "\]_x000D_
\[ "A ", "B ", "A ", "B ", "A ", "B "\]_x000D_
\[ "B ", "B ", "B ", "A ", "A ", "A "\]_x000D_
..._x000D_
And so on._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tasks = \[ "A ", "A ", "A ", "A ", "A ", "A ", "B ", "C ", "D ", "E ", "F ", "G "\], n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 16_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
One possible solution is_x000D_
A -> B -> C -> A -> D -> E -> A -> F -> G -> A -> idle -> idle -> A -> idle -> idle -> A_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= task.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `tasks[i]` is upper-case English letter._x000D_
*   The integer `n` is in the range `[0, 100]`.

title: Design Circular Queue
content:
Design your implementation of the circular queue. The circular queue is a linear data structure in which the operations are performed based on FIFO (First In First Out) principle, and the last position is connected back to the first position to make a circle. It is also called "Ring Buffer "._x000D_
_x000D_
One of the benefits of the circular queue is that we can make use of the spaces in front of the queue. In a normal queue, once the queue becomes full, we cannot insert the next element even if there is a space in front of the queue. But using the circular queue, we can use the space to store new values._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `MyCircularQueue` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `MyCircularQueue(k)` Initializes the object with the size of the queue to be `k`._x000D_
*   `int Front()` Gets the front item from the queue. If the queue is empty, return `-1`._x000D_
*   `int Rear()` Gets the last item from the queue. If the queue is empty, return `-1`._x000D_
*   `boolean enQueue(int value)` Inserts an element into the circular queue. Return `true` if the operation is successful._x000D_
*   `boolean deQueue()` Deletes an element from the circular queue. Return `true` if the operation is successful._x000D_
*   `boolean isEmpty()` Checks whether the circular queue is empty or not._x000D_
*   `boolean isFull()` Checks whether the circular queue is full or not._x000D_
_x000D_
You must solve the problem without using the built-in queue data structure in your programming language._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "MyCircularQueue ",  "enQueue ",  "enQueue ",  "enQueue ",  "enQueue ",  "Rear ",  "isFull ",  "deQueue ",  "enQueue ",  "Rear "\]_x000D_
\[\[3\], \[1\], \[2\], \[3\], \[4\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[4\], \[\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, true, true, true, false, 3, true, true, true, 4\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
MyCircularQueue myCircularQueue = new MyCircularQueue(3);_x000D_
myCircularQueue.enQueue(1); // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.enQueue(2); // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.enQueue(3); // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.enQueue(4); // return False_x000D_
myCircularQueue.Rear();     // return 3_x000D_
myCircularQueue.isFull();   // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.deQueue();  // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.enQueue(4); // return True_x000D_
myCircularQueue.Rear();     // return 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= value <= 1000`_x000D_
*   At most `3000` calls will be made to `enQueue`, `deQueue`, `Front`, `Rear`, `isEmpty`, and `isFull`.

title: Add One Row to Tree
content:
Given the `root` of a binary tree and two integers `val` and `depth`, add a row of nodes with value `val` at the given depth `depth`._x000D_
_x000D_
Note that the `root` node is at depth `1`._x000D_
_x000D_
The adding rule is:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Given the integer `depth`, for each not null tree node `cur` at the depth `depth - 1`, create two tree nodes with value `val` as `cur`'s left subtree root and right subtree root._x000D_
*   `cur`'s original left subtree should be the left subtree of the new left subtree root._x000D_
*   `cur`'s original right subtree should be the right subtree of the new right subtree root._x000D_
*   If `depth == 1` that means there is no depth `depth - 1` at all, then create a tree node with value `val` as the new root of the whole original tree, and the original tree is the new root's left subtree._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[4,2,6,3,1,5\], val = 1, depth = 2_x000D_
**Output:** \[4,1,1,2,null,null,6,3,1,5\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[4,2,null,3,1\], val = 1, depth = 3_x000D_
**Output:** \[4,2,null,1,1,3,null,null,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   The depth of the tree is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   `-100 <= Node.val <= 100`_x000D_
*   `-105 <= val <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= depth <= the depth of tree + 1`

title: Maximum Distance in Arrays
content:
You are given `m` `arrays`, where each array is sorted in **ascending order**._x000D_
_x000D_
You can pick up two integers from two different arrays (each array picks one) and calculate the distance. We define the distance between two integers `a` and `b` to be their absolute difference `|a - b|`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the maximum distance_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arrays = \[\[1,2,3\],\[4,5\],\[1,2,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** One way to reach the maximum distance 4 is to pick 1 in the first or third array and pick 5 in the second array._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arrays = \[\[1\],\[1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == arrays.length`_x000D_
*   `2 <= m <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= arrays[i].length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= arrays[i][j] <= 104`_x000D_
*   `arrays[i]` is sorted in **ascending order**._x000D_
*   There will be at most `105` integers in all the arrays.

title: Minimum Factorization
content:
Given a positive integer num, return _the smallest positive integer_ `x` _whose multiplication of each digit equals_ `num`. If there is no answer or the answer is not fit in **32-bit** signed integer, return `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** num = 48_x000D_
**Output:** 68_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** num = 15_x000D_
**Output:** 35_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= num <= 231 - 1`

title: Maximum Product of Three Numbers
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, _find three numbers whose product is maximum and return the maximum product_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 24_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[-1,-2,-3\]_x000D_
**Output:** -6_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `3 <= nums.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= nums[i] <= 1000`

title: K Inverse Pairs Array
content:
For an integer array `nums`, an **inverse pair** is a pair of integers `[i, j]` where `0 <= i < j < nums.length` and `nums[i] > nums[j]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given two integers n and k, return the number of different arrays consist of numbers from `1` to `n` such that there are exactly `k` **inverse pairs**. Since the answer can be huge, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3, k = 0_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** Only the array \[1,2,3\] which consists of numbers from 1 to 3 has exactly 0 inverse pairs._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3, k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** The array \[1,3,2\] and \[2,1,3\] have exactly 1 inverse pair._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= k <= 1000`

title: Course Schedule III
content:
There are `n` different online courses numbered from `1` to `n`. You are given an array `courses` where `courses[i] = [durationi, lastDayi]` indicate that the `ith` course should be taken **continuously** for `durationi` days and must be finished before or on `lastDayi`._x000D_
_x000D_
You will start on the `1st` day and you cannot take two or more courses simultaneously._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the maximum number of courses that you can take_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** courses = \[\[100,200\],\[200,1300\],\[1000,1250\],\[2000,3200\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
Explanation: _x000D_
There are totally 4 courses, but you can take 3 courses at most:_x000D_
First, take the 1st course, it costs 100 days so you will finish it on the 100th day, and ready to take the next course on the 101st day._x000D_
Second, take the 3rd course, it costs 1000 days so you will finish it on the 1100th day, and ready to take the next course on the 1101st day. _x000D_
Third, take the 2nd course, it costs 200 days so you will finish it on the 1300th day. _x000D_
The 4th course cannot be taken now, since you will finish it on the 3300th day, which exceeds the closed date._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** courses = \[\[1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** courses = \[\[3,2\],\[4,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= courses.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= durationi, lastDayi <= 104`

title: Design Excel Sum Formula
Smallest Range Covering Elements from K Lists
content:
You have `k` lists of sorted integers in **non-decreasing order**. Find the **smallest** range that includes at least one number from each of the `k` lists._x000D_
_x000D_
We define the range `[a, b]` is smaller than range `[c, d]` if `b - a < d - c` **or** `a < c` if `b - a == d - c`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[\[4,10,15,24,26\],\[0,9,12,20\],\[5,18,22,30\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[20,24\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
List 1: \[4, 10, 15, 24,26\], 24 is in range \[20,24\]._x000D_
List 2: \[0, 9, 12, 20\], 20 is in range \[20,24\]._x000D_
List 3: \[5, 18, 22, 30\], 22 is in range \[20,24\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[\[1,2,3\],\[1,2,3\],\[1,2,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `nums.length == k`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 3500`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i].length <= 50`_x000D_
*   `-105 <= nums[i][j] <= 105`_x000D_
*   `nums[i]` is sorted in **non-decreasing** order.

title: Sum of Square Numbers
content:
Given a non-negative integer `c`, decide whether there're two integers `a` and `b` such that `a2 + b2 = c`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** c = 5_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** 1 \* 1 + 2 \* 2 = 5_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** c = 3_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= c <= 231 - 1`

title: Find the Derangement of An Array
content:
In combinatorial mathematics, a **derangement** is a permutation of the elements of a set, such that no element appears in its original position._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given an integer `n`. There is originally an array consisting of `n` integers from `1` to `n` in ascending order, return _the number of **derangements** it can generate_. Since the answer may be huge, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** The original array is \[1,2,3\]. The two derangements are \[2,3,1\] and \[3,1,2\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 106`

title: Design Log Storage System
content:
You are given several logs, where each log contains a unique ID and timestamp. Timestamp is a string that has the following format: `Year:Month:Day:Hour:Minute:Second`, for example, `2017:01:01:23:59:59`. All domains are zero-padded decimal numbers._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `LogSystem` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `LogSystem()` Initializes the `LogSystem` object._x000D_
*   `void put(int id, string timestamp)` Stores the given log `(id, timestamp)` in your storage system._x000D_
*   `int[] retrieve(string start, string end, string granularity)` Returns the IDs of the logs whose timestamps are within the range from `start` to `end` inclusive. `start` and `end` all have the same format as `timestamp`, and `granularity` means how precise the range should be (i.e. to the exact `Day`, `Minute`, etc.). For example, `start = "2017:01:01:23:59:59 "`, `end = "2017:01:02:23:59:59 "`, and `granularity = "Day "` means that we need to find the logs within the inclusive range from **Jan. 1st 2017** to **Jan. 2nd 2017**, and the `Hour`, `Minute`, and `Second` for each log entry can be ignored._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "LogSystem ",  "put ",  "put ",  "put ",  "retrieve ",  "retrieve "\]_x000D_
\[\[\], \[1,  "2017:01:01:23:59:59 "\], \[2,  "2017:01:01:22:59:59 "\], \[3,  "2016:01:01:00:00:00 "\], \[ "2016:01:01:01:01:01 ",  "2017:01:01:23:00:00 ",  "Year "\], \[ "2016:01:01:01:01:01 ",  "2017:01:01:23:00:00 ",  "Hour "\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, null, null, null, \[3, 2, 1\], \[2, 1\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
LogSystem logSystem = new LogSystem();_x000D_
logSystem.put(1,  "2017:01:01:23:59:59 ");_x000D_
logSystem.put(2,  "2017:01:01:22:59:59 ");_x000D_
logSystem.put(3,  "2016:01:01:00:00:00 ");_x000D_
_x000D_
// return \[3,2,1\], because you need to return all logs between 2016 and 2017._x000D_
logSystem.retrieve( "2016:01:01:01:01:01 ",  "2017:01:01:23:00:00 ",  "Year ");_x000D_
_x000D_
// return \[2,1\], because you need to return all logs between Jan. 1, 2016 01:XX:XX and Jan. 1, 2017 23:XX:XX._x000D_
// Log 3 is not returned because Jan. 1, 2016 00:00:00 comes before the start of the range._x000D_
logSystem.retrieve( "2016:01:01:01:01:01 ",  "2017:01:01:23:00:00 ",  "Hour ");_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= id <= 500`_x000D_
*   `2000 <= Year <= 2017`_x000D_
*   `1 <= Month <= 12`_x000D_
*   `1 <= Day <= 31`_x000D_
*   `0 <= Hour <= 23`_x000D_
*   `0 <= Minute, Second <= 59`_x000D_
*   `granularity` is one of the values `[ "Year ", "Month ", "Day ", "Hour ", "Minute ", "Second "]`._x000D_
*   At most `500` calls will be made to `put` and `retrieve`.

title: Exclusive Time of Functions
content:
On a **single-threaded** CPU, we execute a program containing `n` functions. Each function has a unique ID between `0` and `n-1`._x000D_
_x000D_
Function calls are **stored in a [call stack](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_stack)**: when a function call starts, its ID is pushed onto the stack, and when a function call ends, its ID is popped off the stack. The function whose ID is at the top of the stack is **the current function being executed**. Each time a function starts or ends, we write a log with the ID, whether it started or ended, and the timestamp._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given a list `logs`, where `logs[i]` represents the `ith` log message formatted as a string `"{function_id}:{ "start " | "end "}:{timestamp} "`. For example, `"0:start:3 "` means a function call with function ID `0` **started at the beginning** of timestamp `3`, and `"1:end:2 "` means a function call with function ID `1` **ended at the end** of timestamp `2`. Note that a function can be called **multiple times, possibly recursively**._x000D_
_x000D_
A function's **exclusive time** is the sum of execution times for all function calls in the program. For example, if a function is called twice, one call executing for `2` time units and another call executing for `1` time unit, the **exclusive time** is `2 + 1 = 3`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **exclusive time** of each function in an array, where the value at the_ `ith` _index represents the exclusive time for the function with ID_ `i`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, logs = \[ "0:start:0 ", "1:start:2 ", "1:end:5 ", "0:end:6 "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,4\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Function 0 starts at the beginning of time 0, then it executes 2 for units of time and reaches the end of time 1._x000D_
Function 1 starts at the beginning of time 2, executes for 4 units of time, and ends at the end of time 5._x000D_
Function 0 resumes execution at the beginning of time 6 and executes for 1 unit of time._x000D_
So function 0 spends 2 + 1 = 3 units of total time executing, and function 1 spends 4 units of total time executing._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1, logs = \[ "0:start:0 ", "0:start:2 ", "0:end:5 ", "0:start:6 ", "0:end:6 ", "0:end:7 "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[8\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Function 0 starts at the beginning of time 0, executes for 2 units of time, and recursively calls itself._x000D_
Function 0 (recursive call) starts at the beginning of time 2 and executes for 4 units of time._x000D_
Function 0 (initial call) resumes execution then immediately calls itself again._x000D_
Function 0 (2nd recursive call) starts at the beginning of time 6 and executes for 1 unit of time._x000D_
Function 0 (initial call) resumes execution at the beginning of time 7 and executes for 1 unit of time._x000D_
So function 0 spends 2 + 4 + 1 + 1 = 8 units of total time executing._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, logs = \[ "0:start:0 ", "0:start:2 ", "0:end:5 ", "1:start:6 ", "1:end:6 ", "0:end:7 "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[7,1\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
Function 0 starts at the beginning of time 0, executes for 2 units of time, and recursively calls itself._x000D_
Function 0 (recursive call) starts at the beginning of time 2 and executes for 4 units of time._x000D_
Function 0 (initial call) resumes execution then immediately calls function 1._x000D_
Function 1 starts at the beginning of time 6, executes 1 unit of time, and ends at the end of time 6._x000D_
Function 0 resumes execution at the beginning of time 6 and executes for 2 units of time._x000D_
So function 0 spends 2 + 4 + 1 = 7 units of total time executing, and function 1 spends 1 unit of total time executing._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= logs.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `0 <= function_id < n`_x000D_
*   `0 <= timestamp <= 109`_x000D_
*   No two start events will happen at the same timestamp._x000D_
*   No two end events will happen at the same timestamp._x000D_
*   Each function has an `"end "` log for each `"start "` log.

title: Average of Levels in Binary Tree
content:
Given the `root` of a binary tree, return _the average value of the nodes on each level in the form of an array_. Answers within `10-5` of the actual answer will be accepted._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[3,9,20,null,null,15,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3.00000,14.50000,11.00000\]_x000D_
Explanation: The average value of nodes on level 0 is 3, on level 1 is 14.5, and on level 2 is 11._x000D_
Hence return \[3, 14.5, 11\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[3,9,20,15,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3.00000,14.50000,11.00000\]_x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_

*   `-231 <= Node.val <= 231 - 1`

title: Shopping Offers
content:
In LeetCode Store, there are `n` items to sell. Each item has a price. However, there are some special offers, and a special offer consists of one or more different kinds of items with a sale price._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given an integer array `price` where `price[i]` is the price of the `ith` item, and an integer array `needs` where `needs[i]` is the number of pieces of the `ith` item you want to buy._x000D_
_x000D_
You are also given an array `special` where `special[i]` is of size `n + 1` where `special[i][j]` is the number of pieces of the `jth` item in the `ith` offer and `special[i][n]` (i.e., the last integer in the array) is the price of the `ith` offer._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the lowest price you have to pay for exactly certain items as given, where you could make optimal use of the special offers_. You are not allowed to buy more items than you want, even if that would lower the overall price. You could use any of the special offers as many times as you want._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** price = \[2,5\], special = \[\[3,0,5\],\[1,2,10\]\], needs = \[3,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 14_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are two kinds of items, A and B. Their prices are $2 and $5 respectively. _x000D_
In special offer 1, you can pay $5 for 3A and 0B_x000D_
In special offer 2, you can pay $10 for 1A and 2B. _x000D_
You need to buy 3A and 2B, so you may pay $10 for 1A and 2B (special offer #2), and $4 for 2A._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** price = \[2,3,4\], special = \[\[1,1,0,4\],\[2,2,1,9\]\], needs = \[1,2,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 11_x000D_
**Explanation:** The price of A is $2, and $3 for B, $4 for C. _x000D_
You may pay $4 for 1A and 1B, and $9 for 2A ,2B and 1C. _x000D_
You need to buy 1A ,2B and 1C, so you may pay $4 for 1A and 1B (special offer #1), and $3 for 1B, $4 for 1C. _x000D_
You cannot add more items, though only $9 for 2A ,2B and 1C._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == price.length == needs.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 6`_x000D_
*   `0 <= price[i], needs[i] <= 10`_x000D_
*   `1 <= special.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `special[i].length == n + 1`_x000D_
*   `0 <= special[i][j] <= 50`

title: Decode Ways II
content:
A message containing letters from `A-Z` can be **encoded** into numbers using the following mapping:_x000D_
_x000D_
'A' ->  "1 "_x000D_
'B' ->  "2 "_x000D_
..._x000D_
'Z' ->  "26 "_x000D_
_x000D_
To **decode** an encoded message, all the digits must be grouped then mapped back into letters using the reverse of the mapping above (there may be multiple ways). For example, `"11106 "` can be mapped into:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `"AAJF "` with the grouping `(1 1 10 6)`_x000D_
*   `"KJF "` with the grouping `(11 10 6)`_x000D_
_x000D_
Note that the grouping `(1 11 06)` is invalid because `"06 "` cannot be mapped into `'F'` since `"6 "` is different from `"06 "`._x000D_
_x000D_
**In addition** to the mapping above, an encoded message may contain the `'*'` character, which can represent any digit from `'1'` to `'9'` (`'0'` is excluded). For example, the encoded message `"1* "` may represent any of the encoded messages `"11 "`, `"12 "`, `"13 "`, `"14 "`, `"15 "`, `"16 "`, `"17 "`, `"18 "`, or `"19 "`. Decoding `"1* "` is equivalent to decoding **any** of the encoded messages it can represent._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a string `s` consisting of digits and `'*'` characters, return _the **number** of ways to **decode** it_._x000D_
_x000D_
Since the answer may be very large, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "\* "_x000D_
**Output:** 9_x000D_
**Explanation:** The encoded message can represent any of the encoded messages  "1 ",  "2 ",  "3 ",  "4 ",  "5 ",  "6 ",  "7 ",  "8 ", or  "9 "._x000D_
Each of these can be decoded to the strings  "A ",  "B ",  "C ",  "D ",  "E ",  "F ",  "G ",  "H ", and  "I " respectively._x000D_
Hence, there are a total of 9 ways to decode  "\* "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1\* "_x000D_
**Output:** 18_x000D_
**Explanation:** The encoded message can represent any of the encoded messages  "11 ",  "12 ",  "13 ",  "14 ",  "15 ",  "16 ",  "17 ",  "18 ", or  "19 "._x000D_
Each of these encoded messages have 2 ways to be decoded (e.g.  "11 " can be decoded to  "AA " or  "K ")._x000D_
Hence, there are a total of 9 \* 2 = 18 ways to decode  "1\* "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "2\* "_x000D_
**Output:** 15_x000D_
**Explanation:** The encoded message can represent any of the encoded messages  "21 ",  "22 ",  "23 ",  "24 ",  "25 ",  "26 ",  "27 ",  "28 ", or  "29 "._x000D_
 "21 ",  "22 ",  "23 ",  "24 ",  "25 ", and  "26 " have 2 ways of being decoded, but  "27 ",  "28 ", and  "29 " only have 1 way._x000D_
Hence, there are a total of (6 \* 2) + (3 \* 1) = 12 + 3 = 15 ways to decode  "2\* "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `s[i]` is a digit or `'*'`.

title: Solve the Equation
content:
Solve a given equation and return the value of `'x'` in the form of a string `"x=#value "`. The equation contains only `'+'`, `'-'` operation, the variable `'x'` and its coefficient. You should return `"No solution "` if there is no solution for the equation, or `"Infinite solutions "` if there are infinite solutions for the equation._x000D_
_x000D_
If there is exactly one solution for the equation, we ensure that the value of `'x'` is an integer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** equation =  "x+5-3+x=6+x-2 "_x000D_
**Output:**  "x=2 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** equation =  "x=x "_x000D_
**Output:**  "Infinite solutions "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** equation =  "2x=x "_x000D_
**Output:**  "x=0 "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `3 <= equation.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `equation` has exactly one `'='`._x000D_
*   `equation` consists of integers with an absolute value in the range `[0, 100]` without any leading zeros, and the variable `'x'`.

title: Design Circular Deque
content:
Design your implementation of the circular double-ended queue (deque)._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `MyCircularDeque` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `MyCircularDeque(int k)` Initializes the deque with a maximum size of `k`._x000D_
*   `boolean insertFront()` Adds an item at the front of Deque. Returns `true` if the operation is successful, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
*   `boolean insertLast()` Adds an item at the rear of Deque. Returns `true` if the operation is successful, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
*   `boolean deleteFront()` Deletes an item from the front of Deque. Returns `true` if the operation is successful, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
*   `boolean deleteLast()` Deletes an item from the rear of Deque. Returns `true` if the operation is successful, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
*   `int getFront()` Returns the front item from the Deque. Returns `-1` if the deque is empty._x000D_
*   `int getRear()` Returns the last item from Deque. Returns `-1` if the deque is empty._x000D_
*   `boolean isEmpty()` Returns `true` if the deque is empty, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
*   `boolean isFull()` Returns `true` if the deque is full, or `false` otherwise._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "MyCircularDeque ",  "insertLast ",  "insertLast ",  "insertFront ",  "insertFront ",  "getRear ",  "isFull ",  "deleteLast ",  "insertFront ",  "getFront "\]_x000D_
\[\[3\], \[1\], \[2\], \[3\], \[4\], \[\], \[\], \[\], \[4\], \[\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, true, true, true, false, 2, true, true, true, 4\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
MyCircularDeque myCircularDeque = new MyCircularDeque(3);_x000D_
myCircularDeque.insertLast(1);  // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.insertLast(2);  // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.insertFront(3); // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.insertFront(4); // return False, the queue is full._x000D_
myCircularDeque.getRear();      // return 2_x000D_
myCircularDeque.isFull();       // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.deleteLast();   // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.insertFront(4); // return True_x000D_
myCircularDeque.getFront();     // return 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= value <= 1000`_x000D_
*   At most `2000` calls will be made to `insertFront`, `insertLast`, `deleteFront`, `deleteLast`, `getFront`, `getRear`, `isEmpty`, `isFull`.

title: Design Search Autocomplete System
content:
Design a search autocomplete system for a search engine. Users may input a sentence (at least one word and end with a special character `'#'`)._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given a string array `sentences` and an integer array `times` both of length `n` where `sentences[i]` is a previously typed sentence and `times[i]` is the corresponding number of times the sentence was typed. For each input character except `'#'`, return the top `3` historical hot sentences that have the same prefix as the part of the sentence already typed._x000D_
_x000D_
Here are the specific rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The hot degree for a sentence is defined as the number of times a user typed the exactly same sentence before._x000D_
*   The returned top `3` hot sentences should be sorted by hot degree (The first is the hottest one). If several sentences have the same hot degree, use ASCII-code order (smaller one appears first)._x000D_
*   If less than `3` hot sentences exist, return as many as you can._x000D_
*   When the input is a special character, it means the sentence ends, and in this case, you need to return an empty list._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `AutocompleteSystem` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `AutocompleteSystem(String[] sentences, int[] times)` Initializes the object with the `sentences` and `times` arrays._x000D_
*   `List input(char c)` This indicates that the user typed the character `c`._x000D_
    *   Returns an empty array `[]` if `c == '#'` and stores the inputted sentence in the system._x000D_
    *   Returns the top `3` historical hot sentences that have the same prefix as the part of the sentence already typed. If there are fewer than `3` matches, return them all._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "AutocompleteSystem ",  "input ",  "input ",  "input ",  "input "\]_x000D_
\[\[\[ "i love you ",  "island ",  "iroman ",  "i love leetcode "\], \[5, 3, 2, 2\]\], \[ "i "\], \[ "  "\], \[ "a "\], \[ "# "\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null, \[ "i love you ",  "island ",  "i love leetcode "\], \[ "i love you ",  "i love leetcode "\], \[\], \[\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
AutocompleteSystem obj = new AutocompleteSystem(\[ "i love you ",  "island ",  "iroman ",  "i love leetcode "\], \[5, 3, 2, 2\]);_x000D_
obj.input( "i "); // return \[ "i love you ",  "island ",  "i love leetcode "\]. There are four sentences that have prefix  "i ". Among them,  "ironman " and  "i love leetcode " have same hot degree. Since ' ' has ASCII code 32 and 'r' has ASCII code 114,  "i love leetcode " should be in front of  "ironman ". Also we only need to output top 3 hot sentences, so  "ironman " will be ignored._x000D_
obj.input( "  "); // return \[ "i love you ",  "i love leetcode "\]. There are only two sentences that have prefix  "i  "._x000D_
obj.input( "a "); // return \[\]. There are no sentences that have prefix  "i a "._x000D_
obj.input( "# "); // return \[\]. The user finished the input, the sentence  "i a " should be saved as a historical sentence in system. And the following input will be counted as a new search._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == sentences.length`_x000D_
*   `n == times.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= sentences[i].length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= times[i] <= 50`_x000D_
*   `c` is a lowercase English letter, a hash `'#'`, or space `' '`._x000D_
*   Each tested sentence will be a sequence of characters `c` that end with the character `'#'`._x000D_
*   Each tested sentence will have a length in the range `[1, 200]`._x000D_
*   The words in each input sentence are separated by single spaces._x000D_
*   At most `5000` calls will be made to `input`.

title: Maximum Average Subarray I
content:
You are given an integer array `nums` consisting of `n` elements, and an integer `k`._x000D_
_x000D_
Find a contiguous subarray whose **length is equal to** `k` that has the maximum average value and return _this value_. Any answer with a calculation error less than `10-5` will be accepted._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,12,-5,-6,50,3\], k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 12.75000_x000D_
**Explanation:** Maximum average is (12 - 5 - 6 + 50) / 4 = 51 / 4 = 12.75_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[5\], k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 5.00000_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == nums.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= nums[i] <= 104`

title: Maximum Average Subarray II
content:
You are given an integer array `nums` consisting of `n` elements, and an integer `k`._x000D_
_x000D_
Find a contiguous subarray whose **length is greater than or equal to** `k` that has the maximum average value and return _this value_. Any answer with a calculation error less than `10-5` will be accepted._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,12,-5,-6,50,3\], k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 12.75000_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
\- When the length is 4, averages are \[0.5, 12.75, 10.5\] and the maximum average is 12.75_x000D_
- When the length is 5, averages are \[10.4, 10.8\] and the maximum average is 10.8_x000D_
- When the length is 6, averages are \[9.16667\] and the maximum average is 9.16667_x000D_
The maximum average is when we choose a subarray of length 4 (i.e., the sub array \[12, -5, -6, 50\]) which has the max average 12.75, so we return 12.75_x000D_
Note that we do not consider the subarrays of length < 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[5\], k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 5.00000_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == nums.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= n <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= nums[i] <= 104`

title: Set Mismatch
content:
You have a set of integers `s`, which originally contains all the numbers from `1` to `n`. Unfortunately, due to some error, one of the numbers in `s` got duplicated to another number in the set, which results in **repetition of one** number and **loss of another** number._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given an integer array `nums` representing the data status of this set after the error._x000D_
_x000D_
Find the number that occurs twice and the number that is missing and return _them in the form of an array_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,2,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,3\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,2\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `2 <= nums.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 104`

title: Maximum Length of Pair Chain
content:
You are given an array of `n` pairs `pairs` where `pairs[i] = [lefti, righti]` and `lefti < righti`._x000D_
_x000D_
A pair `p2 = [c, d]` **follows** a pair `p1 = [a, b]` if `b < c`. A **chain** of pairs can be formed in this fashion._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the length longest chain which can be formed_._x000D_
_x000D_
You do not need to use up all the given intervals. You can select pairs in any order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** pairs = \[\[1,2\],\[2,3\],\[3,4\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest chain is \[1,2\] -> \[3,4\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** pairs = \[\[1,2\],\[7,8\],\[4,5\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest chain is \[1,2\] -> \[4,5\] -> \[7,8\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == pairs.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= lefti < righti <= 1000`

title: Palindromic Substrings
content:
Given a string `s`, return _the number of **palindromic substrings** in it_._x000D_
_x000D_
A string is a **palindrome** when it reads the same backward as forward._x000D_
_x000D_
A **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within the string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "abc "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** Three palindromic strings:  "a ",  "b ",  "c "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "aaa "_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** Six palindromic strings:  "a ",  "a ",  "a ",  "aa ",  "aa ",  "aaa "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of lowercase English letters.

title: Replace Words
content:
In English, we have a concept called **root**, which can be followed by some other word to form another longer word - let's call this word **successor**. For example, when the **root** `"an "` is followed by the **successor** word `"other "`, we can form a new word `"another "`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a `dictionary` consisting of many **roots** and a `sentence` consisting of words separated by spaces, replace all the **successors** in the sentence with the **root** forming it. If a **successor** can be replaced by more than one **root**, replace it with the **root** that has **the shortest length**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the `sentence`_ after the replacement._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** dictionary = \[ "cat ", "bat ", "rat "\], sentence =  "the cattle was rattled by the battery "_x000D_
**Output:**  "the cat was rat by the bat "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** dictionary = \[ "a ", "b ", "c "\], sentence =  "aadsfasf absbs bbab cadsfafs "_x000D_
**Output:**  "a a b c "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= dictionary.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= dictionary[i].length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `dictionary[i]` consists of only lower-case letters._x000D_
*   `1 <= sentence.length <= 106`_x000D_
*   `sentence` consists of only lower-case letters and spaces._x000D_
*   The number of words in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`_x000D_
*   The length of each word in `sentence` is in the range `[1, 1000]`_x000D_
*   Every two consecutive words in `sentence` will be separated by exactly one space._x000D_
*   `sentence` does not have leading or trailing spaces.

title: Dota2 Senate
content:
In the world of Dota2, there are two parties: the Radiant and the Dire._x000D_
_x000D_
The Dota2 senate consists of senators coming from two parties. Now the Senate wants to decide on a change in the Dota2 game. The voting for this change is a round-based procedure. In each round, each senator can exercise **one** of the two rights:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   **Ban one senator's right:** A senator can make another senator lose all his rights in this and all the following rounds._x000D_
*   **Announce the victory:** If this senator found the senators who still have rights to vote are all from the same party, he can announce the victory and decide on the change in the game._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a string `senate` representing each senator's party belonging. The character `'R'` and `'D'` represent the Radiant party and the Dire party. Then if there are `n` senators, the size of the given string will be `n`._x000D_
_x000D_
The round-based procedure starts from the first senator to the last senator in the given order. This procedure will last until the end of voting. All the senators who have lost their rights will be skipped during the procedure._x000D_
_x000D_
Suppose every senator is smart enough and will play the best strategy for his own party. Predict which party will finally announce the victory and change the Dota2 game. The output should be `"Radiant "` or `"Dire "`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** senate =  "RD "_x000D_
**Output:**  "Radiant "_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
The first senator comes from Radiant and he can just ban the next senator's right in round 1. _x000D_
And the second senator can't exercise any rights anymore since his right has been banned. _x000D_
And in round 2, the first senator can just announce the victory since he is the only guy in the senate who can vote._x000D_
_x000D_
