**Output:** \[2,1,0,3\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[7,7,7,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[0,0,0,0\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `2 <= nums.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums[i] <= 100`

title: Rank Teams by Votes
content:
In a special ranking system, each voter gives a rank from highest to lowest to all teams participating in the competition._x000D_
_x000D_
The ordering of teams is decided by who received the most position-one votes. If two or more teams tie in the first position, we consider the second position to resolve the conflict, if they tie again, we continue this process until the ties are resolved. If two or more teams are still tied after considering all positions, we rank them alphabetically based on their team letter._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given an array of strings `votes` which is the votes of all voters in the ranking systems. Sort all teams according to the ranking system described above._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _a string of all teams **sorted** by the ranking system_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** votes = \[ "ABC ", "ACB ", "ABC ", "ACB ", "ACB "\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "ACB "_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
Team A was ranked first place by 5 voters. No other team was voted as first place, so team A is the first team._x000D_
Team B was ranked second by 2 voters and ranked third by 3 voters._x000D_
Team C was ranked second by 3 voters and ranked third by 2 voters._x000D_
As most of the voters ranked C second, team C is the second team, and team B is the third._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** votes = \[ "WXYZ ", "XYZW "\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "XWYZ "_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
X is the winner due to the tie-breaking rule. X has the same votes as W for the first position, but X has one vote in the second position, while W does not have any votes in the second position. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** votes = \[ "ZMNAGUEDSJYLBOPHRQICWFXTVK "\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "ZMNAGUEDSJYLBOPHRQICWFXTVK "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Only one voter, so their votes are used for the ranking._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= votes.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= votes[i].length <= 26`_x000D_
*   `votes[i].length == votes[j].length` for `0 <= i, j < votes.length`._x000D_
*   `votes[i][j]` is an English **uppercase** letter._x000D_
*   All characters of `votes[i]` are unique._x000D_
*   All the characters that occur in `votes[0]` **also occur** in `votes[j]` where `1 <= j < votes.length`.

title: Linked List in Binary Tree
content:
Given a binary tree `root` and a linked list with `head` as the first node._x000D_
_x000D_
Return True if all the elements in the linked list starting from the `head` correspond to some _downward path_ connected in the binary tree otherwise return False._x000D_
_x000D_
In this context downward path means a path that starts at some node and goes downwards._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[4,2,8\], root = \[1,4,4,null,2,2,null,1,null,6,8,null,null,null,null,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** Nodes in blue form a subpath in the binary Tree.  _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,4,2,6\], root = \[1,4,4,null,2,2,null,1,null,6,8,null,null,null,null,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** head = \[1,4,2,6,8\], root = \[1,4,4,null,2,2,null,1,null,6,8,null,null,null,null,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is no path in the binary tree that contains all the elements of the linked list from `head`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree will be in the range `[1, 2500]`._x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the list will be in the range `[1, 100]`._x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 100` for each node in the linked list and binary tree.

title: Minimum Cost to Make at Least One Valid Path in a Grid
content:
Given an `m x n` grid. Each cell of the grid has a sign pointing to the next cell you should visit if you are currently in this cell. The sign of `grid[i][j]` can be:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1` which means go to the cell to the right. (i.e go from `grid[i][j]` to `grid[i][j + 1]`)_x000D_
*   `2` which means go to the cell to the left. (i.e go from `grid[i][j]` to `grid[i][j - 1]`)_x000D_
*   `3` which means go to the lower cell. (i.e go from `grid[i][j]` to `grid[i + 1][j]`)_x000D_
*   `4` which means go to the upper cell. (i.e go from `grid[i][j]` to `grid[i - 1][j]`)_x000D_
_x000D_
Notice that there could be some signs on the cells of the grid that point outside the grid._x000D_
_x000D_
You will initially start at the upper left cell `(0, 0)`. A valid path in the grid is a path that starts from the upper left cell `(0, 0)` and ends at the bottom-right cell `(m - 1, n - 1)` following the signs on the grid. The valid path does not have to be the shortest._x000D_
_x000D_
You can modify the sign on a cell with `cost = 1`. You can modify the sign on a cell **one time only**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the minimum cost to make the grid have at least one valid path_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,1,1,1\],\[2,2,2,2\],\[1,1,1,1\],\[2,2,2,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** You will start at point (0, 0)._x000D_
The path to (3, 3) is as follows. (0, 0) --> (0, 1) --> (0, 2) --> (0, 3) change the arrow to down with cost = 1 --> (1, 3) --> (1, 2) --> (1, 1) --> (1, 0) change the arrow to down with cost = 1 --> (2, 0) --> (2, 1) --> (2, 2) --> (2, 3) change the arrow to down with cost = 1 --> (3, 3)_x000D_
The total cost = 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,1,3\],\[3,2,2\],\[1,1,4\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can follow the path from (0, 0) to (2, 2)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,2\],\[4,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == grid.length`_x000D_
*   `n == grid[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= grid[i][j] <= 4`

title: Increasing Decreasing String
content:
You are given a string `s`. Reorder the string using the following algorithm:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  Pick the **smallest** character from `s` and **append** it to the result._x000D_
2.  Pick the **smallest** character from `s` which is greater than the last appended character to the result and **append** it._x000D_
3.  Repeat step 2 until you cannot pick more characters._x000D_
4.  Pick the **largest** character from `s` and **append** it to the result._x000D_
5.  Pick the **largest** character from `s` which is smaller than the last appended character to the result and **append** it._x000D_
6.  Repeat step 5 until you cannot pick more characters._x000D_
7.  Repeat the steps from 1 to 6 until you pick all characters from `s`._x000D_
_x000D_
In each step, If the smallest or the largest character appears more than once you can choose any occurrence and append it to the result._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the result string after sorting_ `s` _with this algorithm_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "aaaabbbbcccc "_x000D_
**Output:**  "abccbaabccba "_x000D_
**Explanation:** After steps 1, 2 and 3 of the first iteration, result =  "abc "_x000D_
After steps 4, 5 and 6 of the first iteration, result =  "abccba "_x000D_
First iteration is done. Now s =  "aabbcc " and we go back to step 1_x000D_
After steps 1, 2 and 3 of the second iteration, result =  "abccbaabc "_x000D_
After steps 4, 5 and 6 of the second iteration, result =  "abccbaabccba "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "rat "_x000D_
**Output:**  "art "_x000D_
**Explanation:** The word  "rat " becomes  "art " after re-ordering it with the mentioned algorithm._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of only lowercase English letters.

title: Find the Longest Substring Containing Vowels in Even Counts
content:
Given the string `s`, return the size of the longest substring containing each vowel an even number of times. That is, 'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', and 'u' must appear an even number of times._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "eleetminicoworoep "_x000D_
**Output:** 13_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest substring is  "leetminicowor " which contains two each of the vowels: **e**, **i** and **o** and zero of the vowels: **a** and **u**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "leetcodeisgreat "_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** The longest substring is  "leetc " which contains two e's._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "bcbcbc "_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this case, the given string  "bcbcbc " is the longest because all vowels: **a**, **e**, **i**, **o** and **u** appear zero times._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 5 x 10^5`_x000D_
*   `s` contains only lowercase English letters._x000D_
_x000D_
It is the empty string, or It can be written as AB (A concatenated with B), where A and B are valid strings, or It can be written as (A), where A is a valid string.

title: Longest ZigZag Path in a Binary Tree
content:
You are given the `root` of a binary tree._x000D_
_x000D_
A ZigZag path for a binary tree is defined as follow:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Choose **any** node in the binary tree and a direction (right or left)._x000D_
*   If the current direction is right, move to the right child of the current node; otherwise, move to the left child._x000D_
*   Change the direction from right to left or from left to right._x000D_
*   Repeat the second and third steps until you can't move in the tree._x000D_
_x000D_
Zigzag length is defined as the number of nodes visited - 1. (A single node has a length of 0)._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the longest **ZigZag** path contained in that tree_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,1,1,1,null,null,1,1,null,1,null,null,null,1,null,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** Longest ZigZag path in blue nodes (right -> left -> right)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,1,1,null,1,null,null,1,1,null,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** Longest ZigZag path in blue nodes (left -> right -> left -> right)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 5 * 104]`._x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 100`

title: Maximum Sum BST in Binary Tree
content:
Given a **binary tree** `root`, return _the maximum sum of all keys of **any** sub-tree which is also a Binary Search Tree (BST)_._x000D_
_x000D_
Assume a BST is defined as follows:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The left subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys **less than** the node's key._x000D_
*   The right subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys **greater than** the node's key._x000D_
*   Both the left and right subtrees must also be binary search trees._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,4,3,2,4,2,5,null,null,null,null,null,null,4,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** 20_x000D_
**Explanation:** Maximum sum in a valid Binary search tree is obtained in root node with key equal to 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[4,3,null,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** Maximum sum in a valid Binary search tree is obtained in a single root node with key equal to 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[-4,-2,-5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** All values are negatives. Return an empty BST._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 4 * 104]`._x000D_
*   `-4 * 104 <= Node.val <= 4 * 104`

title: Generate a String With Characters That Have Odd Counts
content:
Given an integer `n`, _return a string with `n` characters such that each character in such string occurs **an odd number of times**_._x000D_
_x000D_
The returned string must contain only lowercase English letters. If there are multiples valid strings, return **any** of them._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 4_x000D_
**Output:**  "pppz "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "pppz " is a valid string since the character 'p' occurs three times and the character 'z' occurs once. Note that there are many other valid strings such as  "ohhh " and  "love "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2_x000D_
**Output:**  "xy "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "xy " is a valid string since the characters 'x' and 'y' occur once. Note that there are many other valid strings such as  "ag " and  "ur "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 7_x000D_
**Output:**  "holasss "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 500`

title: Number of Times Binary String Is Prefix-Aligned
content:
You have a **1-indexed** binary string of length `n` where all the bits are `0` initially. We will flip all the bits of this binary string (i.e., change them from `0` to `1`) one by one. You are given a **1-indexed** integer array `flips` where `flips[i]` indicates that the bit at index `i` will be flipped in the `ith` step._x000D_
_x000D_
A binary string is **prefix-aligned** if, after the `ith` step, all the bits in the **inclusive** range `[1, i]` are ones and all the other bits are zeros._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of times the binary string is **prefix-aligned** during the flipping process_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flips = \[3,2,4,1,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** The binary string is initially  "00000 "._x000D_
After applying step 1: The string becomes  "00100 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 2: The string becomes  "01100 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 3: The string becomes  "01110 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 4: The string becomes  "11110 ", which is prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 5: The string becomes  "11111 ", which is prefix-aligned._x000D_
We can see that the string was prefix-aligned 2 times, so we return 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** flips = \[4,1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The binary string is initially  "0000 "._x000D_
After applying step 1: The string becomes  "0001 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 2: The string becomes  "1001 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 3: The string becomes  "1101 ", which is not prefix-aligned._x000D_
After applying step 4: The string becomes  "1111 ", which is prefix-aligned._x000D_
We can see that the string was prefix-aligned 1 time, so we return 1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == flips.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   `flips` is a permutation of the integers in the range `[1, n]`.

title: Time Needed to Inform All Employees
content:
A company has `n` employees with a unique ID for each employee from `0` to `n - 1`. The head of the company is the one with `headID`._x000D_
_x000D_
Each employee has one direct manager given in the `manager` array where `manager[i]` is the direct manager of the `i-th` employee, `manager[headID] = -1`. Also, it is guaranteed that the subordination relationships have a tree structure._x000D_
_x000D_
The head of the company wants to inform all the company employees of an urgent piece of news. He will inform his direct subordinates, and they will inform their subordinates, and so on until all employees know about the urgent news._x000D_
_x000D_
The `i-th` employee needs `informTime[i]` minutes to inform all of his direct subordinates (i.e., After informTime\[i\] minutes, all his direct subordinates can start spreading the news)._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of minutes_ needed to inform all the employees about the urgent news._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1, headID = 0, manager = \[-1\], informTime = \[0\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The head of the company is the only employee in the company._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 6, headID = 2, manager = \[2,2,-1,2,2,2\], informTime = \[0,0,1,0,0,0\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The head of the company with id = 2 is the direct manager of all the employees in the company and needs 1 minute to inform them all._x000D_
The tree structure of the employees in the company is shown._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= headID < n`_x000D_
*   `manager.length == n`_x000D_
*   `0 <= manager[i] < n`_x000D_
*   `manager[headID] == -1`_x000D_
*   `informTime.length == n`_x000D_
*   `0 <= informTime[i] <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `informTime[i] == 0` if employee `i` has no subordinates._x000D_
*   It is **guaranteed** that all the employees can be informed.

title: Frog Position After T Seconds
content:
Given an undirected tree consisting of `n` vertices numbered from `1` to `n`. A frog starts jumping from **vertex 1**. In one second, the frog jumps from its current vertex to another **unvisited** vertex if they are directly connected. The frog can not jump back to a visited vertex. In case the frog can jump to several vertices, it jumps randomly to one of them with the same probability. Otherwise, when the frog can not jump to any unvisited vertex, it jumps forever on the same vertex._x000D_
_x000D_
The edges of the undirected tree are given in the array `edges`, where `edges[i] = [ai, bi]` means that exists an edge connecting the vertices `ai` and `bi`._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return the probability that after `t` seconds the frog is on the vertex `target`._ Answers within `10-5` of the actual answer will be accepted._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 7, edges = \[\[1,2\],\[1,3\],\[1,7\],\[2,4\],\[2,6\],\[3,5\]\], t = 2, target = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 0.16666666666666666 _x000D_
**Explanation:** The figure above shows the given graph. The frog starts at vertex 1, jumping with 1/3 probability to the vertex 2 after **second 1** and then jumping with 1/2 probability to vertex 4 after **second 2**. Thus the probability for the frog is on the vertex 4 after 2 seconds is 1/3 \* 1/2 = 1/6 = 0.16666666666666666. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 7, edges = \[\[1,2\],\[1,3\],\[1,7\],\[2,4\],\[2,6\],\[3,5\]\], t = 1, target = 7_x000D_
**Output:** 0.3333333333333333_x000D_
**Explanation:** The figure above shows the given graph. The frog starts at vertex 1, jumping with 1/3 = 0.3333333333333333 probability to the vertex 7 after **second 1**. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 100`_x000D_
*   `edges.length == n - 1`_x000D_
*   `edges[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= ai, bi <= n`_x000D_
*   `1 <= t <= 50`_x000D_
*   `1 <= target <= n`

title: Find a Corresponding Node of a Binary Tree in a Clone of That Tree
content:
Given two binary trees `original` and `cloned` and given a reference to a node `target` in the original tree._x000D_
_x000D_
The `cloned` tree is a **copy of** the `original` tree._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _a reference to the same node_ in the `cloned` tree._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that you are **not allowed** to change any of the two trees or the `target` node and the answer **must be** a reference to a node in the `cloned` tree._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tree = \[7,4,3,null,null,6,19\], target = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** In all examples the original and cloned trees are shown. The target node is a green node from the original tree. The answer is the yellow node from the cloned tree._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tree = \[7\], target =  7_x000D_
**Output:** 7_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** tree = \[8,null,6,null,5,null,4,null,3,null,2,null,1\], target = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the `tree` is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   The values of the nodes of the `tree` are unique._x000D_
*   `target` node is a node from the `original` tree and is not `null`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Follow up:** Could you solve the problem if repeated values on the tree are allowed?

title: Lucky Numbers in a Matrix
content:
Given an `m x n` matrix of **distinct** numbers, return _all **lucky numbers** in the matrix in **any** order_._x000D_
_x000D_
A **lucky number** is an element of the matrix such that it is the minimum element in its row and maximum in its column._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** matrix = \[\[3,7,8\],\[9,11,13\],\[15,16,17\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[15\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** 15 is the only lucky number since it is the minimum in its row and the maximum in its column._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** matrix = \[\[1,10,4,2\],\[9,3,8,7\],\[15,16,17,12\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[12\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** 12 is the only lucky number since it is the minimum in its row and the maximum in its column._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** matrix = \[\[7,8\],\[1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[7\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** 7 is the only lucky number since it is the minimum in its row and the maximum in its column._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == mat.length`_x000D_
*   `n == mat[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n, m <= 50`_x000D_
*   `1 <= matrix[i][j] <= 105`._x000D_
*   All elements in the matrix are distinct.

title: Design a Stack With Increment Operation
content:
Design a stack that supports increment operations on its elements._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `CustomStack` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `CustomStack(int maxSize)` Initializes the object with `maxSize` which is the maximum number of elements in the stack._x000D_
*   `void push(int x)` Adds `x` to the top of the stack if the stack has not reached the `maxSize`._x000D_
*   `int pop()` Pops and returns the top of the stack or `-1` if the stack is empty._x000D_
*   `void inc(int k, int val)` Increments the bottom `k` elements of the stack by `val`. If there are less than `k` elements in the stack, increment all the elements in the stack._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "CustomStack ", "push ", "push ", "pop ", "push ", "push ", "push ", "increment ", "increment ", "pop ", "pop ", "pop ", "pop "\]_x000D_
\[\[3\],\[1\],\[2\],\[\],\[2\],\[3\],\[4\],\[5,100\],\[2,100\],\[\],\[\],\[\],\[\]\]_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null,null,null,2,null,null,null,null,null,103,202,201,-1\]_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
CustomStack stk = new CustomStack(3); // Stack is Empty \[\]_x000D_
stk.push(1);                          // stack becomes \[1\]_x000D_
stk.push(2);                          // stack becomes \[1, 2\]_x000D_
stk.pop();                            // return 2 --> Return top of the stack 2, stack becomes \[1\]_x000D_
stk.push(2);                          // stack becomes \[1, 2\]_x000D_
stk.push(3);                          // stack becomes \[1, 2, 3\]_x000D_
stk.push(4);                          // stack still \[1, 2, 3\], Do not add another elements as size is 4_x000D_
stk.increment(5, 100);                // stack becomes \[101, 102, 103\]_x000D_
stk.increment(2, 100);                // stack becomes \[201, 202, 103\]_x000D_
stk.pop();                            // return 103 --> Return top of the stack 103, stack becomes \[201, 202\]_x000D_
stk.pop();                            // return 202 --> Return top of the stack 202, stack becomes \[201\]_x000D_
stk.pop();                            // return 201 --> Return top of the stack 201, stack becomes \[\]_x000D_
stk.pop();                            // return -1 --> Stack is empty return -1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= maxSize, x, k <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= val <= 100`_x000D_
*   At most `1000` calls will be made to each method of `increment`, `push` and `pop` each separately.

title: Balance a Binary Search Tree
content:
Given the `root` of a binary search tree, return _a **balanced** binary search tree with the same node values_. If there is more than one answer, return **any of them**._x000D_
_x000D_
A binary search tree is **balanced** if the depth of the two subtrees of every node never differs by more than `1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[1,null,2,null,3,null,4,null,null\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,1,3,null,null,null,4\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** This is not the only correct answer, \[3,1,4,null,2\] is also correct._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** root = \[2,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,1,3\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The number of nodes in the tree is in the range `[1, 104]`._x000D_
*   `1 <= Node.val <= 105`

title: Maximum Performance of a Team
content:
You are given two integers `n` and `k` and two integer arrays `speed` and `efficiency` both of length `n`. There are `n` engineers numbered from `1` to `n`. `speed[i]` and `efficiency[i]` represent the speed and efficiency of the `ith` engineer respectively._x000D_
_x000D_
Choose **at most** `k` different engineers out of the `n` engineers to form a team with the maximum **performance**._x000D_
_x000D_
The performance of a team is the sum of their engineers' speeds multiplied by the minimum efficiency among their engineers._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the maximum performance of this team_. Since the answer can be a huge number, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 6, speed = \[2,10,3,1,5,8\], efficiency = \[5,4,3,9,7,2\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 60_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
We have the maximum performance of the team by selecting engineer 2 (with speed=10 and efficiency=4) and engineer 5 (with speed=5 and efficiency=7). That is, performance = (10 + 5) \* min(4, 7) = 60._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 6, speed = \[2,10,3,1,5,8\], efficiency = \[5,4,3,9,7,2\], k = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 68_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
This is the same example as the first but k = 3. We can select engineer 1, engineer 2 and engineer 5 to get the maximum performance of the team. That is, performance = (2 + 10 + 5) \* min(5, 4, 7) = 68._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 6, speed = \[2,10,3,1,5,8\], efficiency = \[5,4,3,9,7,2\], k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 72_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `speed.length == n`_x000D_
*   `efficiency.length == n`_x000D_
*   `1 <= speed[i] <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= efficiency[i] <= 108`

title: Find the Distance Value Between Two Arrays
content:
Given two integer arrays `arr1` and `arr2`, and the integer `d`, _return the distance value between the two arrays_._x000D_
_x000D_
The distance value is defined as the number of elements `arr1[i]` such that there is not any element `arr2[j]` where `|arr1[i]-arr2[j]| <= d`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr1 = \[4,5,8\], arr2 = \[10,9,1,8\], d = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
For arr1\[0\]=4 we have: _x000D_
|4-10|=6 > d=2 _x000D_
|4-9|=5 > d=2 _x000D_
|4-1|=3 > d=2 _x000D_
|4-8|=4 > d=2 _x000D_
For arr1\[1\]=5 we have: _x000D_
|5-10|=5 > d=2 _x000D_
|5-9|=4 > d=2 _x000D_
|5-1|=4 > d=2 _x000D_
|5-8|=3 > d=2_x000D_
For arr1\[2\]=8 we have:_x000D_
**|8-10|=2 <= d=2**_x000D_
**|8-9|=1 <= d=2**_x000D_
|8-1|=7 > d=2_x000D_
**|8-8|=0 <= d=2**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr1 = \[1,4,2,3\], arr2 = \[-4,-3,6,10,20,30\], d = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr1 = \[2,1,100,3\], arr2 = \[-5,-2,10,-3,7\], d = 6_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= arr1.length, arr2.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= arr1[i], arr2[j] <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= d <= 100`

title: Cinema Seat Allocation
content:
A cinema has `n` rows of seats, numbered from 1 to `n` and there are ten seats in each row, labelled from 1 to 10 as shown in the figure above._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the array `reservedSeats` containing the numbers of seats already reserved, for example, `reservedSeats[i] = [3,8]` means the seat located in row **3** and labelled with **8** is already reserved._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return the maximum number of four-person groups you can assign on the cinema seats._ A four-person group occupies four adjacent seats **in one single row**. Seats across an aisle (such as \[3,3\] and \[3,4\]) are not considered to be adjacent, but there is an exceptional case on which an aisle split a four-person group, in that case, the aisle split a four-person group in the middle, which means to have two people on each side._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3, reservedSeats = \[\[1,2\],\[1,3\],\[1,8\],\[2,6\],\[3,1\],\[3,10\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** The figure above shows the optimal allocation for four groups, where seats mark with blue are already reserved and contiguous seats mark with orange are for one group._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, reservedSeats = \[\[2,1\],\[1,8\],\[2,6\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 4, reservedSeats = \[\[4,3\],\[1,4\],\[4,6\],\[1,7\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 10^9`_x000D_
*   `1 <= reservedSeats.length <= min(10*n, 10^4)`_x000D_
*   `reservedSeats[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= reservedSeats[i][0] <= n`_x000D_
*   `1 <= reservedSeats[i][1] <= 10`_x000D_
*   All `reservedSeats[i]` are distinct.

title: Pizza With 3n Slices
content:
There is a pizza with `3n` slices of varying size, you and your friends will take slices of pizza as follows:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   You will pick **any** pizza slice._x000D_
*   Your friend Alice will pick the next slice in the anti-clockwise direction of your pick._x000D_
*   Your friend Bob will pick the next slice in the clockwise direction of your pick._x000D_
*   Repeat until there are no more slices of pizzas._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an integer array `slices` that represent the sizes of the pizza slices in a clockwise direction, return _the maximum possible sum of slice sizes that you can pick_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** slices = \[1,2,3,4,5,6\]_x000D_
**Output:** 10_x000D_
**Explanation:** Pick pizza slice of size 4, Alice and Bob will pick slices with size 3 and 5 respectively. Then Pick slices with size 6, finally Alice and Bob will pick slice of size 2 and 1 respectively. Total = 4 + 6._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** slices = \[8,9,8,6,1,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 16_x000D_
**Explanation:** Pick pizza slice of size 8 in each turn. If you pick slice with size 9 your partners will pick slices of size 8._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `3 * n == slices.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= slices.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `1 <= slices[i] <= 1000`

title: Four Divisors
content:
Given an integer array `nums`, return _the sum of divisors of the integers in that array that have exactly four divisors_. If there is no such integer in the array, return `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[21,4,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** 32_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
21 has 4 divisors: 1, 3, 7, 21_x000D_
4 has 3 divisors: 1, 2, 4_x000D_
7 has 2 divisors: 1, 7_x000D_
The answer is the sum of divisors of 21 only._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[21,21\]_x000D_
**Output:** 64_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 105`

title: Check if There is a Valid Path in a Grid
content:
You are given an `m x n` `grid`. Each cell of `grid` represents a street. The street of `grid[i][j]` can be:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1` which means a street connecting the left cell and the right cell._x000D_
*   `2` which means a street connecting the upper cell and the lower cell._x000D_
*   `3` which means a street connecting the left cell and the lower cell._x000D_
*   `4` which means a street connecting the right cell and the lower cell._x000D_
*   `5` which means a street connecting the left cell and the upper cell._x000D_
*   `6` which means a street connecting the right cell and the upper cell._x000D_
_x000D_
You will initially start at the street of the upper-left cell `(0, 0)`. A valid path in the grid is a path that starts from the upper left cell `(0, 0)` and ends at the bottom-right cell `(m - 1, n - 1)`. **The path should only follow the streets**._x000D_
_x000D_
**Notice** that you are **not allowed** to change any street._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `true` _if there is a valid path in the grid or_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[2,4,3\],\[6,5,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** As shown you can start at cell (0, 0) and visit all the cells of the grid to reach (m - 1, n - 1)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,2,1\],\[1,2,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** As shown you the street at cell (0, 0) is not connected with any street of any other cell and you will get stuck at cell (0, 0)_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** You will get stuck at cell (0, 1) and you cannot reach cell (0, 2)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == grid.length`_x000D_
*   `n == grid[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 300`_x000D_
*   `1 <= grid[i][j] <= 6`

title: Find Lucky Integer in an Array
content:
Given an array of integers `arr`, a **lucky integer** is an integer that has a frequency in the array equal to its value._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the largest **lucky integer** in the array_. If there is no **lucky integer** return `-1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr = \[2,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only lucky number in the array is 2 because frequency\[2\] == 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr = \[1,2,2,3,3,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** 1, 2 and 3 are all lucky numbers, return the largest of them._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr = \[2,2,2,3,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are no lucky numbers in the array._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= arr.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `1 <= arr[i] <= 500`

title: Count Number of Teams
content:
There are `n` soldiers standing in a line. Each soldier is assigned a **unique** `rating` value._x000D_
_x000D_
You have to form a team of 3 soldiers amongst them under the following rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Choose 3 soldiers with index (`i`, `j`, `k`) with rating (`rating[i]`, `rating[j]`, `rating[k]`)._x000D_
*   A team is valid if: (`rating[i] < rating[j] < rating[k]`) or (`rating[i] > rating[j] > rating[k]`) where (`0 <= i < j < k < n`)._x000D_
_x000D_
Return the number of teams you can form given the conditions. (soldiers can be part of multiple teams)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rating = \[2,5,3,4,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can form three teams given the conditions. (2,3,4), (5,4,1), (5,3,1). _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rating = \[2,1,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can't form any team given the conditions._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** rating = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == rating.length`_x000D_
*   `3 <= n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= rating[i] <= 105`_x000D_
*   All the integers in `rating` are **unique**._x000D_
_x000D_
In one second, you can either: - Move vertically by one unit, - Move horizontally by one unit, or - Move diagonally sqrt(2) units (in other words, move one unit vertically then one unit horizontally in one second). You have to visit the points in the same order as they appear in the array. You are allowed to pass through points, but they do not count as visited unless you stop on them.

title: Design Underground System
content:
An underground railway system is keeping track of customer travel times between different stations. They are using this data to calculate the average time it takes to travel from one station to another._x000D_
_x000D_
Implement the `UndergroundSystem` class:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `void checkIn(int id, string stationName, int t)`_x000D_
    *   A customer with a card ID equal to `id`, checks in at the station `stationName` at time `t`._x000D_
    *   A customer can only be checked into one place at a time._x000D_
*   `void checkOut(int id, string stationName, int t)`_x000D_
    *   A customer with a card ID equal to `id`, checks out from the station `stationName` at time `t`._x000D_
*   `double getAverageTime(string startStation, string endStation)`_x000D_
    *   Returns the average time it takes to travel from `startStation` to `endStation`._x000D_
    *   The average time is computed from all the previous traveling times from `startStation` to `endStation` that happened **directly**, meaning a check in at `startStation` followed by a check out from `endStation`._x000D_
    *   The time it takes to travel from `startStation` to `endStation` **may be different** from the time it takes to travel from `endStation` to `startStation`._x000D_
    *   There will be at least one customer that has traveled from `startStation` to `endStation` before `getAverageTime` is called._x000D_
_x000D_
You may assume all calls to the `checkIn` and `checkOut` methods are consistent. If a customer checks in at time `t1` then checks out at time `t2`, then `t1 < t2`. All events happen in chronological order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "UndergroundSystem ", "checkIn ", "checkIn ", "checkIn ", "checkOut ", "checkOut ", "checkOut ", "getAverageTime ", "getAverageTime ", "checkIn ", "getAverageTime ", "checkOut ", "getAverageTime "\]_x000D_
\[\[\],\[45, "Leyton ",3\],\[32, "Paradise ",8\],\[27, "Leyton ",10\],\[45, "Waterloo ",15\],\[27, "Waterloo ",20\],\[32, "Cambridge ",22\],\[ "Paradise ", "Cambridge "\],\[ "Leyton ", "Waterloo "\],\[10, "Leyton ",24\],\[ "Leyton ", "Waterloo "\],\[10, "Waterloo ",38\],\[ "Leyton ", "Waterloo "\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null,null,null,null,null,null,null,14.00000,11.00000,null,11.00000,null,12.00000\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
UndergroundSystem undergroundSystem = new UndergroundSystem();_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(45,  "Leyton ", 3);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(32,  "Paradise ", 8);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(27,  "Leyton ", 10);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(45,  "Waterloo ", 15);  // Customer 45  "Leyton " ->  "Waterloo " in 15-3 = 12_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(27,  "Waterloo ", 20);  // Customer 27  "Leyton " ->  "Waterloo " in 20-10 = 10_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(32,  "Cambridge ", 22); // Customer 32  "Paradise " ->  "Cambridge " in 22-8 = 14_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Paradise ",  "Cambridge "); // return 14.00000. One trip  "Paradise " ->  "Cambridge ", (14) / 1 = 14_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Waterloo ");    // return 11.00000. Two trips  "Leyton " ->  "Waterloo ", (10 + 12) / 2 = 11_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(10,  "Leyton ", 24);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Waterloo ");    // return 11.00000_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(10,  "Waterloo ", 38);  // Customer 10  "Leyton " ->  "Waterloo " in 38-24 = 14_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Waterloo ");    // return 12.00000. Three trips  "Leyton " ->  "Waterloo ", (10 + 12 + 14) / 3 = 12_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input**_x000D_
\[ "UndergroundSystem ", "checkIn ", "checkOut ", "getAverageTime ", "checkIn ", "checkOut ", "getAverageTime ", "checkIn ", "checkOut ", "getAverageTime "\]_x000D_
\[\[\],\[10, "Leyton ",3\],\[10, "Paradise ",8\],\[ "Leyton ", "Paradise "\],\[5, "Leyton ",10\],\[5, "Paradise ",16\],\[ "Leyton ", "Paradise "\],\[2, "Leyton ",21\],\[2, "Paradise ",30\],\[ "Leyton ", "Paradise "\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Output**_x000D_
\[null,null,null,5.00000,null,null,5.50000,null,null,6.66667\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Explanation**_x000D_
UndergroundSystem undergroundSystem = new UndergroundSystem();_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(10,  "Leyton ", 3);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(10,  "Paradise ", 8); // Customer 10  "Leyton " ->  "Paradise " in 8-3 = 5_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Paradise "); // return 5.00000, (5) / 1 = 5_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(5,  "Leyton ", 10);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(5,  "Paradise ", 16); // Customer 5  "Leyton " ->  "Paradise " in 16-10 = 6_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Paradise "); // return 5.50000, (5 + 6) / 2 = 5.5_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkIn(2,  "Leyton ", 21);_x000D_
undergroundSystem.checkOut(2,  "Paradise ", 30); // Customer 2  "Leyton " ->  "Paradise " in 30-21 = 9_x000D_
undergroundSystem.getAverageTime( "Leyton ",  "Paradise "); // return 6.66667, (5 + 6 + 9) / 3 = 6.66667_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= id, t <= 106`_x000D_
*   `1 <= stationName.length, startStation.length, endStation.length <= 10`_x000D_
*   All strings consist of uppercase and lowercase English letters and digits._x000D_
*   There will be at most `2 * 104` calls **in total** to `checkIn`, `checkOut`, and `getAverageTime`._x000D_
*   Answers within `10-5` of the actual value will be accepted.

title: Find All Good Strings
content:
Given the strings `s1` and `s2` of size `n` and the string `evil`, return _the number of **good** strings_._x000D_
_x000D_
A **good** string has size `n`, it is alphabetically greater than or equal to `s1`, it is alphabetically smaller than or equal to `s2`, and it does not contain the string `evil` as a substring. Since the answer can be a huge number, return this **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, s1 =  "aa ", s2 =  "da ", evil =  "b "_x000D_
**Output:** 51 _x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 25 good strings starting with 'a':  "aa ", "ac ", "ad ",..., "az ". Then there are 25 good strings starting with 'c':  "ca ", "cc ", "cd ",..., "cz " and finally there is one good string starting with 'd':  "da ". _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 8, s1 =  "leetcode ", s2 =  "leetgoes ", evil =  "leet "_x000D_
**Output:** 0 _x000D_
**Explanation:** All strings greater than or equal to s1 and smaller than or equal to s2 start with the prefix  "leet ", therefore, there is not any good string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, s1 =  "gx ", s2 =  "gz ", evil =  "x "_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `s1.length == n`_x000D_
*   `s2.length == n`_x000D_
*   `s1 <= s2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 500`_x000D_
*   `1 <= evil.length <= 50`_x000D_
*   All strings consist of lowercase English letters.

title: Count Largest Group
content:
You are given an integer `n`._x000D_
_x000D_
Each number from `1` to `n` is grouped according to the sum of its digits._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of groups that have the largest size_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 13_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 9 groups in total, they are grouped according sum of its digits of numbers from 1 to 13:_x000D_
\[1,10\], \[2,11\], \[3,12\], \[4,13\], \[5\], \[6\], \[7\], \[8\], \[9\]._x000D_
There are 4 groups with largest size._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 2 groups \[1\], \[2\] of size 1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 104`

title: Construct K Palindrome Strings
content:
Given a string `s` and an integer `k`, return `true` _if you can use all the characters in_ `s` _to construct_ `k` _palindrome strings or_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "annabelle ", k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can construct two palindromes using all characters in s._x000D_
Some possible constructions  "anna " +  "elble ",  "anbna " +  "elle ",  "anellena " +  "b "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "leetcode ", k = 3_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** It is impossible to construct 3 palindromes using all the characters of s._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "true ", k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only possible solution is to put each character in a separate string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 105`

title: Circle and Rectangle Overlapping
content:
You are given a circle represented as `(radius, xCenter, yCenter)` and an axis-aligned rectangle represented as `(x1, y1, x2, y2)`, where `(x1, y1)` are the coordinates of the bottom-left corner, and `(x2, y2)` are the coordinates of the top-right corner of the rectangle._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `true` _if the circle and rectangle are overlapped otherwise return_ `false`. In other words, check if there is **any** point `(xi, yi)` that belongs to the circle and the rectangle at the same time._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** radius = 1, xCenter = 0, yCenter = 0, x1 = 1, y1 = -1, x2 = 3, y2 = 1_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** Circle and rectangle share the point (1,0)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** radius = 1, xCenter = 1, yCenter = 1, x1 = 1, y1 = -3, x2 = 2, y2 = -1_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** radius = 1, xCenter = 0, yCenter = 0, x1 = -1, y1 = 0, x2 = 0, y2 = 1_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= radius <= 2000`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= xCenter, yCenter <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= x1 < x2 <= 104`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= y1 < y2 <= 104`

title: Reducing Dishes
content:
A chef has collected data on the `satisfaction` level of his `n` dishes. Chef can cook any dish in 1 unit of time._x000D_
_x000D_
**Like-time coefficient** of a dish is defined as the time taken to cook that dish including previous dishes multiplied by its satisfaction level i.e. `time[i] * satisfaction[i]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the maximum sum of **like-time coefficient** that the chef can obtain after dishes preparation_._x000D_
_x000D_
Dishes can be prepared in **any** order and the chef can discard some dishes to get this maximum value._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** satisfaction = \[-1,-8,0,5,-9\]_x000D_
**Output:** 14_x000D_
**Explanation:** After Removing the second and last dish, the maximum total **like-time coefficient** will be equal to (-1\*1 + 0\*2 + 5\*3 = 14)._x000D_
Each dish is prepared in one unit of time._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** satisfaction = \[4,3,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 20_x000D_
**Explanation:** Dishes can be prepared in any order, (2\*1 + 3\*2 + 4\*3 = 20)_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** satisfaction = \[-1,-4,-5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** People do not like the dishes. No dish is prepared._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == satisfaction.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 500`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= satisfaction[i] <= 1000`

title: Minimum Subsequence in Non-Increasing Order
content:
Given the array `nums`, obtain a subsequence of the array whose sum of elements is **strictly greater** than the sum of the non included elements in such subsequence._x000D_
_x000D_
If there are multiple solutions, return the subsequence with **minimum size** and if there still exist multiple solutions, return the subsequence with the **maximum total sum** of all its elements. A subsequence of an array can be obtained by erasing some (possibly zero) elements from the array._x000D_
_x000D_
Note that the solution with the given constraints is guaranteed to be **unique**. Also return the answer sorted in **non-increasing** order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[4,3,10,9,8\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[10,9\] _x000D_
**Explanation:** The subsequences \[10,9\] and \[10,8\] are minimal such that the sum of their elements is strictly greater than the sum of elements not included. However, the subsequence \[10,9\] has the maximum total sum of its elements. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[4,4,7,6,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[7,7,6\] _x000D_
**Explanation:** The subsequence \[7,7\] has the sum of its elements equal to 14 which is not strictly greater than the sum of elements not included (14 = 4 + 4 + 6). Therefore, the subsequence \[7,6,7\] is the minimal satisfying the conditions. Note the subsequence has to be returned in non-decreasing order.  _x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 100`

title: Number of Steps to Reduce a Number in Binary Representation to One
content:
Given the binary representation of an integer as a string `s`, return _the number of steps to reduce it to_ `1` _under the following rules_:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   If the current number is even, you have to divide it by `2`._x000D_
    _x000D_
*   If the current number is odd, you have to add `1` to it._x000D_
    _x000D_
_x000D_
It is guaranteed that you can always reach one for all test cases._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1101 "_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "1101 " corressponds to number 13 in their decimal representation._x000D_
Step 1) 13 is odd, add 1 and obtain 14. _x000D_
Step 2) 14 is even, divide by 2 and obtain 7._x000D_
Step 3) 7 is odd, add 1 and obtain 8._x000D_
Step 4) 8 is even, divide by 2 and obtain 4.  _x000D_
Step 5) 4 is even, divide by 2 and obtain 2. _x000D_
Step 6) 2 is even, divide by 2 and obtain 1.  _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "10 "_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "10 " corressponds to number 2 in their decimal representation._x000D_
Step 1) 2 is even, divide by 2 and obtain 1.  _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1 "_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of characters '0' or '1'_x000D_
*   `s[0] == '1'`

title: Longest Happy String
content:
A string `s` is called **happy** if it satisfies the following conditions:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `s` only contains the letters `'a'`, `'b'`, and `'c'`._x000D_
*   `s` does not contain any of `"aaa "`, `"bbb "`, or `"ccc "` as a substring._x000D_
*   `s` contains **at most** `a` occurrences of the letter `'a'`._x000D_
*   `s` contains **at most** `b` occurrences of the letter `'b'`._x000D_
*   `s` contains **at most** `c` occurrences of the letter `'c'`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given three integers `a`, `b`, and `c`, return _the **longest possible happy** string_. If there are multiple longest happy strings, return _any of them_. If there is no such string, return _the empty string_ `" "`._x000D_
_x000D_
A **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within a string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** a = 1, b = 1, c = 7_x000D_
**Output:**  "ccaccbcc "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "ccbccacc " would also be a correct answer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** a = 7, b = 1, c = 0_x000D_
**Output:**  "aabaa "_x000D_
**Explanation:** It is the only correct answer in this case._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= a, b, c <= 100`_x000D_
*   `a + b + c > 0`

title: Stone Game III
content:
Alice and Bob continue their games with piles of stones. There are several stones **arranged in a row**, and each stone has an associated value which is an integer given in the array `stoneValue`._x000D_
_x000D_
Alice and Bob take turns, with Alice starting first. On each player's turn, that player can take `1`, `2`, or `3` stones from the **first** remaining stones in the row._x000D_
_x000D_
The score of each player is the sum of the values of the stones taken. The score of each player is `0` initially._x000D_
_x000D_
The objective of the game is to end with the highest score, and the winner is the player with the highest score and there could be a tie. The game continues until all the stones have been taken._x000D_
_x000D_
Assume Alice and Bob **play optimally**._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `"Alice "` _if Alice will win,_ `"Bob "` _if Bob will win, or_ `"Tie "` _if they will end the game with the same score_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** values = \[1,2,3,7\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "Bob "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice will always lose. Her best move will be to take three piles and the score become 6. Now the score of Bob is 7 and Bob wins._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** values = \[1,2,3,-9\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "Alice "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice must choose all the three piles at the first move to win and leave Bob with negative score._x000D_
If Alice chooses one pile her score will be 1 and the next move Bob's score becomes 5. In the next move, Alice will take the pile with value = -9 and lose._x000D_
If Alice chooses two piles her score will be 3 and the next move Bob's score becomes 3. In the next move, Alice will take the pile with value = -9 and also lose._x000D_
Remember that both play optimally so here Alice will choose the scenario that makes her win._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** values = \[1,2,3,6\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "Tie "_x000D_
**Explanation:** Alice cannot win this game. She can end the game in a draw if she decided to choose all the first three piles, otherwise she will lose._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= stoneValue.length <= 5 * 104`_x000D_
*   `-1000 <= stoneValue[i] <= 1000`

title: String Matching in an Array
content:
Given an array of string `words`, return _all strings in_ `words` _that is a **substring** of another word_. You can return the answer in **any order**._x000D_
_x000D_
A **substring** is a contiguous sequence of characters within a string_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** words = \[ "mass ", "as ", "hero ", "superhero "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "as ", "hero "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "as " is substring of  "mass " and  "hero " is substring of  "superhero "._x000D_
\[ "hero ", "as "\] is also a valid answer._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** words = \[ "leetcode ", "et ", "code "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[ "et ", "code "\]_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "et ",  "code " are substring of  "leetcode "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** words = \[ "blue ", "green ", "bu "\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** No string of words is substring of another string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= words.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `1 <= words[i].length <= 30`_x000D_
*   `words[i]` contains only lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   All the strings of `words` are **unique**.

title: Queries on a Permutation With Key
content:
Given the array `queries` of positive integers between `1` and `m`, you have to process all `queries[i]` (from `i=0` to `i=queries.length-1`) according to the following rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   In the beginning, you have the permutation `P=[1,2,3,...,m]`._x000D_
*   For the current `i`, find the position of `queries[i]` in the permutation `P` (**indexing from 0**) and then move this at the beginning of the permutation `P.` Notice that the position of `queries[i]` in `P` is the result for `queries[i]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return an array containing the result for the given `queries`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** queries = \[3,1,2,1\], m = 5_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,1,2,1\] _x000D_
**Explanation:** The queries are processed as follow: _x000D_
For i=0: queries\[i\]=3, P=\[1,2,3,4,5\], position of 3 in P is **2**, then we move 3 to the beginning of P resulting in P=\[3,1,2,4,5\]. _x000D_
For i=1: queries\[i\]=1, P=\[3,1,2,4,5\], position of 1 in P is **1**, then we move 1 to the beginning of P resulting in P=\[1,3,2,4,5\]. _x000D_
For i=2: queries\[i\]=2, P=\[1,3,2,4,5\], position of 2 in P is **2**, then we move 2 to the beginning of P resulting in P=\[2,1,3,4,5\]. _x000D_
For i=3: queries\[i\]=1, P=\[2,1,3,4,5\], position of 1 in P is **1**, then we move 1 to the beginning of P resulting in P=\[1,2,3,4,5\]. _x000D_
Therefore, the array containing the result is \[2,1,2,1\].  _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** queries = \[4,1,2,2\], m = 4_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,1,2,0\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** queries = \[7,5,5,8,3\], m = 8_x000D_
**Output:** \[6,5,0,7,5\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= m <= 10^3`_x000D_
*   `1 <= queries.length <= m`_x000D_
*   `1 <= queries[i] <= m`

title: HTML Entity Parser
content:
**HTML entity parser** is the parser that takes HTML code as input and replace all the entities of the special characters by the characters itself._x000D_
_x000D_
The special characters and their entities for HTML are:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   **Quotation Mark:** the entity is `"` and symbol character is `"`._x000D_
*   **Single Quote Mark:** the entity is `'` and symbol character is `'`._x000D_
*   **Ampersand:** the entity is `&` and symbol character is `&`._x000D_
*   **Greater Than Sign:** the entity is `>` and symbol character is `>`._x000D_
*   **Less Than Sign:** the entity is `<` and symbol character is `<`._x000D_
*   **Slash:** the entity is `⁄` and symbol character is `/`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the input `text` string to the HTML parser, you have to implement the entity parser._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the text after replacing the entities by the special characters_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** text =  "& is an HTML entity but &ambassador; is not. "_x000D_
**Output:**  "& is an HTML entity but &ambassador; is not. "_x000D_
**Explanation:** The parser will replace the & entity by &_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** text =  "and I quote: "..." "_x000D_
**Output:**  "and I quote: \\ "...\\ " "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= text.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   The string may contain any possible characters out of all the 256 ASCII characters.

title: Number of Ways to Paint N × 3 Grid
content:
You have a `grid` of size `n x 3` and you want to paint each cell of the grid with exactly one of the three colors: **Red**, **Yellow,** or **Green** while making sure that no two adjacent cells have the same color (i.e., no two cells that share vertical or horizontal sides have the same color)._x000D_
_x000D_
Given `n` the number of rows of the grid, return _the number of ways_ you can paint this `grid`. As the answer may grow large, the answer **must be** computed modulo `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 12 possible way to paint the grid as shown._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 5000_x000D_
**Output:** 30228214_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `n == grid.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 5000`

title: Minimum Value to Get Positive Step by Step Sum
content:
Given an array of integers `nums`, you start with an initial **positive** value _startValue__.__x000D_
_x000D_
In each iteration, you calculate the step by step sum of _startValue_ plus elements in `nums` (from left to right)._x000D_
_x000D_
Return the minimum **positive** value of _startValue_ such that the step by step sum is never less than 1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[-3,2,-3,4,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** If you choose startValue = 4, in the third iteration your step by step sum is less than 1._x000D_
**step by step sum**_x000D_
**startValue = 4 | startValue = 5 | nums**_x000D_
  (4 **\-3** ) = 1  | (5 **\-3** ) = 2    |  -3_x000D_
  (1 **+2** ) = 3  | (2 **+2** ) = 4    |   2_x000D_
  (3 **\-3** ) = 0  | (4 **\-3** ) = 1    |  -3_x000D_
  (0 **+4** ) = 4  | (1 **+4** ) = 5    |   4_x000D_
  (4 **+2** ) = 6  | (5 **+2** ) = 7    |   2_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** Minimum start value should be positive. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,-2,-3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `-100 <= nums[i] <= 100`

title: Find the Minimum Number of Fibonacci Numbers Whose Sum Is K
content:
Given an integer `k`, _return the minimum number of Fibonacci numbers whose sum is equal to_ `k`. The same Fibonacci number can be used multiple times._x000D_
_x000D_
The Fibonacci numbers are defined as:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `F1 = 1`_x000D_
*   `F2 = 1`_x000D_
*   `Fn = Fn-1 + Fn-2` for `n > 2.`_x000D_
_x000D_
It is guaranteed that for the given constraints we can always find such Fibonacci numbers that sum up to `k`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** k = 7_x000D_
**Output:** 2 _x000D_
**Explanation:** The Fibonacci numbers are: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ... _x000D_
For k = 7 we can use 2 + 5 = 7._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** k = 10_x000D_
**Output:** 2 _x000D_
**Explanation:** For k = 10 we can use 2 + 8 = 10._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** k = 19_x000D_
**Output:** 3 _x000D_
**Explanation:** For k = 19 we can use 1 + 5 + 13 = 19._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 109`

title: The k-th Lexicographical String of All Happy Strings of Length n
content:
A **happy string** is a string that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   consists only of letters of the set `['a', 'b', 'c']`._x000D_
*   `s[i] != s[i + 1]` for all values of `i` from `1` to `s.length - 1` (string is 1-indexed)._x000D_
_x000D_
For example, strings **"abc ", "ac ", "b "** and **"abcbabcbcb "** are all happy strings and strings **"aa ", "baa "** and **"ababbc "** are not happy strings._x000D_
_x000D_
Given two integers `n` and `k`, consider a list of all happy strings of length `n` sorted in lexicographical order._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the kth string_ of this list or return an **empty string** if there are less than `k` happy strings of length `n`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1, k = 3_x000D_
**Output:**  "c "_x000D_
**Explanation:** The list \[ "a ",  "b ",  "c "\] contains all happy strings of length 1. The third string is  "c "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 1, k = 4_x000D_
**Output:**  " "_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are only 3 happy strings of length 1._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3, k = 9_x000D_
**Output:**  "cab "_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 12 different happy string of length 3 \[ "aba ",  "abc ",  "aca ",  "acb ",  "bab ",  "bac ",  "bca ",  "bcb ",  "cab ",  "cac ",  "cba ",  "cbc "\]. You will find the 9th string =  "cab "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 10`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 100`

title: Restore The Array
content:
A program was supposed to print an array of integers. The program forgot to print whitespaces and the array is printed as a string of digits `s` and all we know is that all integers in the array were in the range `[1, k]` and there are no leading zeros in the array._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the string `s` and the integer `k`, return _the number of the possible arrays that can be printed as_ `s` _using the mentioned program_. Since the answer may be very large, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1000 ", k = 10000_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only possible array is \[1000\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1000 ", k = 10_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** There cannot be an array that was printed this way and has all integer >= 1 and <= 10._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1317 ", k = 2000_x000D_
**Output:** 8_x000D_
**Explanation:** Possible arrays are \[1317\],\[131,7\],\[13,17\],\[1,317\],\[13,1,7\],\[1,31,7\],\[1,3,17\],\[1,3,1,7\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of only digits and does not contain leading zeros._x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 109`

title: Reformat The String
content:
You are given an alphanumeric string `s`. (**Alphanumeric string** is a string consisting of lowercase English letters and digits)._x000D_
_x000D_
You have to find a permutation of the string where no letter is followed by another letter and no digit is followed by another digit. That is, no two adjacent characters have the same type._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the reformatted string_ or return **an empty string** if it is impossible to reformat the string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "a0b1c2 "_x000D_
**Output:**  "0a1b2c "_x000D_
**Explanation:** No two adjacent characters have the same type in  "0a1b2c ".  "a0b1c2 ",  "0a1b2c ",  "0c2a1b " are also valid permutations._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "leetcode "_x000D_
**Output:**  " "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "leetcode " has only characters so we cannot separate them by digits._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1229857369 "_x000D_
**Output:**  " "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  "1229857369 " has only digits so we cannot separate them by characters._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   `s` consists of only lowercase English letters and/or digits.

title: Display Table of Food Orders in a Restaurant
content:
Given the array `orders`, which represents the orders that customers have done in a restaurant. More specifically `orders[i]=[customerNamei,tableNumberi,foodItemi]` where `customerNamei` is the name of the customer, `tableNumberi` is the table customer sit at, and `foodItemi` is the item customer orders._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return the restaurant's "**display table**"_. The "**display table**" is a table whose row entries denote how many of each food item each table ordered. The first column is the table number and the remaining columns correspond to each food item in alphabetical order. The first row should be a header whose first column is "Table", followed by the names of the food items. Note that the customer names are not part of the table. Additionally, the rows should be sorted in numerically increasing order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** orders = \[\[ "David ", "3 ", "Ceviche "\],\[ "Corina ", "10 ", "Beef Burrito "\],\[ "David ", "3 ", "Fried Chicken "\],\[ "Carla ", "5 ", "Water "\],\[ "Carla ", "5 ", "Ceviche "\],\[ "Rous ", "3 ", "Ceviche "\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "Table ", "Beef Burrito ", "Ceviche ", "Fried Chicken ", "Water "\],\[ "3 ", "0 ", "2 ", "1 ", "0 "\],\[ "5 ", "0 ", "1 ", "0 ", "1 "\],\[ "10 ", "1 ", "0 ", "0 ", "0 "\]\] _x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
The displaying table looks like:_x000D_
**Table,Beef Burrito,Ceviche,Fried Chicken,Water**_x000D_
3    ,0           ,2      ,1            ,0_x000D_
5    ,0           ,1      ,0            ,1_x000D_
10   ,1           ,0      ,0            ,0_x000D_
For the table 3: David orders  "Ceviche " and  "Fried Chicken ", and Rous orders  "Ceviche "._x000D_
For the table 5: Carla orders  "Water " and  "Ceviche "._x000D_
For the table 10: Corina orders  "Beef Burrito ". _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** orders = \[\[ "James ", "12 ", "Fried Chicken "\],\[ "Ratesh ", "12 ", "Fried Chicken "\],\[ "Amadeus ", "12 ", "Fried Chicken "\],\[ "Adam ", "1 ", "Canadian Waffles "\],\[ "Brianna ", "1 ", "Canadian Waffles "\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "Table ", "Canadian Waffles ", "Fried Chicken "\],\[ "1 ", "2 ", "0 "\],\[ "12 ", "0 ", "3 "\]\] _x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
For the table 1: Adam and Brianna order  "Canadian Waffles "._x000D_
For the table 12: James, Ratesh and Amadeus order  "Fried Chicken "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** orders = \[\[ "Laura ", "2 ", "Bean Burrito "\],\[ "Jhon ", "2 ", "Beef Burrito "\],\[ "Melissa ", "2 ", "Soda "\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[ "Table ", "Bean Burrito ", "Beef Burrito ", "Soda "\],\[ "2 ", "1 ", "1 ", "1 "\]\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= orders.length <= 5 * 10^4`_x000D_
*   `orders[i].length == 3`_x000D_
*   `1 <= customerNamei.length, foodItemi.length <= 20`_x000D_
*   `customerNamei` and `foodItemi` consist of lowercase and uppercase English letters and the space character._x000D_
*   `tableNumberi` is a valid integer between `1` and `500`.

title: Minimum Number of Frogs Croaking
content:
You are given the string `croakOfFrogs`, which represents a combination of the string `"croak "` from different frogs, that is, multiple frogs can croak at the same time, so multiple `"croak "` are mixed._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return the minimum number of_ different _frogs to finish all the croaks in the given string.__x000D_
_x000D_
A valid `"croak "` means a frog is printing five letters `'c'`, `'r'`, `'o'`, `'a'`, and `'k'` **sequentially**. The frogs have to print all five letters to finish a croak. If the given string is not a combination of a valid `"croak "` return `-1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** croakOfFrogs =  "croakcroak "_x000D_
**Output:** 1 _x000D_
**Explanation:** One frog yelling  "croak **"** twice._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** croakOfFrogs =  "crcoakroak "_x000D_
**Output:** 2 _x000D_
**Explanation:** The minimum number of frogs is two. _x000D_
The first frog could yell  "**cr**c**oak**roak "._x000D_
The second frog could yell later  "cr**c**oak**roak** "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** croakOfFrogs =  "croakcrook "_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The given string is an invalid combination of  "croak **"** from different frogs._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= croakOfFrogs.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `croakOfFrogs` is either `'c'`, `'r'`, `'o'`, `'a'`, or `'k'`.

title: Build Array Where You Can Find The Maximum Exactly K Comparisons
content:
You are given three integers `n`, `m` and `k`. Consider the following algorithm to find the maximum element of an array of positive integers:_x000D_
_x000D_
You should build the array arr which has the following properties:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `arr` has exactly `n` integers._x000D_
*   `1 <= arr[i] <= m` where `(0 <= i < n)`._x000D_
*   After applying the mentioned algorithm to `arr`, the value `search_cost` is equal to `k`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of ways_ to build the array `arr` under the mentioned conditions. As the answer may grow large, the answer **must be** computed modulo `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 2, m = 3, k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** The possible arrays are \[1, 1\], \[2, 1\], \[2, 2\], \[3, 1\], \[3, 2\] \[3, 3\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 5, m = 2, k = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are no possible arrays that satisify the mentioned conditions._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 9, m = 1, k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only possible array is \[1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1\]_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 50`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m <= 100`_x000D_
*   `0 <= k <= n`

title: Maximum Score After Splitting a String
content:
Given a string `s` of zeros and ones, _return the maximum score after splitting the string into two **non-empty** substrings_ (i.e. **left** substring and **right** substring)._x000D_
_x000D_
The score after splitting a string is the number of **zeros** in the **left** substring plus the number of **ones** in the **right** substring._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "011101 "_x000D_
**Output:** 5 _x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
All possible ways of splitting s into two non-empty substrings are:_x000D_
left =  "0 " and right =  "11101 ", score = 1 + 4 = 5 _x000D_
left =  "01 " and right =  "1101 ", score = 1 + 3 = 4 _x000D_
left =  "011 " and right =  "101 ", score = 1 + 2 = 3 _x000D_
left =  "0111 " and right =  "01 ", score = 1 + 1 = 2 _x000D_
left =  "01110 " and right =  "1 ", score = 2 + 1 = 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "00111 "_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** When left =  "00 " and right =  "111 ", we get the maximum score = 2 + 3 = 5_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1111 "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `2 <= s.length <= 500`_x000D_
*   The string `s` consists of characters `'0'` and `'1'` only.

title: Maximum Points You Can Obtain from Cards
content:
There are several cards **arranged in a row**, and each card has an associated number of points. The points are given in the integer array `cardPoints`._x000D_
_x000D_
In one step, you can take one card from the beginning or from the end of the row. You have to take exactly `k` cards._x000D_
_x000D_
Your score is the sum of the points of the cards you have taken._x000D_
_x000D_
Given the integer array `cardPoints` and the integer `k`, return the _maximum score_ you can obtain._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** cardPoints = \[1,2,3,4,5,6,1\], k = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 12_x000D_
**Explanation:** After the first step, your score will always be 1. However, choosing the rightmost card first will maximize your total score. The optimal strategy is to take the three cards on the right, giving a final score of 1 + 6 + 5 = 12._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** cardPoints = \[2,2,2\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** Regardless of which two cards you take, your score will always be 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** cardPoints = \[9,7,7,9,7,7,9\], k = 7_x000D_
**Output:** 55_x000D_
**Explanation:** You have to take all the cards. Your score is the sum of points of all cards._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= cardPoints.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= cardPoints[i] <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= cardPoints.length`_x000D_
_x000D_
1\. The number of unique characters in the substring must not exceed k. 2. The substring must not contain more than one instance of the same character. 3. The length of the substring must not exceed the length of the original string.

title: Constrained Subsequence Sum
content:
Given an integer array `nums` and an integer `k`, return the maximum sum of a **non-empty** subsequence of that array such that for every two **consecutive** integers in the subsequence, `nums[i]` and `nums[j]`, where `i < j`, the condition `j - i <= k` is satisfied._x000D_
_x000D_
A _subsequence_ of an array is obtained by deleting some number of elements (can be zero) from the array, leaving the remaining elements in their original order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[10,2,-10,5,20\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 37_x000D_
**Explanation:** The subsequence is \[10, 2, 5, 20\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[-1,-2,-3\], k = 1_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** The subsequence must be non-empty, so we choose the largest number._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[10,-2,-10,-5,20\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 23_x000D_
**Explanation:** The subsequence is \[10, -2, -5, 20\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `-104 <= nums[i] <= 104`

title: Counting Elements
content:
Given an integer array `arr`, count how many elements `x` there are, such that `x + 1` is also in `arr`. If there are duplicates in `arr`, count them separately._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr = \[1,2,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** 1 and 2 are counted cause 2 and 3 are in arr._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** arr = \[1,1,3,3,5,5,7,7\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** No numbers are counted, cause there is no 2, 4, 6, or 8 in arr._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= arr.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= arr[i] <= 1000`

title: Perform String Shifts
content:
You are given a string `s` containing lowercase English letters, and a matrix `shift`, where `shift[i] = [directioni, amounti]`:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `directioni` can be `0` (for left shift) or `1` (for right shift)._x000D_
*   `amounti` is the amount by which string `s` is to be shifted._x000D_
*   A left shift by 1 means remove the first character of `s` and append it to the end._x000D_
*   Similarly, a right shift by 1 means remove the last character of `s` and add it to the beginning._x000D_
_x000D_
Return the final string after all operations._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "abc ", shift = \[\[0,1\],\[1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "cab "_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
\[0,1\] means shift to left by 1.  "abc " ->  "bca "_x000D_
\[1,2\] means shift to right by 2.  "bca " ->  "cab "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "abcdefg ", shift = \[\[1,1\],\[1,1\],\[0,2\],\[1,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "efgabcd "_x000D_
**Explanation:**  _x000D_
\[1,1\] means shift to right by 1.  "abcdefg " ->  "gabcdef "_x000D_
\[1,1\] means shift to right by 1.  "gabcdef " ->  "fgabcde "_x000D_
\[0,2\] means shift to left by 2.  "fgabcde " ->  "abcdefg "_x000D_
\[1,3\] means shift to right by 3.  "abcdefg " ->  "efgabcd "_x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `s` only contains lower case English letters._x000D_
*   `1 <= shift.length <= 100`_x000D_
*   `shift[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `directioni` is either `0` or `1`._x000D_
*   `0 <= amounti <= 100`

title: Leftmost Column with at Least a One
content:
A **row-sorted binary matrix** means that all elements are `0` or `1` and each row of the matrix is sorted in non-decreasing order._x000D_
_x000D_
Given a **row-sorted binary matrix** `binaryMatrix`, return _the index (0-indexed) of the **leftmost column** with a 1 in it_. If such an index does not exist, return `-1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**You can't access the Binary Matrix directly.** You may only access the matrix using a `BinaryMatrix` interface:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `BinaryMatrix.get(row, col)` returns the element of the matrix at index `(row, col)` (0-indexed)._x000D_
*   `BinaryMatrix.dimensions()` returns the dimensions of the matrix as a list of 2 elements `[rows, cols]`, which means the matrix is `rows x cols`._x000D_
_x000D_
