title: Maximum Price to Fill a Bag
content:
You are given a 2D integer array `items` where `items[i] = [pricei, weighti]` denotes the price and weight of the `ith` item, respectively._x000D_
_x000D_
You are also given a **positive** integer `capacity`._x000D_
_x000D_
Each item can be divided into two items with ratios `part1` and `part2`, where `part1 + part2 == 1`._x000D_
_x000D_
*   The weight of the first item is `weighti * part1` and the price of the first item is `pricei * part1`._x000D_
*   Similarly, the weight of the second item is `weighti * part2` and the price of the second item is `pricei * part2`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _**the maximum total price** to fill a bag of capacity_ `capacity` _with given items_. If it is impossible to fill a bag return `-1`. Answers within `10-5` of the **actual answer** will be considered accepted._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** items = \[\[50,1\],\[10,8\]\], capacity = 5_x000D_
**Output:** 55.00000_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
We divide the 2nd item into two parts with part1 = 0.5 and part2 = 0.5._x000D_
The price and weight of the 1st item are 5, 4. And similarly, the price and the weight of the 2nd item are 5, 4._x000D_
The array items after operation becomes \[\[50,1\],\[5,4\],\[5,4\]\]. _x000D_
To fill a bag with capacity 5 we take the 1st element with a price of 50 and the 2nd element with a price of 5._x000D_
It can be proved that 55.0 is the maximum total price that we can achieve._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** items = \[\[100,30\]\], capacity = 50_x000D_
**Output:** -1.00000_x000D_
**Explanation:** It is impossible to fill a bag with the given item._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= items.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `items[i].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= pricei, weighti <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= capacity <= 109`

title: Count Distinct Numbers on Board
content:
You are given a positive integer `n`, that is initially placed on a board. Every day, for `109` days, you perform the following procedure:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   For each number `x` present on the board, find all numbers `1 <= i <= n` such that `x % i == 1`._x000D_
*   Then, place those numbers on the board._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of **distinct** integers present on the board after_ `109` _days have elapsed_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Once a number is placed on the board, it will remain on it until the end._x000D_
*   `%` stands for the modulo operation. For example, `14 % 3` is `2`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 5_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** Initially, 5 is present on the board. _x000D_
The next day, 2 and 4 will be added since 5 % 2 == 1 and 5 % 4 == 1. _x000D_
After that day, 3 will be added to the board because 4 % 3 == 1. _x000D_
At the end of a billion days, the distinct numbers on the board will be 2, 3, 4, and 5. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
Since 3 % 2 == 1, 2 will be added to the board. _x000D_
After a billion days, the only two distinct numbers on the board are 2 and 3. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 100`

title: Count Collisions of Monkeys on a Polygon
content:
There is a regular convex polygon with `n` vertices. The vertices are labeled from `0` to `n - 1` in a clockwise direction, and each vertex has **exactly one monkey**. The following figure shows a convex polygon of `6` vertices._x000D_
_x000D_
Each monkey moves simultaneously to a neighboring vertex. A neighboring vertex for a vertex `i` can be:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   the vertex `(i + 1) % n` in the clockwise direction, or_x000D_
*   the vertex `(i - 1 + n) % n` in the counter-clockwise direction._x000D_
_x000D_
A **collision** happens if at least two monkeys reside on the same vertex after the movement or intersect on an edge._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of ways the monkeys can move so that at least **one collision**_ _happens_. Since the answer may be very large, return it modulo `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that each monkey can only move once._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 3_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 8 total possible movements._x000D_
Two ways such that they collide at some point are:_x000D_
- Monkey 1 moves in a clockwise direction; monkey 2 moves in an anticlockwise direction; monkey 3 moves in a clockwise direction. Monkeys 1 and 2 collide._x000D_
- Monkey 1 moves in an anticlockwise direction; monkey 2 moves in an anticlockwise direction; monkey 3 moves in a clockwise direction. Monkeys 1 and 3 collide._x000D_
It can be shown 6 total movements result in a collision._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 14_x000D_
**Explanation:** It can be shown that there are 14 ways for the monkeys to collide._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `3 <= n <= 109`

title: Put Marbles in Bags
content:
You have `k` bags. You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `weights` where `weights[i]` is the weight of the `ith` marble. You are also given the integer `k.`_x000D_
_x000D_
Divide the marbles into the `k` bags according to the following rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   No bag is empty._x000D_
*   If the `ith` marble and `jth` marble are in a bag, then all marbles with an index between the `ith` and `jth` indices should also be in that same bag._x000D_
*   If a bag consists of all the marbles with an index from `i` to `j` inclusively, then the cost of the bag is `weights[i] + weights[j]`._x000D_
_x000D_
The **score** after distributing the marbles is the sum of the costs of all the `k` bags._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **difference** between the **maximum** and **minimum** scores among marble distributions_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** weights = \[1,3,5,1\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
The distribution \[1\],\[3,5,1\] results in the minimal score of (1+1) + (3+1) = 6. _x000D_
The distribution \[1,3\],\[5,1\], results in the maximal score of (1+3) + (5+1) = 10. _x000D_
Thus, we return their difference 10 - 6 = 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** weights = \[1, 3\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** The only distribution possible is \[1\],\[3\]. _x000D_
Since both the maximal and minimal score are the same, we return 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= weights.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= weights[i] <= 109`

title: Count Increasing Quadruplets
content:
Given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums` of size `n` containing all numbers from `1` to `n`, return _the number of increasing quadruplets_._x000D_
_x000D_
A quadruplet `(i, j, k, l)` is increasing if:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= i < j < k < l < n`, and_x000D_
*   `nums[i] < nums[k] < nums[j] < nums[l]`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,3,2,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
- When i = 0, j = 1, k = 2, and l = 3, nums\[i\] < nums\[k\] < nums\[j\] < nums\[l\]._x000D_
- When i = 0, j = 1, k = 2, and l = 4, nums\[i\] < nums\[k\] < nums\[j\] < nums\[l\]. _x000D_
There are no other quadruplets, so we return 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,2,3,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** There exists only one quadruplet with i = 0, j = 1, k = 2, l = 3, but since nums\[j\] < nums\[k\], we return 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `4 <= nums.length <= 4000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= nums.length`_x000D_
*   All the integers of `nums` are **unique**. `nums` is a permutation.

title: Separate the Digits in an Array
content:
Given an array of positive integers `nums`, return _an array_ `answer` _that consists of the digits of each integer in_ `nums` _after separating them in **the same order** they appear in_ `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
To separate the digits of an integer is to get all the digits it has in the same order._x000D_
_x000D_
*   For example, for the integer `10921`, the separation of its digits is `[1,0,9,2,1]`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[13,25,83,77\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,3,2,5,8,3,7,7\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
- The separation of 13 is \[1,3\]._x000D_
- The separation of 25 is \[2,5\]._x000D_
- The separation of 83 is \[8,3\]._x000D_
- The separation of 77 is \[7,7\]._x000D_
answer = \[1,3,2,5,8,3,7,7\]. Note that answer contains the separations in the same order._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[7,1,3,9\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[7,1,3,9\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The separation of each integer in nums is itself._x000D_
answer = \[7,1,3,9\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 105`

title: Maximum Number of Integers to Choose From a Range I
content:
You are given an integer array `banned` and two integers `n` and `maxSum`. You are choosing some number of integers following the below rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The chosen integers have to be in the range `[1, n]`._x000D_
*   Each integer can be chosen **at most once**._x000D_
*   The chosen integers should not be in the array `banned`._x000D_
*   The sum of the chosen integers should not exceed `maxSum`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **maximum** number of integers you can choose following the mentioned rules_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** banned = \[1,6,5\], n = 5, maxSum = 6_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can choose the integers 2 and 4._x000D_
2 and 4 are from the range \[1, 5\], both did not appear in banned, and their sum is 6, which did not exceed maxSum._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** banned = \[1,2,3,4,5,6,7\], n = 8, maxSum = 1_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** You cannot choose any integer while following the mentioned conditions._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** banned = \[11\], n = 7, maxSum = 50_x000D_
**Output:** 7_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can choose the integers 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, and 7._x000D_
They are from the range \[1, 7\], all did not appear in banned, and their sum is 28, which did not exceed maxSum._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= banned.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= banned[i], n <= 104`_x000D_
*   `1 <= maxSum <= 109`

title: Maximize Win From Two Segments
content:
There are some prizes on the **X-axis**. You are given an integer array `prizePositions` that is **sorted in non-decreasing order**, where `prizePositions[i]` is the position of the `ith` prize. There could be different prizes at the same position on the line. You are also given an integer `k`._x000D_
_x000D_
You are allowed to select two segments with integer endpoints. The length of each segment must be `k`. You will collect all prizes whose position falls within at least one of the two selected segments (including the endpoints of the segments). The two selected segments may intersect._x000D_
_x000D_
*   For example if `k = 2`, you can choose segments `[1, 3]` and `[2, 4]`, and you will win any prize i that satisfies `1 <= prizePositions[i] <= 3` or `2 <= prizePositions[i] <= 4`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **maximum** number of prizes you can win if you choose the two segments optimally_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prizePositions = \[1,1,2,2,3,3,5\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 7_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this example, you can win all 7 prizes by selecting two segments \[1, 3\] and \[3, 5\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** prizePositions = \[1,2,3,4\], k = 0_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** For this example, **one choice** for the segments is `[3, 3]` and `[4, 4],` and you will be able to get `2` prizes. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= prizePositions.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= prizePositions[i] <= 109`_x000D_
*   `0 <= k <= 109`_x000D_
*   `prizePositions` is sorted in non-decreasing order._x000D_
_x000D_

title: Disconnect Path in a Binary Matrix by at Most One Flip
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** `m x n` **binary** matrix `grid`. You can move from a cell `(row, col)` to any of the cells `(row + 1, col)` or `(row, col + 1)` that has the value `1`. The matrix is **disconnected** if there is no path from `(0, 0)` to `(m - 1, n - 1)`._x000D_
_x000D_
You can flip the value of **at most one** (possibly none) cell. You **cannot flip** the cells `(0, 0)` and `(m - 1, n - 1)`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return `true` _if it is possible to make the matrix disconnect or_ `false` _otherwise_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that flipping a cell changes its value from `0` to `1` or from `1` to `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,1,1\],\[1,0,0\],\[1,1,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** true_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can change the cell shown in the diagram above. There is no path from (0, 0) to (2, 2) in the resulting grid._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[1,1,1\],\[1,0,1\],\[1,1,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** false_x000D_
**Explanation:** It is not possible to change at most one cell such that there is not path from (0, 0) to (2, 2)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == grid.length`_x000D_
*   `n == grid[i].length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m, n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m * n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `grid[i][j]` is either `0` or `1`._x000D_
*   `grid[0][0] == grid[m - 1][n - 1] == 1`

title: Maximum Number of Integers to Choose From a Range II
content:
You are given an integer array `banned` and two integers `n` and `maxSum`. You are choosing some number of integers following the below rules:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   The chosen integers have to be in the range `[1, n]`._x000D_
*   Each integer can be chosen **at most once**._x000D_
*   The chosen integers should not be in the array `banned`._x000D_
*   The sum of the chosen integers should not exceed `maxSum`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **maximum** number of integers you can choose following the mentioned rules_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** banned = \[1,4,6\], n = 6, maxSum = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can choose the integer 3._x000D_
3 is in the range \[1, 6\], and do not appear in banned. The sum of the chosen integers is 3, which does not exceed maxSum._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** banned = \[4,3,5,6\], n = 7, maxSum = 18_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** You can choose the integers 1, 2, and 7._x000D_
All these integers are in the range \[1, 7\], all do not appear in banned, and their sum is 18, which does not exceed maxSum._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= banned.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= banned[i] <= n <= 109`_x000D_
*   `1 <= maxSum <= 1015`

title: Take Gifts From the Richest Pile
content:
You are given an integer array `gifts` denoting the number of gifts in various piles. Every second, you do the following:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Choose the pile with the maximum number of gifts._x000D_
*   If there is more than one pile with the maximum number of gifts, choose any._x000D_
*   Leave behind the floor of the square root of the number of gifts in the pile. Take the rest of the gifts._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of gifts remaining after_ `k` _seconds.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** gifts = \[25,64,9,4,100\], k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 29_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
The gifts are taken in the following way:_x000D_
- In the first second, the last pile is chosen and 10 gifts are left behind._x000D_
- Then the second pile is chosen and 8 gifts are left behind._x000D_
- After that the first pile is chosen and 5 gifts are left behind._x000D_
- Finally, the last pile is chosen again and 3 gifts are left behind._x000D_
The final remaining gifts are \[5,8,9,4,3\], so the total number of gifts remaining is 29._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** gifts = \[1,1,1,1\], k = 4_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
In this case, regardless which pile you choose, you have to leave behind 1 gift in each pile. _x000D_
That is, you can't take any pile with you. _x000D_
So, the total gifts remaining are 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= gifts.length <= 103`_x000D_
*   `1 <= gifts[i] <= 109`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= 103`

title: Count Vowel Strings in Ranges
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** array of strings `words` and a 2D array of integers `queries`._x000D_
_x000D_
Each query `queries[i] = [li, ri]` asks us to find the number of strings present in the range `li` to `ri` (both **inclusive**) of `words` that start and end with a vowel._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _an array_ `ans` _of size_ `queries.length`_, where_ `ans[i]` _is the answer to the_ `i`th _query_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Note** that the vowel letters are `'a'`, `'e'`, `'i'`, `'o'`, and `'u'`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** words = \[ "aba ", "bcb ", "ece ", "aa ", "e "\], queries = \[\[0,2\],\[1,4\],\[1,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[2,3,0\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The strings starting and ending with a vowel are  "aba ",  "ece ",  "aa " and  "e "._x000D_
The answer to the query \[0,2\] is 2 (strings  "aba " and  "ece ")._x000D_
to query \[1,4\] is 3 (strings  "ece ",  "aa ",  "e ")._x000D_
to query \[1,1\] is 0._x000D_
We return \[2,3,0\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** words = \[ "a ", "e ", "i "\], queries = \[\[0,2\],\[0,1\],\[2,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3,2,1\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** Every string satisfies the conditions, so we return \[3,2,1\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= words.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= words[i].length <= 40`_x000D_
*   `words[i]` consists only of lowercase English letters._x000D_
*   `sum(words[i].length) <= 3 * 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= queries.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= li <= ri < words.length`

title: House Robber IV
content:
There are several consecutive houses along a street, each of which has some money inside. There is also a robber, who wants to steal money from the homes, but he **refuses to steal from adjacent homes**._x000D_
_x000D_
The **capability** of the robber is the maximum amount of money he steals from one house of all the houses he robbed._x000D_
_x000D_
You are given an integer array `nums` representing how much money is stashed in each house. More formally, the `ith` house from the left has `nums[i]` dollars._x000D_
_x000D_
You are also given an integer `k`, representing the **minimum** number of houses the robber will steal from. It is always possible to steal at least `k` houses._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimum** capability of the robber out of all the possible ways to steal at least_ `k` _houses_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,3,5,9\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 5_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
There are three ways to rob at least 2 houses:_x000D_
- Rob the houses at indices 0 and 2. Capability is max(nums\[0\], nums\[2\]) = 5._x000D_
- Rob the houses at indices 0 and 3. Capability is max(nums\[0\], nums\[3\]) = 9._x000D_
- Rob the houses at indices 1 and 3. Capability is max(nums\[1\], nums\[3\]) = 9._x000D_
Therefore, we return min(5, 9, 9) = 5._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,7,9,3,1\], k = 2_x000D_
**Output:** 2_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 7 ways to rob the houses. The way which leads to minimum capability is to rob the house at index 0 and 4. Return max(nums\[0\], nums\[4\]) = 2._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 109`_x000D_
*   `1 <= k <= (nums.length + 1)/2`

title: Rearranging Fruits
content:
You have two fruit baskets containing `n` fruits each. You are given two **0-indexed** integer arrays `basket1` and `basket2` representing the cost of fruit in each basket. You want to make both baskets **equal**. To do so, you can use the following operation as many times as you want:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Chose two indices `i` and `j`, and swap the `ith` fruit of `basket1` with the `jth` fruit of `basket2`._x000D_
*   The cost of the swap is `min(basket1[i],basket2[j])`._x000D_
_x000D_
Two baskets are considered equal if sorting them according to the fruit cost makes them exactly the same baskets._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the minimum cost to make both the baskets equal or_ `-1` _if impossible.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** basket1 = \[4,2,2,2\], basket2 = \[1,4,1,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** Swap index 1 of basket1 with index 0 of basket2, which has cost 1. Now basket1 = \[4,1,2,2\] and basket2 = \[2,4,1,2\]. Rearranging both the arrays makes them equal._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** basket1 = \[2,3,4,1\], basket2 = \[3,2,5,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** It can be shown that it is impossible to make both the baskets equal._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `basket1.length == bakste2.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= basket1.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= basket1[i],basket2[i] <= 109`

title: Find the Array Concatenation Value
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
The **concatenation** of two numbers is the number formed by concatenating their numerals._x000D_
_x000D_
*   For example, the concatenation of `15`, `49` is `1549`._x000D_
_x000D_
The **concatenation value** of `nums` is initially equal to `0`. Perform this operation until `nums` becomes empty:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   If there exists more than one number in `nums`, pick the first element and last element in `nums` respectively and add the value of their concatenation to the **concatenation value** of `nums`, then delete the first and last element from `nums`._x000D_
*   If one element exists, add its value to the **concatenation value** of `nums`, then delete it._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the concatenation value of the `nums`_._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[7,52,2,4\]_x000D_
**Output:** 596_x000D_
**Explanation:** Before performing any operation, nums is \[7,52,2,4\] and concatenation value is 0._x000D_
 - In the first operation:_x000D_
We pick the first element, 7, and the last element, 4._x000D_
Their concatenation is 74, and we add it to the concatenation value, so it becomes equal to 74._x000D_
Then we delete them from nums, so nums becomes equal to \[52,2\]._x000D_
 - In the second operation:_x000D_
We pick the first element, 52, and the last element, 2._x000D_
Their concatenation is 522, and we add it to the concatenation value, so it becomes equal to 596._x000D_
Then we delete them from the nums, so nums becomes empty._x000D_
Since the concatenation value is 596 so the answer is 596._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[5,14,13,8,12\]_x000D_
**Output:** 673_x000D_
**Explanation:** Before performing any operation, nums is \[5,14,13,8,12\] and concatenation value is 0._x000D_
 - In the first operation:_x000D_
We pick the first element, 5, and the last element, 12._x000D_
Their concatenation is 512, and we add it to the concatenation value, so it becomes equal to 512._x000D_
Then we delete them from the nums, so nums becomes equal to \[14,13,8\]._x000D_
 - In the second operation:_x000D_
We pick the first element, 14, and the last element, 8._x000D_
Their concatenation is 148, and we add it to the concatenation value, so it becomes equal to 660._x000D_
Then we delete them from the nums, so nums becomes equal to \[13\]._x000D_
 - In the third operation:_x000D_
nums has only one element, so we pick 13 and add it to the concatenation value, so it becomes equal to 673._x000D_
Then we delete it from nums, so nums become empty._x000D_
Since the concatenation value is 673 so the answer is 673._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 104`_x000D_
_x000D_

title: Count the Number of Fair Pairs
content:
Given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums` of size `n` and two integers `lower` and `upper`, return _the number of fair pairs_._x000D_
_x000D_
A pair `(i, j)` is **fair** if:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `0 <= i < j < n`, and_x000D_
*   `lower <= nums[i] + nums[j] <= upper`_x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[0,1,7,4,4,5\], lower = 3, upper = 6_x000D_
**Output:** 6_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 6 fair pairs: (0,3), (0,4), (0,5), (1,3), (1,4), and (1,5)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,7,9,2,5\], lower = 11, upper = 11_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is a single fair pair: (2,3)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `nums.length == n`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= nums[i] <= 109`_x000D_
*   `-109 <= lower <= upper <= 109`

title: Substring XOR Queries
content:
You are given a **binary string** `s`, and a **2D** integer array `queries` where `queries[i] = [firsti, secondi]`._x000D_
_x000D_
For the `ith` query, find the **shortest substring** of `s` whose **decimal value**, `val`, yields `secondi` when **bitwise XORed** with `firsti`. In other words, `val ^ firsti == secondi`._x000D_
_x000D_
The answer to the `ith` query is the endpoints (**0-indexed**) of the substring `[lefti, righti]` or `[-1, -1]` if no such substring exists. If there are multiple answers, choose the one with the **minimum** `lefti`._x000D_
_x000D_
_Return an array_ `ans` _where_ `ans[i] = [lefti, righti]` _is the answer to the_ `ith` _query.__x000D_
_x000D_
A **substring** is a contiguous non-empty sequence of characters within a string._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "101101 ", queries = \[\[0,5\],\[1,2\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[0,2\],\[2,3\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** For the first query the substring in range `[0,2]` is ** "101 "** which has a decimal value of **`5`**, and **`5 ^ 0 = 5`**, hence the answer to the first query is `[0,2]`. In the second query, the substring in range `[2,3]` is ** "11 ",** and has a decimal value of **3**, and **3 `^ 1 = 2`**. So, `[2,3]` is returned for the second query. _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "0101 ", queries = \[\[12,8\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[-1,-1\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this example there is no substring that answers the query, hence `[-1,-1] is returned`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "1 ", queries = \[\[4,5\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[0,0\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** For this example, the substring in range `[0,0]` has a decimal value of **`1`**, and **`1 ^ 4 = 5`**. So, the answer is `[0,0]`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length <= 104`_x000D_
*   `s[i]` is either `'0'` or `'1'`._x000D_
*   `1 <= queries.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= firsti, secondi <= 109`

title: Subsequence With the Minimum Score
content:
You are given two strings `s` and `t`._x000D_
_x000D_
You are allowed to remove any number of characters from the string `t`._x000D_
_x000D_
The score of the string is `0` if no characters are removed from the string `t`, otherwise:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Let `left` be the minimum index among all removed characters._x000D_
*   Let `right` be the maximum index among all removed characters._x000D_
_x000D_
Then the score of the string is `right - left + 1`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the minimum possible score to make_ `t` _a subsequence of_ `s`_.__x000D_
_x000D_
A **subsequence** of a string is a new string that is formed from the original string by deleting some (can be none) of the characters without disturbing the relative positions of the remaining characters. (i.e., `"ace "` is a subsequence of `"abcde "` while `"aec "` is not)._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "abacaba ", t =  "bzaa "_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this example, we remove the character  "z " at index 1 (0-indexed)._x000D_
The string t becomes  "baa " which is a subsequence of the string  "abacaba " and the score is 1 - 1 + 1 = 1._x000D_
It can be proven that 1 is the minimum score that we can achieve._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** s =  "cde ", t =  "xyz "_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** In this example, we remove characters  "x ",  "y " and  "z " at indices 0, 1, and 2 (0-indexed)._x000D_
The string t becomes  " " which is a subsequence of the string  "cde " and the score is 2 - 0 + 1 = 3._x000D_
It can be proven that 3 is the minimum score that we can achieve._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= s.length, t.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `s` and `t` consist of only lowercase English letters.

title: Maximum Difference by Remapping a Digit
content:
You are given an integer `num`. You know that Danny Mittal will sneakily **remap** one of the `10` possible digits (`0` to `9`) to another digit._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the difference between the maximum and minimum_ _values Danny can make by remapping **exactly** **one** digit_ _in_ `num`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Notes:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   When Danny remaps a digit d1 to another digit d2, Danny replaces all occurrences of `d1` in `num` with `d2`._x000D_
*   Danny can remap a digit to itself, in which case `num` does not change._x000D_
*   Danny can remap different digits for obtaining minimum and maximum values respectively._x000D_
*   The resulting number after remapping can contain leading zeroes._x000D_
*   We mentioned "Danny Mittal " to congratulate him on being in the top 10 in Weekly Contest 326._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** num = 11891_x000D_
**Output:** 99009_x000D_
**Explanation:** _x000D_
To achieve the maximum value, Danny can remap the digit 1 to the digit 9 to yield 99899._x000D_
To achieve the minimum value, Danny can remap the digit 1 to the digit 0, yielding 890._x000D_
The difference between these two numbers is 99009._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** num = 90_x000D_
**Output:** 99_x000D_
**Explanation:**_x000D_
The maximum value that can be returned by the function is 99 (if 0 is replaced by 9) and the minimum value that can be returned by the function is 0 (if 9 is replaced by 0)._x000D_
Thus, we return 99._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= num <= 108`

title: Minimum Score by Changing Two Elements
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
*   The **low** score of `nums` is the minimum value of `|nums[i] - nums[j]|` over all `0 <= i < j < nums.length`._x000D_
*   The **high** score of `nums` is the maximum value of `|nums[i] - nums[j]|` over all `0 <= i < j < nums.length`._x000D_
*   The **score** of `nums` is the sum of the **high** and **low** scores of nums._x000D_
_x000D_
To minimize the score of `nums`, we can change the value of **at most two** elements of `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimum** possible **score** after changing the value of **at most two** elements o_f `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
Note that `|x|` denotes the absolute value of `x`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,4,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** 0_x000D_
**Explanation:** Change value of nums\[1\] and nums\[2\] to 1 so that nums becomes \[1,1,1\]. Now, the value of `|nums[i] - nums[j]|` is always equal to 0, so we return 0 + 0 = 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1,4,7,8,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** Change nums\[0\] and nums\[1\] to be 6. Now nums becomes \[6,6,7,8,5\]._x000D_
Our low score is achieved when i = 0 and j = 1, in which case |`nums[i] - nums[j]`| = |6 - 6| = 0._x000D_
Our high score is achieved when i = 3 and j = 4, in which case |`nums[i] - nums[j]`| = |8 - 5| = 3._x000D_
The sum of our high and low score is 3, which we can prove to be minimal._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `3 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 109`

title: Minimum Impossible OR
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
We say that an integer x is **expressible** from `nums` if there exist some integers `0 <= index1 < index2 < ... < indexk < nums.length` for which `nums[index1] | nums[index2] | ... | nums[indexk] = x`. In other words, an integer is expressible if it can be written as the bitwise OR of some subsequence of `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the minimum **positive non-zero integer** that is not_ _expressible from_ `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[2,1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 4_x000D_
**Explanation:** 1 and 2 are already present in the array. We know that 3 is expressible, since nums\[0\] | nums\[1\] = 2 | 1 = 3. Since 4 is not expressible, we return 4._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[5,3,2\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can show that 1 is the smallest number that is not expressible._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 109`

title: Handling Sum Queries After Update
content:
You are given two **0-indexed** arrays `nums1` and `nums2` and a 2D array `queries` of queries. There are three types of queries:_x000D_
_x000D_
1.  For a query of type 1, `queries[i] = [1, l, r]`. Flip the values from `0` to `1` and from `1` to `0` in `nums1` from index `l` to index `r`. Both `l` and `r` are **0-indexed**._x000D_
2.  For a query of type 2, `queries[i] = [2, p, 0]`. For every index `0 <= i < n`, set `nums2[i] = nums2[i] + nums1[i] * p`._x000D_
3.  For a query of type 3, `queries[i] = [3, 0, 0]`. Find the sum of the elements in `nums2`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _an array containing all the answers to the third type queries.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[1,0,1\], nums2 = \[0,0,0\], queries = \[\[1,1,1\],\[2,1,0\],\[3,0,0\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[3\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** After the first query nums1 becomes \[1,1,1\]. After the second query, nums2 becomes \[1,1,1\], so the answer to the third query is 3. Thus, \[3\] is returned._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[1\], nums2 = \[5\], queries = \[\[2,0,0\],\[3,0,0\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[5\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** After the first query, nums2 remains \[5\], so the answer to the second query is 5. Thus, \[5\] is returned._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums1.length,nums2.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `nums1.length = nums2.length`_x000D_
*   `1 <= queries.length <= 105`_x000D_
*   `queries[i].length = 3`_x000D_
*   `0 <= l <= r <= nums1.length - 1`_x000D_
*   `0 <= p <= 106`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums1[i] <= 1`_x000D_
*   `0 <= nums2[i] <= 109`

title: Merge Two 2D Arrays by Summing Values
content:
You are given two **2D** integer arrays `nums1` and `nums2.`_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `nums1[i] = [idi, vali]` indicate that the number with the id `idi` has a value equal to `vali`._x000D_
*   `nums2[i] = [idi, vali]` indicate that the number with the id `idi` has a value equal to `vali`._x000D_
_x000D_
Each array contains **unique** ids and is sorted in **ascending** order by id._x000D_
_x000D_
Merge the two arrays into one array that is sorted in ascending order by id, respecting the following conditions:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Only ids that appear in at least one of the two arrays should be included in the resulting array._x000D_
*   Each id should be included **only once** and its value should be the sum of the values of this id in the two arrays. If the id does not exist in one of the two arrays then its value in that array is considered to be `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the resulting array_. The returned array must be sorted in ascending order by id._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[\[1,2\],\[2,3\],\[4,5\]\], nums2 = \[\[1,4\],\[3,2\],\[4,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1,6\],\[2,3\],\[3,2\],\[4,6\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The resulting array contains the following:_x000D_
- id = 1, the value of this id is 2 + 4 = 6._x000D_
- id = 2, the value of this id is 3._x000D_
- id = 3, the value of this id is 2._x000D_
- id = 4, the value of this id is 5 + 1 = 6._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums1 = \[\[2,4\],\[3,6\],\[5,5\]\], nums2 = \[\[1,3\],\[4,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[\[1,3\],\[2,4\],\[3,6\],\[4,3\],\[5,5\]\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are no common ids, so we just include each id with its value in the resulting list._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums1.length, nums2.length <= 200`_x000D_
*   `nums1[i].length == nums2[j].length == 2`_x000D_
*   `1 <= idi, vali <= 1000`_x000D_
*   Both arrays contain unique ids._x000D_
*   Both arrays are in strictly ascending order by id.

title: Minimum Operations to Reduce an Integer to 0
content:
You are given a positive integer `n`, you can do the following operation **any** number of times:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   Add or subtract a **power** of `2` from `n`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimum** number of operations to make_ `n` _equal to_ `0`._x000D_
_x000D_
A number `x` is power of `2` if `x == 2i` where `i >= 0`_.__x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 39_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can do the following operations:_x000D_
- Add 20 = 1 to n, so now n = 40._x000D_
- Subtract 23 = 8 from n, so now n = 32._x000D_
- Subtract 25 = 32 from n, so now n = 0._x000D_
It can be shown that 3 is the minimum number of operations we need to make n equal to 0._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** n = 54_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** We can do the following operations:_x000D_
- Add 21 = 2 to n, so now n = 56._x000D_
- Add 23 = 8 to n, so now n = 64._x000D_
- Subtract 26 = 64 from n, so now n = 0._x000D_
So the minimum number of operations is 3._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 105`

title: Count the Number of Square-Free Subsets
content:
You are given a positive integer **0-indexed** array `nums`._x000D_
_x000D_
A subset of the array `nums` is **square-free** if the product of its elements is a **square-free integer**._x000D_
_x000D_
A **square-free integer** is an integer that is divisible by no square number other than `1`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the number of square-free non-empty subsets of the array_ **nums**. Since the answer may be too large, return it **modulo** `109 + 7`._x000D_
_x000D_
A **non-empty** **subset** of `nums` is an array that can be obtained by deleting some (possibly none but not all) elements from `nums`. Two subsets are different if and only if the chosen indices to delete are different._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[3,4,4,5\]_x000D_
**Output:** 3_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are 3 square-free subsets in this example:_x000D_
- The subset consisting of the 0th element \[3\]. The product of its elements is 3, which is a square-free integer._x000D_
- The subset consisting of the 3rd element \[5\]. The product of its elements is 5, which is a square-free integer._x000D_
- The subset consisting of 0th and 3rd elements \[3,5\]. The product of its elements is 15, which is a square-free integer._x000D_
It can be proven that there are no more than 3 square-free subsets in the given array._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** 1_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is 1 square-free subset in this example:_x000D_
- The subset consisting of the 0th element \[1\]. The product of its elements is 1, which is a square-free integer._x000D_
It can be proven that there is no more than 1 square-free subset in the given array._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 30`

title: Find the String with LCP
content:
We define the `lcp` matrix of any **0-indexed** string `word` of `n` lowercase English letters as an `n x n` grid such that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `lcp[i][j]` is equal to the length of the **longest common prefix** between the substrings `word[i,n-1]` and `word[j,n-1]`._x000D_
_x000D_
Given an `n x n` matrix `lcp`, return the alphabetically smallest string `word` that corresponds to `lcp`. If there is no such string, return an empty string._x000D_
_x000D_
A string `a` is lexicographically smaller than a string `b` (of the same length) if in the first position where `a` and `b` differ, string `a` has a letter that appears earlier in the alphabet than the corresponding letter in `b`. For example, `"aabd "` is lexicographically smaller than `"aaca "` because the first position they differ is at the third letter, and `'b'` comes before `'c'`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** lcp = \[\[4,0,2,0\],\[0,3,0,1\],\[2,0,2,0\],\[0,1,0,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "abab "_x000D_
**Explanation:** lcp corresponds to any 4 letter string with two alternating letters. The lexicographically smallest of them is  "abab "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** lcp = \[\[4,3,2,1\],\[3,3,2,1\],\[2,2,2,1\],\[1,1,1,1\]\]_x000D_
**Output:**  "aaaa "_x000D_
**Explanation:** lcp corresponds to any 4 letter string with a single distinct letter. The lexicographically smallest of them is  "aaaa ". _x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 3:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** lcp = \[\[4,3,2,1\],\[3,3,2,1\],\[2,2,2,1\],\[1,1,1,3\]\]_x000D_
**Output:**  " "_x000D_
**Explanation:** lcp\[3\]\[3\] cannot be equal to 3 since word\[3,...,3\] consists of only a single letter; Thus, no answer exists._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n ==` `lcp.length ==` `lcp[i].length` `<= 1000`_x000D_
*   `0 <= lcp[i][j] <= n`

title: Left and Right Sum Differences
content:
Given a **0-indexed** integer array `nums`, find a **0-indexed** integer array `answer` where:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `answer.length == nums.length`._x000D_
*   `answer[i] = |leftSum[i] - rightSum[i]|`._x000D_
_x000D_
Where:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `leftSum[i]` is the sum of elements to the left of the index `i` in the array `nums`. If there is no such element, `leftSum[i] = 0`._x000D_
*   `rightSum[i]` is the sum of elements to the right of the index `i` in the array `nums`. If there is no such element, `rightSum[i] = 0`._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the array_ `answer`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[10,4,8,3\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[15,1,11,22\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The array leftSum is \[0,10,14,22\] and the array rightSum is \[15,11,3,0\]._x000D_
The array answer is \[|0 - 15|,|10 - 11|,|14 - 3|,|22 - 0|\] = \[15,1,11,22\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** nums = \[1\]_x000D_
**Output:** \[0\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** The array leftSum is \[0\] and the array rightSum is \[0\]._x000D_
The array answer is \[|0 - 0|\] = \[0\]._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums.length <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `1 <= nums[i] <= 105`

title: Find the Divisibility Array of a String
content:
You are given a **0-indexed** string `word` of length `n` consisting of digits, and a positive integer `m`._x000D_
_x000D_
The **divisibility array** `div` of `word` is an integer array of length `n` such that:_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `div[i] = 1` if the **numeric value** of `word[0,...,i]` is divisible by `m`, or_x000D_
*   `div[i] = 0` otherwise._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the divisibility array of_ `word`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** word =  "998244353 ", m = 3_x000D_
**Output:** \[1,1,0,0,0,1,1,0,0\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are only 4 prefixes that are divisible by 3:  "9 ",  "99 ",  "998244 ", and  "9982443 "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** word =  "1010 ", m = 10_x000D_
**Output:** \[0,1,0,1\]_x000D_
**Explanation:** There are only 2 prefixes that are divisible by 10:  "10 ", and  "1010 "._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `1 <= n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `word.length == n`_x000D_
*   `word` consists of digits from `0` to `9`_x000D_
*   `1 <= m <= 109`

title: Minimum Time to Visit a Cell In a Grid
content:
You are given a `m x n` matrix `grid` consisting of **non-negative** integers where `grid[row][col]` represents the **minimum** time required to be able to visit the cell `(row, col)`, which means you can visit the cell `(row, col)` only when the time you visit it is greater than or equal to `grid[row][col]`._x000D_
_x000D_
You are standing in the **top-left** cell of the matrix in the `0th` second, and you must move to **any** adjacent cell in the four directions: up, down, left, and right. Each move you make takes 1 second._x000D_
_x000D_
Return _the **minimum** time required in which you can visit the bottom-right cell of the matrix_. If you cannot visit the bottom-right cell, then return `-1`._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 1:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[0,1,3,2\],\[5,1,2,5\],\[4,3,8,6\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** 7_x000D_
**Explanation:** One of the paths that we can take is the following:_x000D_
- at t = 0, we are on the cell (0,0)._x000D_
- at t = 1, we move to the cell (0,1). It is possible because grid\[0\]\[1\] <= 1._x000D_
- at t = 2, we move to the cell (1,1). It is possible because grid\[1\]\[1\] <= 2._x000D_
- at t = 3, we move to the cell (1,2). It is possible because grid\[1\]\[2\] <= 3._x000D_
- at t = 4, we move to the cell (1,1). It is possible because grid\[1\]\[1\] <= 4._x000D_
- at t = 5, we move to the cell (1,2). It is possible because grid\[1\]\[2\] <= 5._x000D_
- at t = 6, we move to the cell (1,3). It is possible because grid\[1\]\[3\] <= 6._x000D_
- at t = 7, we move to the cell (2,3). It is possible because grid\[2\]\[3\] <= 7._x000D_
The final time is 7. It can be shown that it is the minimum time possible._x000D_
_x000D_
**Example 2:**_x000D_
_x000D_
**Input:** grid = \[\[0,2,4\],\[3,2,1\],\[1,0,4\]\]_x000D_
**Output:** -1_x000D_
**Explanation:** There is no path from the top left to the bottom-right cell._x000D_
_x000D_
**Constraints:**_x000D_
_x000D_
*   `m == grid.length`_x000D_
*   `n == grid[i].length`_x000D_
*   `2 <= m, n <= 1000`_x000D_
*   `4 <= m * n <= 105`_x000D_
*   `0 <= grid[i][j] <= 105`_x000D_
*   `grid[0][0] == 0`_x000D_
_x000D_
